1
00:01:51,722 --> 00:01:55,563
[SPEAKER_05]: Medford City Council Committee of the Whole, June 2nd, 2026 is called to order.

2
00:01:55,603 --> 00:01:56,604
[SPEAKER_05]: Mr. Clerk, please call the roll.

3
00:01:59,825 --> 00:02:00,545
[SPEAKER_02]: Councilor Kellyanne?

4
00:02:02,546 --> 00:02:02,746
[SPEAKER_02]: Present.

5
00:02:02,766 --> 00:02:03,366
[SPEAKER_02]: Councilor Lemming?

6
00:02:04,126 --> 00:02:04,607
[SPEAKER_02]: Present.

7
00:02:06,447 --> 00:02:07,067
[SPEAKER_02]: Councilor Mullane?

8
00:02:07,087 --> 00:02:07,608
Present.

9
00:02:08,688 --> 00:02:09,648
[SPEAKER_02]: Councilor Scott Pelley?

10
00:02:10,309 --> 00:02:10,689
[SPEAKER_02]: Present.

11
00:02:12,289 --> 00:02:12,929
[SPEAKER_02]: Councilor Singh?

12
00:02:12,949 --> 00:02:15,730
[SPEAKER_02]: Present.

13
00:02:15,750 --> 00:02:19,552
[SPEAKER_02]: Vice President Lazaro is absent at the moment.

14
00:02:20,658 --> 00:02:21,479
[SPEAKER_02]: And President Beers.

15
00:02:21,719 --> 00:02:22,059
[SPEAKER_05]: Present.

16
00:02:22,100 --> 00:02:22,980
[SPEAKER_05]: Six present, one absent.

17
00:02:23,000 --> 00:02:24,061
[SPEAKER_05]: The meeting is called to order.

18
00:02:24,602 --> 00:02:27,525
[SPEAKER_05]: Vice President Lazaro will be joining us a little late.

19
00:02:29,981 --> 00:02:37,307
[SPEAKER_05]: Action discussion items paper 26061 offered by President Baird's annual budget process for fiscal year 27 preliminary budget meeting number seven.

20
00:02:37,547 --> 00:02:40,990
[SPEAKER_05]: This will be the seventh preliminary budget meeting of the fiscal 27 budget process.

21
00:02:41,070 --> 00:02:45,214
[SPEAKER_05]: The mayor is planning to attend the meeting and she is present and will give a presentation.

22
00:02:45,394 --> 00:02:58,045
[SPEAKER_05]: The mayor has also communicated that the following departments will be present, parking, police, including traffic supervisors and traffic commission, Medford public schools, department of public works, general fund, cemetery, engineering, forestry, highway and parks,

23
00:02:58,545 --> 00:03:01,507
[SPEAKER_05]: and the Department of Public Works Enterprise Fund Water and Sewer.

24
00:03:02,808 --> 00:03:07,792
[SPEAKER_05]: Is there anything from members of the council before we turn it over to the mayor for her presentation?

25
00:03:11,095 --> 00:03:15,198
[SPEAKER_05]: Seeing none, Madam Mayor, welcome.

26
00:03:15,852 --> 00:03:16,132
[SPEAKER_16]: Thank you.

27
00:03:16,252 --> 00:03:22,073
[SPEAKER_16]: Thank you President Behrs and councillors for allowing me some time to speak to you about the fiscal year 27 budget.

28
00:03:23,013 --> 00:03:29,715
[SPEAKER_16]: First off, the general fund operating expenses are a total of $218,238,427.50, and our water and sewer enterprise operating expenses are $30,030,904.68.

29
00:03:44,371 --> 00:03:50,716
[SPEAKER_16]: Before I begin, I wanted to take the opportunity to thank everyone who contributed to completing this budget.

30
00:03:51,156 --> 00:03:55,859
[SPEAKER_16]: Thank you for allowing us a slight extension for delivering the budget books as well.

31
00:03:57,660 --> 00:04:08,568
[SPEAKER_16]: Compiling this comprehensive breakdown of the city's financial outlook took countless of hours of preparation, debate, and insight from our department heads and our budget team, led by Finance Director Bob Dickinson.

32
00:04:09,230 --> 00:04:19,618
[SPEAKER_16]: Our former assistant finance director and budget director, Filiana Lima, and my team in the mayor's office, led by Chief of Staff Nina Nazarian, who has been at your meetings.

33
00:04:20,840 --> 00:04:32,768
[SPEAKER_16]: I also need to credit our communications director, Steve Smerdi, and communications specialist, Emma Tumbley, for putting in so many hours of work on the granular aspects of the budget book that often go unnoticed.

34
00:04:33,548 --> 00:04:47,878
[SPEAKER_16]: The work of this team is invaluable and will hopefully lead us to a fourth Distinguished Budget Award from the Government Finance Officers Association, after having received back-to-back awards recently, a recognition we all are extremely proud of.

35
00:04:49,786 --> 00:05:04,630
[SPEAKER_16]: The city's on a cusp of a generational transformation, both in terms of its development and infrastructure strategy, as well as its broader educational future with the plans for a new state-of-the-art high school building, partially funded by the Massachusetts School Building Authority.

36
00:05:05,670 --> 00:05:16,913
[SPEAKER_16]: Being in a position to navigate such impressive changes, along with the council's help, has required not only sound fiscal management, also a willingness to make difficult fiscal decisions

37
00:05:17,490 --> 00:05:24,031
[SPEAKER_16]: that may not be universally popular, yet, in my opinion, necessary to sustain a collaborative success.

38
00:05:25,251 --> 00:05:37,334
[SPEAKER_16]: This reflects a pragmatic approach to equitable budgeting and an understanding that overleveraging taxpayers, especially those on a fixed income or those struggling to pay rent, is not a long-term solution.

39
00:05:38,974 --> 00:05:45,015
[SPEAKER_16]: This fiscal year brings a number of fiscal challenges, rising fixed costs, particularly in health insurance,

40
00:05:45,587 --> 00:05:53,051
[SPEAKER_16]: pensions, school transportation, special ed services, and debt payments continue to place pressure on our operating budget.

41
00:05:54,252 --> 00:06:03,957
[SPEAKER_16]: This year we are facing a significant increase in health insurance costs, once again, for the third year in a row, alongside the full implementation of recently settled collective bargaining agreements.

42
00:06:04,778 --> 00:06:09,120
[SPEAKER_16]: The great news is, however, that no current CBAs are out of contract.

43
00:06:10,463 --> 00:06:22,246
[SPEAKER_16]: At the same time, we remain cognizant of the financial impact on taxpayers and are committed to maintaining a sustainable financial path without an over-reliance on one-time revenue sources or short-term solutions.

44
00:06:23,927 --> 00:06:29,471
[SPEAKER_16]: The Medford High School building project is currently in the feasibility study phase of the MSBA process.

45
00:06:29,632 --> 00:06:34,475
[SPEAKER_16]: And over the past year and a half, we've hired a OPM and the architect for the project.

46
00:06:35,216 --> 00:06:46,925
[SPEAKER_16]: Alongside our school building committee, school committee, and school administration, the project team has worked hard on developing the educational vision for the new building that will guide our educational priorities for years to come.

47
00:06:47,966 --> 00:06:52,349
[SPEAKER_16]: There is still much due diligence, discussion, and compromise on the horizon for this project.

48
00:06:53,505 --> 00:06:54,445
[SPEAKER_16]: but we will get it done.

49
00:06:55,286 --> 00:07:06,889
[SPEAKER_16]: We need to continue to work collaboratively with the MSBA, our internal team, and external stakeholders to ensure that the space identified in the project is conducive to our educational goals without inflating the price.

50
00:07:07,630 --> 00:07:15,212
[SPEAKER_16]: Publicist support is critical for this project to ultimately get built, so we cannot have an associated price tag that our community can't afford.

51
00:07:16,942 --> 00:07:26,269
[SPEAKER_16]: I want to highlight some of the accomplishments of the city, city council included in these goals, priorities, and initiatives, I'm sure.

52
00:07:27,050 --> 00:07:28,651
[SPEAKER_16]: We, voters approved the new charter.

53
00:07:29,091 --> 00:07:34,976
[SPEAKER_16]: We also restarted the process to update the city zoning on a more deliberate schedule with more community and staff input.

54
00:07:35,756 --> 00:07:42,261
[SPEAKER_16]: We added two assistant city engineers along with key project management administrative staff to the engineering division.

55
00:07:45,200 --> 00:07:50,484
[SPEAKER_16]: and 50 linear feet of roadway reconstruction and 11,000 linear feet of sidewalk reconstruction.

56
00:07:51,305 --> 00:07:58,831
[SPEAKER_16]: We replaced 7,700 feet of water main and 4,600 feet of sewer main were rehabilitated.

57
00:07:59,972 --> 00:08:06,918
[SPEAKER_16]: We identified and addressed 857 unknown and lead service lines through the lead service line program.

58
00:08:07,958 --> 00:08:13,683
[SPEAKER_16]: We completed the Medford economic assessment study which examines the city's current economic landscape

59
00:08:14,627 --> 00:08:26,067
[SPEAKER_16]: Started work on over 2.4 million in park renovations projects this construction season, including but not limited to Logan Park, Riverside Plaza, and wrapping up car park phase two.

60
00:08:27,387 --> 00:08:41,570
[SPEAKER_16]: executed a contract with development company Transom Real Estate for the project to transform three underdeveloped city-owned lots in Medford Square, with the focal point being public art, a community grocery store, and so much more.

61
00:08:42,430 --> 00:08:52,792
[SPEAKER_16]: When completed, the Transom project will realize a significant increase in the city's estimated net growth figures, which increases the commercial tax base and hopefully easing reliance on residential taxes.

62
00:08:53,602 --> 00:09:01,087
[SPEAKER_16]: This is an overall transformative economic development for the square and the community as a whole, and I want to thank the council for helping rezone those parcels.

63
00:09:02,649 --> 00:09:09,113
[SPEAKER_16]: Planted 163 new trees, removed 85 tree stumps, and performed 148 prunings.

64
00:09:09,854 --> 00:09:18,080
[SPEAKER_16]: Completed a wayfinding master plan which will improve navigation across the city, highlight local attractions, and bolster economic development opportunities.

65
00:09:19,598 --> 00:09:35,625
[SPEAKER_16]: Another example of strategic economic development in the community includes parcels reclaimed from the Mystic Valley Development Corporation, which produced over $1 million in funding generated from new growth, allowing the city to pay for part of the transition to a new financial software.

66
00:09:36,532 --> 00:09:50,504
[SPEAKER_16]: This accomplishment was not an easy one, took quite a bit of time, but was achieved through considerable pressure and negotiations from myself with much credit given to the assessor's office for their data support that aided in that successful process.

67
00:09:51,504 --> 00:10:00,492
[SPEAKER_16]: We selected members to the Keep Medford Beautiful steering committee and hosted a record setting over 400 volunteers at the citywide cleanup this past May.

68
00:10:01,712 --> 00:10:06,116
[SPEAKER_16]: nearing completion of substantial HVAC work at the Andrews and McGlynn Middle School.

69
00:10:06,997 --> 00:10:12,783
[SPEAKER_16]: We continue to grow the curbside composting program, which now has almost 9,000 households enrolled.

70
00:10:13,844 --> 00:10:19,710
[SPEAKER_16]: We released its first ever urban forest master plan to further our work to protect the tree canopy.

71
00:10:20,585 --> 00:10:33,215
[SPEAKER_16]: Continued our Medford Connect social and climate resiliency work to connect residents to city services and programs that most recent round of Municipal Vulnerability Preparedness Grant funding was $750,000.

72
00:10:34,276 --> 00:10:43,623
[SPEAKER_16]: Through deliberate and targeted efforts, we secured nearly $90,000 in municipal ADA improvement grants to create a new self-evaluation and transition plan.

73
00:10:44,284 --> 00:10:49,728
[SPEAKER_16]: We launched the Neighborhood Ambassadors Task Force aimed at improving communications between city and residents.

74
00:10:50,740 --> 00:11:03,145
[SPEAKER_16]: secured a firefighter safety equipment grant of almost $35,000, received our first distinguished budget presentation award, oh, sorry, third, from the Government Finance Office Association for fiscal year 26.

75
00:11:04,625 --> 00:11:15,730
[SPEAKER_16]: Also received a certificate of achievement for excellence in financial reporting for our annual comprehensive financial report for fiscal year 24, and have applied for the recently completed report for fiscal year 25.

76
00:11:17,397 --> 00:11:25,685
[SPEAKER_16]: And we broke ground on the city's first mini forest at Tufts Park, led by Trees Medford, to expand and enhance Medford's tree canopy and biodiversity.

77
00:11:27,727 --> 00:11:32,732
[SPEAKER_16]: This spring, the city released its first ever urban master plan, like I just mentioned.

78
00:11:34,434 --> 00:11:40,800
[SPEAKER_16]: We are lucky to have secured multiple MVP grants over the years, which have helped communities build resilience to climate impacts.

79
00:11:41,368 --> 00:11:43,989
[SPEAKER_16]: especially in underserved neighborhoods.

80
00:11:44,689 --> 00:11:57,755
[SPEAKER_16]: The plan studied Medford's current tree inventory, distribution, age, and condition, and threats from pests, diseases, and invasives, and will guide the Department of Public Works in growing, caring for, and protecting our trees in the years to come.

81
00:11:58,855 --> 00:12:00,736
[SPEAKER_16]: Another MVP grant for $750,000 is currently funding

82
00:12:03,556 --> 00:12:09,501
[SPEAKER_16]: Our Med4Connects program, led by the Office of Prevention and Outreach, which I also know is very important to the council.

83
00:12:10,081 --> 00:12:21,751
[SPEAKER_16]: This program connects vulnerable residents to essential city resources and funds a wide variety of programs and events throughout the city, including our amazing multilingual and multicultural community engagement team.

84
00:12:22,512 --> 00:12:29,237
[SPEAKER_16]: This team is an important link to the communities that have historically faced barriers to accessing government resources.

85
00:12:30,058 --> 00:12:32,600
[SPEAKER_16]: They host a wide variety of programming all year round.

86
00:12:33,104 --> 00:12:45,070
[SPEAKER_16]: including the winter preparedness event, Haitian Flag Day, Brazilian Independence Day, Arab American Heritage Month, Hispanic Heritage Month, free financial literacy courses, ESOL courses, and much, much more.

87
00:12:46,010 --> 00:12:52,693
[SPEAKER_16]: The Office of Prevention Outreach also handles most of the city's translation needs, funneling requests through the community engagement team.

88
00:12:53,334 --> 00:13:01,798
[SPEAKER_16]: We're happy to share that we are allocating more funding towards translations in the fiscal year 27 budget to ensure the city resources are accessible to all residents.

89
00:13:02,922 --> 00:13:13,844
[SPEAKER_16]: Along the same lines of improving accessibility, the DEI office secured nearly $90,000 in a municipal ADA improvement grant from the Massachusetts Office of Disability.

90
00:13:14,684 --> 00:13:25,967
[SPEAKER_16]: Work for this grant will continue into fiscal year 27 and will allow the city to create a new self-evaluation and transition plan to support improvement projects related to the Americans with Disabilities Act.

91
00:13:27,107 --> 00:13:32,108
[SPEAKER_16]: We also have an application pending through our Office of Prevention and Outreach for Disability Connector.

92
00:13:32,818 --> 00:13:38,387
[SPEAKER_16]: which will be a connection for the community and one who connects the work being done by many of our departments in this area.

93
00:13:39,829 --> 00:13:45,979
[SPEAKER_16]: With that in mind, the City is in the process of renovating two first floor staff bathrooms at City Hall into fully

94
00:13:46,547 --> 00:13:48,088
[SPEAKER_16]: ADA compliant facilities.

95
00:13:48,949 --> 00:13:53,873
[SPEAKER_16]: Construction began this spring and the project is expected to be completed by mid-June.

96
00:13:54,674 --> 00:14:06,664
[SPEAKER_16]: In addition to improving accessibility for visitors and employees, this project represents an important step towards modernizing City Hall and ensuring public facilities are welcoming and usable for all residents.

97
00:14:08,589 --> 00:14:17,701
[SPEAKER_16]: As part of the fiscal year 27 budget, the city continues to prioritize investments in public health, mental health, and recovery services for residents as well.

98
00:14:18,482 --> 00:14:26,592
[SPEAKER_16]: This includes the launch of the new Veterans and First Responders Recovery Group, a partnership between the Veterans Service Office, led by Veronica Shaw,

99
00:14:27,432 --> 00:14:34,418
[SPEAKER_16]: and public health departments that provides dedicated supports for veterans and first responders dealing with substance use and recovery.

100
00:14:35,179 --> 00:14:38,782
[SPEAKER_16]: The weekly support group will be led by the city's recovery coach, Chris Suma.

101
00:14:39,462 --> 00:14:49,851
[SPEAKER_16]: The program reflects Medford's commitment to expanding accessible community-based behavioral health resources and ensuring that those who have served our community and country have access to the support they need.

102
00:14:51,996 --> 00:15:08,995
[SPEAKER_16]: The city, city council, community development board are also in the midst of the restarted zoning project, which began in December 2025 and is taking the process at a more manageable pace for both staff and residents and includes more community engagement opportunities for everyone to make their voices heard.

103
00:15:09,816 --> 00:15:22,886
[SPEAKER_16]: This thoughtful collaboration has yielded significant results with the city recently amending the zoning for the three underutilized lots and rezoning Medford Square, paving the way for a transformative vision for the area.

104
00:15:23,727 --> 00:15:30,552
[SPEAKER_16]: The team is now prioritizing Boston Ave corridor this spring and the Tufts Institutional Zone on the horizon in the fall.

105
00:15:31,633 --> 00:15:37,398
[SPEAKER_16]: The zoning update project will continue into fiscal year 27 to ensure the process is equitable and reasonable.

106
00:15:39,128 --> 00:15:54,681
[SPEAKER_16]: The fiscal year 27 budget reflects the city's strategic focus on capital infrastructure investments, with the engineering division playing a key role in delivering projects that address a multitude of areas, including deferred maintenance, regulatory requirements, and long-term system reliability.

107
00:15:55,462 --> 00:16:05,931
[SPEAKER_16]: Due to sound fiscal management and targeted investments in key staffing areas, the engineering division has added two assistant city engineers, along with key project management and administrative staff.

108
00:16:06,786 --> 00:16:18,688
[SPEAKER_16]: This investment has improved project delivery timelines, reduced reliance on external consultants, which are very costly, and strengthened oversight of capital construction and utility coordination.

109
00:16:19,388 --> 00:16:24,629
[SPEAKER_16]: We will really see the full impact of this staffing increase during the 2027 construction season.

110
00:16:25,690 --> 00:16:32,311
[SPEAKER_16]: From a capital standpoint, fiscal year 26 investments were directed towards roadway, sidewalk, and underground utility improvements.

111
00:16:33,370 --> 00:16:36,572
[SPEAKER_16]: Water and sewer infrastructure remained a significant priority as well.

112
00:16:36,592 --> 00:16:51,463
[SPEAKER_16]: Approximately 7,700 feet of water main were replaced and 4,600 feet of sewer main were rehabilitated to address inflow and infiltration, reducing long-term system costs and regulatory exposure.

113
00:16:52,464 --> 00:16:56,127
[SPEAKER_16]: In parallel, the lead service line program identified and addressed the 857 unknowns.

114
00:16:59,968 --> 00:17:06,673
[SPEAKER_16]: In fiscal year 27, the city is advancing a targeted capital program aligned with available funding and debt capacity.

115
00:17:07,434 --> 00:17:20,383
[SPEAKER_16]: Planned roadway construction includes Arlington Street, Bowen Ave, Golden Ave, and Willis Ave, totaling that 7,700 feet, with associated sidewalk reconstruction of approximately 14,600 linear feet.

116
00:17:23,655 --> 00:17:30,538
[SPEAKER_16]: Water main replacement is scheduled on Brewster Road, Capen Street, Governor's Ave, and Sherwood Road, totaling approximately 6,800 linear feet.

117
00:17:32,218 --> 00:17:40,102
[SPEAKER_16]: The city is also working to address more than 581 million in identified capital needs alongside hundreds of millions more in long-term infrastructure needs.

118
00:17:40,902 --> 00:17:46,064
[SPEAKER_16]: These needs span critical areas including roadway and sidewalk reconstruction and safety improvements.

119
00:17:46,778 --> 00:17:54,766
[SPEAKER_16]: HVAC upgrades in our school, water and sewer infrastructure repairs, ADA upgrades at City Hall, and essential equipment replacement.

120
00:17:55,407 --> 00:18:02,894
[SPEAKER_16]: Many of these investments have been deferred over decades and now require substantial funding to maintain safe, functional, and compliant systems.

121
00:18:03,895 --> 00:18:09,060
[SPEAKER_16]: By prioritizing our infrastructure enhancements, we're promoting the city's commitment to economic development,

122
00:18:09,518 --> 00:18:18,811
[SPEAKER_16]: by reducing our overall long-term costs, increased productivity, attracting investment, creating jobs, and improving the overall quality and resilience of our community.

123
00:18:20,132 --> 00:18:27,217
[SPEAKER_16]: In addition to these existing obligations, the city must also plan for upcoming projects that will further impact our debt capacity.

124
00:18:27,838 --> 00:18:33,822
[SPEAKER_16]: Chief among them is the new proposed Medford High School, which is expected to require a sizable debt exclusion.

125
00:18:34,543 --> 00:18:44,110
[SPEAKER_16]: At the same time, the city understands the need to bond for a fire headquarters, another essential public safety investment that can't be delayed indefinitely.

126
00:18:44,130 --> 00:18:48,153
[SPEAKER_16]: And has included that in the capital improvement six or seven year plan.

127
00:18:49,380 --> 00:18:52,281
[SPEAKER_16]: Taken together, these needs present a clear financial challenge.

128
00:18:52,901 --> 00:19:02,203
[SPEAKER_16]: While borrowing is a necessary tool to fund large scale capital projects, it also increases the city's long term debt obligation as it has a direct impact on our taxpayers.

129
00:19:02,223 --> 00:19:09,965
[SPEAKER_16]: It's therefore critical that we carefully balance the urgency of these investments while remaining aware of the cost burdens they present for our residents.

130
00:19:11,026 --> 00:19:16,147
[SPEAKER_16]: Not every project can be undertaken at once and decisions must be guided by public safety permitting

131
00:19:16,653 --> 00:19:20,696
[SPEAKER_16]: requirements and the understanding to not over leverage the city's revenue sources.

132
00:19:21,256 --> 00:19:26,280
[SPEAKER_16]: The city is actively pursuing state and federal funding opportunities to offset local costs.

133
00:19:27,321 --> 00:19:36,547
[SPEAKER_16]: Ultimately, Medford is committed to making the investments necessary to support a growing and evolving community, but we need to be careful not to place a burden on our residents.

134
00:19:37,288 --> 00:19:40,250
[SPEAKER_16]: By taking a measured strategic approach, capital planning,

135
00:19:40,832 --> 00:19:47,316
[SPEAKER_16]: The City aims to responsibly manage its debt while continuing to deliver the infrastructure and services that residents rely on every day.

136
00:19:50,477 --> 00:19:55,480
[SPEAKER_16]: The City has selected Transom Real Estate as our partner in transforming the three underutilized lots.

137
00:19:55,740 --> 00:20:00,463
[SPEAKER_16]: This project will create a true village square atmosphere and ensure ample parking for our seniors.

138
00:20:00,947 --> 00:20:03,709
[SPEAKER_16]: and patrons for Chevalier Theatre.

139
00:20:04,409 --> 00:20:07,732
[SPEAKER_16]: Transom's proposal reflects the values we share as a city.

140
00:20:08,332 --> 00:20:19,700
[SPEAKER_16]: It includes both market rate and affordable housing, anchored by a 13,500 square foot grocery store across from the senior center, and designed with pedestrian access and safety at the center.

141
00:20:20,468 --> 00:20:28,610
[SPEAKER_16]: It is a vision that aligns with our comprehensive plan and advances the goals laid out in your requests and the request for proposals.

142
00:20:29,130 --> 00:20:32,130
[SPEAKER_16]: A Medford Square that is walkable, welcoming, and filled with opportunity.

143
00:20:32,970 --> 00:20:42,752
[SPEAKER_16]: To best support investments, the city completed the Medford Economic Assessment Study, which examines the city's current economic landscape and provides recommendation for future programs.

144
00:20:43,432 --> 00:20:47,533
[SPEAKER_16]: Staff will use the findings to inform policy decisions, prioritize initiatives,

145
00:20:48,025 --> 00:20:55,050
[SPEAKER_16]: and collaborate with community partners regarding opportunities to support local businesses and strengthen the growth of the innovation economy.

146
00:20:56,611 --> 00:21:07,579
[SPEAKER_16]: Also, the city is undertaking over the 2.4 million in park renovation projects that I mentioned, with several slated for completion this construction season that extends into fiscal year 27.

147
00:21:08,280 --> 00:21:17,146
[SPEAKER_16]: Projects include Logan Park, Riverside Avenue, Shade Improvement Project, Clippership Pop-Up Park, Playstead Road Safety Improvements, Tufts Park Upgrades,

148
00:21:17,677 --> 00:21:19,798
[SPEAKER_16]: and phase two of the car park renovation.

149
00:21:20,838 --> 00:21:38,046
[SPEAKER_16]: Park and public space improvements that are in queue next include work at Wright's Pond and Condon Shell, a mini forest at Tufts Park, creating a COVID-19 Memorial Grove, and implementing pieces of the Mystic Shoreline Revitalization Plan, which was developed by the Mystic River Watershed Association.

150
00:21:39,767 --> 00:21:53,157
[SPEAKER_16]: To encourage both residents and visitors to visit and patronize Medford's business districts, the Office of Planning, Development and Sustainability has completed a wayfinding master plan conducted by design firm OverUnder and in partnership with MassDevelopment.

151
00:21:53,837 --> 00:22:06,406
[SPEAKER_16]: The study funded by a Massachusetts Gaming Commission Community Grant aims to improve navigation challenges across all modes of transportation and highlights points of interest in the city through signage and citywide public spaces.

152
00:22:07,187 --> 00:22:07,527
[SPEAKER_16]: Almost done.

153
00:22:08,417 --> 00:22:12,679
[SPEAKER_16]: The public art and historical preservation also remains priorities.

154
00:22:13,219 --> 00:22:24,325
[SPEAKER_16]: With the Council's support, the City unveiled the new Sarah Bradley Fulton Statute outside City Hall, recognizing Medford's Revolutionary War history and creating a new civic landmark in the heart of Medford Square.

155
00:22:25,165 --> 00:22:31,829
[SPEAKER_16]: Throughout the fiscal year, the City continued to expand in the arts and strengthen neighborhood identity through a series of cultural programs and celebrations.

156
00:22:32,689 --> 00:22:34,110
[SPEAKER_16]: Major events supported by the City

157
00:22:34,914 --> 00:22:52,376
[SPEAKER_16]: include the Disability Fair, community concerts, Medford Pride, Winter Extravaganza, as well as numerous multicultural and neighborhood-based events that brought residents together across the community, like the annual Citywide Cleanup, Run Medford, and this Saturday will be our annual Porch Fest.

158
00:22:54,053 --> 00:23:01,799
[SPEAKER_16]: Our new Keep Medford Beautiful chapter is a community effort to organize local volunteers interested in cleaning up and beautifying Medford's public spaces.

159
00:23:02,419 --> 00:23:11,085
[SPEAKER_16]: Members were officially named to the steering committee in March, and the team will continue to work alongside the Department of Public Works and our office into the next fiscal year.

160
00:23:11,806 --> 00:23:14,448
[SPEAKER_16]: For the first time, we've included a rodent prevention line.

161
00:23:14,938 --> 00:23:21,481
[SPEAKER_16]: believe that was also one of your priorities in your memo in the budget as another way to keep our city clean and beautiful.

162
00:23:21,942 --> 00:23:26,264
[SPEAKER_16]: Rodent populations are a concern for all of us and every municipality.

163
00:23:26,304 --> 00:23:32,207
[SPEAKER_16]: We want to ensure that our public health and animal control staff have the resources they need to control and mitigate the situation.

164
00:23:35,985 --> 00:23:41,946
[SPEAKER_16]: In its anticipated funding source, this lapse in fiscal year 27 was the city's American Rescue Plan dollars.

165
00:23:42,246 --> 00:23:48,467
[SPEAKER_16]: The city has been funding a number of contracts and staff positions through this federal relief program for the past five years.

166
00:23:49,247 --> 00:24:03,470
[SPEAKER_16]: We've had to rearrange multiple department budgets to account for items like better teams, used by human resources, and salaries such as our federal funds manager, a disability specialist, and associated salary costs for our communications team.

167
00:24:04,399 --> 00:24:11,226
[SPEAKER_16]: This work wouldn't be possible without the support of the strong leadership team we have built here in Medford and without the City Council's support.

168
00:24:12,006 --> 00:24:18,293
[SPEAKER_16]: Over the past year, we've hired a new elections manager and facilities director, as well as promoted a new library director.

169
00:24:19,213 --> 00:24:26,781
[SPEAKER_16]: We're proud of our financial strategy, which has yielded us a double A plus bond rating and strong admiration from our peers in the form of two

170
00:24:27,288 --> 00:24:31,950
[SPEAKER_16]: consecutive government finance officer association budget awards for the last two years.

171
00:24:32,830 --> 00:24:40,313
[SPEAKER_16]: The finance team was also recognized for the exemplary work compiling the city's annual comprehensive financial report.

172
00:24:41,217 --> 00:24:52,629
[SPEAKER_16]: According to the GFOA, the award represents a significant achievement by a municipality that reflects the commitment of the governing body and staff to meet the highest principles of governmental budgeting.

173
00:24:53,250 --> 00:24:58,815
[SPEAKER_16]: We look forward to putting forth a new budget for fiscal year 27 that meets, if not succeeds, these expectations.

174
00:24:59,856 --> 00:25:00,958
[SPEAKER_16]: As this work highlighted

175
00:25:01,438 --> 00:25:14,710
[SPEAKER_16]: exemplifies the professionalism, dedication and expertise of our incredible staff who worked tirelessly to deliver not only exceptional public service to our community but meaningful improvements that strengthen our city's connections to its residents.

176
00:25:15,790 --> 00:25:16,531
[SPEAKER_16]: Thank you for the time.

177
00:25:16,591 --> 00:25:17,432
[SPEAKER_16]: I know I'm long-winded.

178
00:25:17,853 --> 00:25:25,639
[SPEAKER_16]: But I appreciate having the ability to read most of the what will be in the budget book, although I did cut some out because I feel bad it's so long.

179
00:25:25,879 --> 00:25:26,259
[SPEAKER_16]: And thank you.

180
00:25:26,399 --> 00:25:27,540
[SPEAKER_16]: Welcome, Councilor Lazaro.

181
00:25:28,100 --> 00:25:31,103
[SPEAKER_16]: And I'm here to answer any questions you may have.

182
00:25:31,543 --> 00:25:37,047
[SPEAKER_16]: I know we have several budgets before you and Chief of Staff Nazarian is also in attendance.

183
00:25:37,707 --> 00:25:38,088
[SPEAKER_05]: Thank you.

184
00:25:38,208 --> 00:25:40,109
[SPEAKER_05]: Do we have questions for the mayor?

185
00:25:40,369 --> 00:25:42,591
[SPEAKER_05]: I see Council Vice President Lazaro.

186
00:25:43,935 --> 00:25:45,876
[SPEAKER_17]: Hi, I wanted to apologize for my late arrival.

187
00:25:45,896 --> 00:25:57,201
[SPEAKER_17]: I was under the impression that we would be finished with the Committee of the Whole presentations by June 2nd, so I had a conflicting obligation tonight.

188
00:25:58,201 --> 00:26:06,345
[SPEAKER_17]: Also, I want to be really upfront that these meetings have been going on for a long time and we've been reviewing the budgets for,

189
00:26:07,805 --> 00:26:08,726
[SPEAKER_17]: couple months already.

190
00:26:10,907 --> 00:26:20,831
[SPEAKER_17]: And I have a babysitter tonight because my kids are at home and my ex-husband is on a business trip, so I will be leaving at 10 p.m.

191
00:26:21,471 --> 00:26:28,715
[SPEAKER_17]: So these are three massive departments that are all in the last

192
00:26:29,175 --> 00:26:31,497
[SPEAKER_17]: Committee of the Whole jammed in at the end.

193
00:26:31,557 --> 00:26:32,618
[SPEAKER_17]: This happened last year as well.

194
00:26:34,820 --> 00:26:42,446
[SPEAKER_17]: The school budget is over $90 million and we don't, there's not time to discuss it in one evening.

195
00:26:43,366 --> 00:26:47,670
[SPEAKER_17]: But I'm going to leave at 10 because I can't afford to pay a babysitter to stay until 2 in the morning.

196
00:26:48,568 --> 00:26:51,853
[SPEAKER_17]: And we're going to talk about it again on June 9th, I guess, or we're going to vote for it.

197
00:26:52,553 --> 00:26:57,720
[SPEAKER_17]: And it's, you know, 630, and we haven't talked about anything yet.

198
00:26:57,921 --> 00:27:00,684
[SPEAKER_17]: So I'm starting off frustrated.

199
00:27:02,727 --> 00:27:03,508
[SPEAKER_17]: I wish that we could.

200
00:27:05,460 --> 00:27:08,381
[SPEAKER_17]: follow the regulations of the ordinance as written.

201
00:27:09,421 --> 00:27:18,323
[SPEAKER_17]: There are a lot of ordinances that I wish we could follow as written, including the Citizen Control over Public Surveillance Ordinance, known as CCOPS.

202
00:27:18,923 --> 00:27:21,044
[SPEAKER_17]: It's so great to have the police department here tonight.

203
00:27:21,724 --> 00:27:30,386
[SPEAKER_17]: We did not have the police department here on the night that we talked about the CCOPS ordinance, which is supposed to happen as written in the ordinance.

204
00:27:30,726 --> 00:27:33,707
[SPEAKER_17]: That was on May 20th, and nobody was in attendance for that.

205
00:27:35,067 --> 00:27:40,629
[SPEAKER_17]: When ordinances are written in Medford, the intention is that they be enforced.

206
00:27:40,989 --> 00:27:51,152
[SPEAKER_17]: So I've, I'm starting this meeting from a place of frustration and I just want to be upfront about that.

207
00:27:51,952 --> 00:27:52,292
[SPEAKER_17]: Thanks.

208
00:27:54,533 --> 00:27:54,973
[SPEAKER_05]: Thank you.

209
00:27:54,993 --> 00:27:56,193
[SPEAKER_05]: Do we have further questions?

210
00:28:01,015 --> 00:28:01,595
[SPEAKER_05]: Councilor Mlayne.

211
00:28:03,220 --> 00:28:08,903
[SPEAKER_13]: Thank you Mayor for going through that listing of different items to discuss today.

212
00:28:09,243 --> 00:28:31,134
[SPEAKER_13]: One of the areas I was trying to figure out and I apologize as I'm first time going through the budget process but I have been getting a lot of questions about the Medford Family Network and I was wondering where within the different budgets it might lie or rest or kind of where we might stand in that as I know we're kind of coming up to kind of finalizing the budget and looking at the final budget this year.

213
00:28:32,708 --> 00:28:34,810
[SPEAKER_16]: A few things on the Medford Family Network.

214
00:28:35,751 --> 00:28:54,870
[SPEAKER_16]: Myself and Chief of Staff Nina Nazarian have been doing the tough work, which may be why we are saved the larger departments, because they obviously have room where we were trying to squeeze some money to provide more money to our schools, which is about a $2 million gap at this point.

215
00:28:57,267 --> 00:28:59,328
[SPEAKER_16]: and the MedFamily network that needs the $240,000.

216
00:28:59,969 --> 00:29:02,971
[SPEAKER_16]: So we have been doing that hard work.

217
00:29:04,612 --> 00:29:14,178
[SPEAKER_16]: We do not have $2.24 million, but I did have a financial task force meeting with President Behrs, Consul Lazaro,

218
00:29:16,012 --> 00:29:19,374
[SPEAKER_16]: member Master Boney and member Graham from the school committee.

219
00:29:19,554 --> 00:29:24,217
[SPEAKER_16]: And we discussed one way to handle it.

220
00:29:24,877 --> 00:29:35,343
[SPEAKER_16]: So I really do have hope that we'll be able to at least bridge the gap and then hopefully try to get them funding for additional years through grants and different means.

221
00:29:36,044 --> 00:29:38,385
[SPEAKER_16]: But I also have a call with Tufts University tomorrow.

222
00:29:38,545 --> 00:29:42,227
[SPEAKER_16]: I did reach out to Tufts and ask them to provide more.

223
00:29:42,387 --> 00:29:43,808
[SPEAKER_16]: I know they gave them a $5,000 grant through their

224
00:29:45,509 --> 00:29:55,056
[SPEAKER_16]: grant round recently, but I did tell them the situation and explained what they were going through and the loss of the funding that they had over the last 10 years.

225
00:29:55,536 --> 00:29:58,418
[SPEAKER_16]: And I believe one of the school committee members also reached out to Tufts.

226
00:29:58,538 --> 00:29:59,819
[SPEAKER_16]: So that call is in the morning.

227
00:30:00,500 --> 00:30:10,187
[SPEAKER_16]: What we're hoping to do, just a general overview is in why one of the reasons I came tonight is because I've been really digesting that

228
00:30:10,647 --> 00:30:14,871
[SPEAKER_16]: eight to ten page memo from your meeting in March with all the council's priorities.

229
00:30:14,931 --> 00:30:15,932
[SPEAKER_16]: It was very lengthy.

230
00:30:16,413 --> 00:30:21,118
[SPEAKER_16]: Everybody had great requests and wants and needs.

231
00:30:21,658 --> 00:30:23,600
[SPEAKER_16]: I was really trying to evaluate them all.

232
00:30:23,921 --> 00:30:32,609
[SPEAKER_16]: Over the last maybe four to six weeks, you've probably got five to ten emails from me where I've asked department heads to highlight things that I know are continuing.

233
00:30:33,951 --> 00:30:42,417
[SPEAKER_16]: You're very interested in the connectors and the liaisons, so I asked our Board of Health to just write up how that is going to be sustained and how we're going to enhance that.

234
00:30:42,897 --> 00:30:47,560
[SPEAKER_16]: You've asked about home sharing and how we're going to implement the

235
00:30:50,488 --> 00:30:53,812
[SPEAKER_16]: tree work we've done and we want to volunteer day.

236
00:30:53,892 --> 00:30:56,355
[SPEAKER_16]: So I've really been trying to answer your questions throughout.

237
00:30:56,916 --> 00:31:05,467
[SPEAKER_16]: Then we're working with Nina Nazarian, chief of staff, as she goes through budget hearings on additional things that we may be hearing.

238
00:31:05,950 --> 00:31:24,183
[SPEAKER_16]: We're going to do the same thing tonight and her and I are meeting tomorrow to discuss what adjustments we can make for the council, what additional adjustments we can make for council priorities, have those laid out to you in an email tomorrow with my availability for anybody to call me or set up a meeting.

239
00:31:25,063 --> 00:31:43,074
[SPEAKER_16]: And then also what chunk of money we'll be able to give to the schools and to the Medford Family Network, which I'm hopeful that Tess will come through for us and that we'll all agree on how to handle the remainder that Medford Family Networks needs to move forward.

240
00:31:43,494 --> 00:31:54,081
[SPEAKER_16]: So I just hope for a collaboration over the next week by phone call or two if you vote on the budget on the 9th or if you table it and vote on the 23rd.

241
00:31:54,982 --> 00:32:04,206
[SPEAKER_16]: a hopeful collaboration and I'm trying to take all the council's requests and be thoughtful and, and do as much as I, as we, as we can.

242
00:32:04,527 --> 00:32:04,747
[SPEAKER_13]: Sure.

243
00:32:04,767 --> 00:32:05,567
[SPEAKER_13]: No, and I appreciate it.

244
00:32:05,587 --> 00:32:07,648
[SPEAKER_13]: I know there's a, there's a gap we're trying to fill.

245
00:32:08,128 --> 00:32:13,411
[SPEAKER_13]: So I guess between this next week, we'll have a better understanding of where we might be at least to close the gap for this year.

246
00:32:14,571 --> 00:32:16,773
[SPEAKER_13]: Is that what I'm hearing within this next week or so before?

247
00:32:16,813 --> 00:32:17,013
[SPEAKER_13]: Yes.

248
00:32:17,253 --> 00:32:17,433
[SPEAKER_16]: Okay.

249
00:32:17,573 --> 00:32:23,676
[SPEAKER_16]: I think, I think I'll probably try to get an email to you by end of business tomorrow that will outline

250
00:32:24,276 --> 00:32:28,360
[SPEAKER_16]: what adjustments we'll make, what we can give to the schools and the family network.

251
00:32:29,060 --> 00:32:36,387
[SPEAKER_16]: And then we can talk, or you can say that this all sounds good, or this sounds bad, but we'll do what we can.

252
00:32:37,307 --> 00:32:37,648
[SPEAKER_16]: Thank you.

253
00:32:39,870 --> 00:32:40,450
[SPEAKER_03]: Thank you.

254
00:32:44,393 --> 00:32:46,075
[SPEAKER_03]: Do we have any other councilors saying?

255
00:32:47,575 --> 00:32:48,836
[SPEAKER_09]: Thank you, Mayor, for coming today.

256
00:32:49,936 --> 00:32:55,399
[SPEAKER_09]: I think your speech made me excited about the things that we've done in the past.

257
00:32:56,219 --> 00:33:04,903
[SPEAKER_09]: It makes me even more ambitious to dream bigger about what we can do with city government, what we can do for our workers and for our residents as well.

258
00:33:06,524 --> 00:33:15,188
[SPEAKER_09]: I think the council understands that it's never easy to run a municipal budget, especially with the pressures from Prop 2.5

259
00:33:16,347 --> 00:33:23,530
[SPEAKER_09]: from rising inflation that affects the public sector much more than the private sector as well.

260
00:33:24,711 --> 00:33:27,572
[SPEAKER_09]: Of course, there are pressures everywhere.

261
00:33:28,873 --> 00:33:44,180
[SPEAKER_09]: I think at the same time, there's a concern with residents and with members of the council that oftentimes the budgets that we receive are kind of bandaging over

262
00:33:45,732 --> 00:33:49,275
[SPEAKER_09]: the difficulties of a year and then just trying to get us to the next year.

263
00:33:50,797 --> 00:34:03,669
[SPEAKER_09]: And the way out of that is thinking about long term revenue and that plan for what do we do when we know that grants are falling off, what do we know when

264
00:34:04,655 --> 00:34:06,857
[SPEAKER_09]: certain big non-profits in the city are losing money.

265
00:34:07,878 --> 00:34:09,699
[SPEAKER_09]: How do we plan that out over a few years?

266
00:34:10,279 --> 00:34:15,143
[SPEAKER_09]: And how do we make sure that the new growth strategy keeps on pace?

267
00:34:15,663 --> 00:34:18,365
[SPEAKER_09]: I think transom is a real great addition to the city.

268
00:34:18,786 --> 00:34:21,508
[SPEAKER_09]: It's something that we can be really optimistic about.

269
00:34:22,008 --> 00:34:27,172
[SPEAKER_09]: But we'd love to see more transoms, more projects like that.

270
00:34:27,773 --> 00:34:30,555
[SPEAKER_09]: And at the same time, I think it's difficult for the council

271
00:34:32,155 --> 00:34:43,563
[SPEAKER_09]: You know, I think with the rezoning project, the residents were right that there needed to be better communication, there needed to be more kind of opportunities for feedback.

272
00:34:44,724 --> 00:34:45,705
[SPEAKER_09]: They're definitely right on that.

273
00:34:46,545 --> 00:34:51,008
[SPEAKER_09]: At the same time, I think oftentimes we conflate that with the question about pace.

274
00:34:53,130 --> 00:34:58,253
[SPEAKER_09]: And given the kind of concerns that we have about, you know,

275
00:34:59,442 --> 00:35:08,029
[SPEAKER_09]: fiscal pressures facing the city and also the pace of kind of new growth, housing, commercial development to generate revenue over a long term.

276
00:35:10,091 --> 00:35:27,945
[SPEAKER_09]: Can we, can you describe kind of over the next five years what pressures we'll be expecting as a city and how we're gonna get to that revenue plan to generate the revenue for that over the next five years?

277
00:35:28,599 --> 00:35:40,462
[SPEAKER_16]: Yeah, I think we're going to experience pressures as you see the federal governments giving states, including Massachusetts, far less funding.

278
00:35:40,682 --> 00:35:47,524
[SPEAKER_16]: And in turn, the funding that we get from the state pretty much stays stagnant.

279
00:35:47,624 --> 00:35:51,645
[SPEAKER_16]: And so the percentage of what we get from the state continues to decrease.

280
00:35:52,545 --> 00:35:55,826
[SPEAKER_16]: So we have to be creative from a city perspective.

281
00:35:55,866 --> 00:35:57,947
[SPEAKER_16]: We're not in a different boat than any other

282
00:35:58,670 --> 00:36:05,294
[SPEAKER_16]: community that I've been watching, I've been watching the override votes and the debt exclusion votes pass and fail in communities across the Commonwealth.

283
00:36:05,374 --> 00:36:11,978
[SPEAKER_16]: And my colleagues, mayors and town managers are really struggling out there, especially if they have votes that fail.

284
00:36:13,819 --> 00:36:15,560
[SPEAKER_16]: But I think the work that this council

285
00:36:16,822 --> 00:36:28,608
[SPEAKER_16]: along with the planning office and my office are doing to rezone in the right way is going to be definitely pave the way for new development.

286
00:36:28,848 --> 00:36:41,654
[SPEAKER_16]: We also have, I think, seven developments that are just like transom, although not all have a commercial component, but there is the Mystic Valley Parkway development that's close to 300 units.

287
00:36:42,094 --> 00:36:42,995
[SPEAKER_16]: That was a 40B.

288
00:36:43,095 --> 00:36:44,436
[SPEAKER_16]: We have the Davis.

289
00:36:46,317 --> 00:36:50,381
[SPEAKER_16]: company's development that's another almost 300 units.

290
00:36:50,421 --> 00:36:51,442
[SPEAKER_16]: That's on the Fellsway.

291
00:36:51,462 --> 00:37:02,453
[SPEAKER_16]: The KISS 108 station right next to the Wellington Tee is another large-scale development that we've been working on, as well as where Cappy's location is.

292
00:37:02,653 --> 00:37:06,557
[SPEAKER_16]: That's going to be, I think they added 50 more units, so I think that's closer to 350 plus.

293
00:37:09,660 --> 00:37:14,784
[SPEAKER_16]: And there are a few more that are not on the top of my head, but we have been actively working on it.

294
00:37:15,145 --> 00:37:19,889
[SPEAKER_16]: In addition to the zoning review, we're also working on the Wellington Transformation Study.

295
00:37:19,949 --> 00:37:30,918
[SPEAKER_16]: We have a company in helping us create, of course, mixed use, but commercial and industrial to make sure we maintain our commercial tax base and increase what we have.

296
00:37:31,659 --> 00:37:36,643
[SPEAKER_16]: Unfortunately, I think we had eight companies or projects in queue that were

297
00:37:37,725 --> 00:37:45,436
[SPEAKER_16]: small to very large scale life science developments that didn't pan out due to financing and saturation in the market.

298
00:37:45,596 --> 00:37:53,347
[SPEAKER_16]: I think that's because the city didn't start looking at life science or trying to actively obtain life science until 2020 and it was just too late.

299
00:37:55,068 --> 00:38:16,396
[SPEAKER_16]: So there's between the transformation study and what we're doing in West Medford, we have a West Medford study, the rezoning, me negotiating with the Mystic Valley Development Commission and obtaining that $1.3 million, getting those two parcels out of the pilot and onto Medford tax rolls so we could obtain the new growth.

300
00:38:16,916 --> 00:38:21,018
[SPEAKER_16]: I am trying to be as creative and hardworking as I can to

301
00:38:22,384 --> 00:38:34,480
[SPEAKER_16]: try to sustain the budget that we have and increase it as much as we can due to the fact that the federal government and the state government are not providing us as much as we really, really need.

302
00:38:35,221 --> 00:38:35,441
[SPEAKER_09]: Yeah.

303
00:38:35,841 --> 00:38:39,867
[SPEAKER_09]: No, I mean, I think, yeah, I think that's fair to say they're not doing

304
00:38:41,227 --> 00:38:42,888
[SPEAKER_09]: what communities like ours need.

305
00:38:43,728 --> 00:38:47,069
[SPEAKER_09]: But I guess I have two follow-ups on top of that.

306
00:38:47,569 --> 00:38:53,791
[SPEAKER_09]: The first thing is, as you noted, I think we were a little bit behind the curve when it came to life sciences.

307
00:38:54,671 --> 00:39:00,533
[SPEAKER_09]: What lessons are we taking from that in terms of looking at new industrial and commercial development in the city?

308
00:39:02,193 --> 00:39:04,514
[SPEAKER_09]: And the other question is more concrete.

309
00:39:04,534 --> 00:39:10,415
[SPEAKER_09]: Do you have projections of how much new growth revenue those projects that you've noted would bring in?

310
00:39:11,636 --> 00:39:18,317
[SPEAKER_09]: And it'd be useful to see those relative to maybe what we expect insurance and pensions to go up by in future years, too.

311
00:39:18,597 --> 00:39:20,097
[SPEAKER_09]: And if you do have those numbers.

312
00:39:20,137 --> 00:39:24,118
[SPEAKER_16]: I don't have them in my head, but I think we could provide them to you if you are CFO.

313
00:39:24,559 --> 00:39:25,099
[SPEAKER_16]: Absolutely.

314
00:39:25,219 --> 00:39:25,379
[SPEAKER_16]: Yep.

315
00:39:25,879 --> 00:39:26,539
[SPEAKER_16]: We'll take note of that.

316
00:39:28,525 --> 00:39:28,785
[SPEAKER_09]: Great.

317
00:39:29,045 --> 00:39:33,328
[SPEAKER_09]: And then the first question about just commercial and the lessons that we've learned.

318
00:39:34,329 --> 00:39:35,890
[SPEAKER_16]: Yes, I came in in 2020.

319
00:39:36,250 --> 00:39:46,998
[SPEAKER_16]: And right from me taking office was when I started really trying to bring in the life science, because it was just really starting to expand.

320
00:39:47,038 --> 00:39:50,420
[SPEAKER_16]: And you were seeing life science buildings opening in more than just Cambridge.

321
00:39:51,081 --> 00:39:55,524
[SPEAKER_16]: But by the time we had those probably eight or so developments in queue,

322
00:39:56,209 --> 00:40:02,675
[SPEAKER_16]: You just saw over 2022, 2023, each one lose funding due to saturation of the market.

323
00:40:04,097 --> 00:40:20,333
[SPEAKER_16]: I think you'll get a presentation very soon on the Wellington Transformation Study, and that is our main focus is commercial industrial as it relates to making sure that Wellington remains strong with our commercial growth.

324
00:40:21,031 --> 00:40:24,852
[SPEAKER_16]: and adds, you know, additional growth to that location.

325
00:40:24,972 --> 00:40:29,394
[SPEAKER_16]: So that's one of the biggest studies we're doing right now.

326
00:40:29,874 --> 00:40:38,057
[SPEAKER_16]: But we every day are trying to, I think I just signed a letter supporting the vacant storefront grant.

327
00:40:38,197 --> 00:40:40,698
[SPEAKER_16]: So we are actively trying to bring in commercial business.

328
00:40:42,077 --> 00:40:44,418
[SPEAKER_09]: Yeah, I mean, I think that's helpful to know.

329
00:40:45,719 --> 00:40:52,942
[SPEAKER_09]: The, I just wanted to note, you know, as we talked about Wellington, you know, it's a place I'm very passionate about, a place I call home.

330
00:40:54,083 --> 00:41:00,986
[SPEAKER_09]: And I just want to make sure that we're making this next round of growth before it, before it's too late.

331
00:41:01,006 --> 00:41:01,846
[SPEAKER_09]: Right.

332
00:41:02,046 --> 00:41:07,128
[SPEAKER_09]: And, you know, sometimes I'm worried that drawing things out too long makes us miss that boat.

333
00:41:09,207 --> 00:41:12,709
[SPEAKER_09]: I'd also, I had a few questions about the budget process itself.

334
00:41:13,229 --> 00:41:33,742
[SPEAKER_09]: I think at the last meeting we heard that some department heads, maybe many department heads, received the proposed budget around the same time as the council or right before, and that there wasn't necessarily the back and forth that we would expect

335
00:41:34,705 --> 00:41:46,331
[SPEAKER_09]: happen to happen in the budget process between folks putting together the budget and the individual departments that were making the recommendations?

336
00:41:48,432 --> 00:41:48,712
[SPEAKER_09]: Is that?

337
00:41:50,476 --> 00:41:50,916
[SPEAKER_09]: accurate.

338
00:41:51,336 --> 00:42:07,243
[SPEAKER_09]: And I think on top of that, we had a very specific concern that we found out during the, when we were evaluating the city messenger position, which we want to convert to a constituent services aid modernized position to be more useful for the 21st century.

339
00:42:09,204 --> 00:42:11,505
[SPEAKER_09]: I think the council president might have

340
00:42:13,527 --> 00:42:18,470
[SPEAKER_09]: just made some recommendations about where we could find the funding for it within the department.

341
00:42:19,610 --> 00:42:35,177
[SPEAKER_09]: And essentially the idea was re-envisioning, restructuring the legislative department so that we could have that extra person, we could finance that extra person and also kind of modernize in total the vision of how we do things.

342
00:42:35,918 --> 00:42:40,180
[SPEAKER_09]: And then I think the budget that we received had all the cuts but none of the readjustments.

343
00:42:41,922 --> 00:42:56,556
[SPEAKER_09]: And essentially, I think this is the second part of the budget process question is, it seemed like there wasn't communication to understand the kind of, the reason behind why recommendations for certain cuts were made.

344
00:42:57,322 --> 00:43:22,824
[SPEAKER_09]: And I think what we said on the council last week was that we were worried that if this is the approach, we're worried that department heads aren't actually incentivized to make bolder kind of plans for the department because they might be worried that they could make certain line item cuts or cut recommendations to restructure the department but they wouldn't get the kind of the plus at the end of it.

345
00:43:24,105 --> 00:43:25,666
[SPEAKER_09]: to fund that restructuring.

346
00:43:26,247 --> 00:43:31,632
[SPEAKER_09]: And I guess, I'm curious what your approach to the budget process is.

347
00:43:31,712 --> 00:43:32,173
[SPEAKER_16]: Sure, yeah.

348
00:43:32,313 --> 00:43:34,515
[SPEAKER_16]: I'll start with your first question.

349
00:43:34,575 --> 00:43:39,780
[SPEAKER_16]: I think in late February, March, into April,

350
00:43:41,592 --> 00:43:48,936
[SPEAKER_16]: within six weeks of that time frame, we meet with every department head for one to two hours.

351
00:43:49,136 --> 00:43:53,598
[SPEAKER_16]: Myself and my chief of staff, we give them a two hour slot.

352
00:43:53,658 --> 00:43:57,080
[SPEAKER_16]: So I think we did maybe say four or five a week.

353
00:43:58,041 --> 00:44:03,324
[SPEAKER_16]: And we didn't, we, at that point we don't know what the schools are coming in at.

354
00:44:03,664 --> 00:44:05,044
[SPEAKER_16]: We don't ask them to

355
00:44:06,620 --> 00:44:08,262
[SPEAKER_16]: make any cuts at that time.

356
00:44:08,723 --> 00:44:13,869
[SPEAKER_16]: We ask them for what their proposed budget is and requested and required expenses.

357
00:44:14,990 --> 00:44:15,831
[SPEAKER_16]: We take it all in.

358
00:44:15,891 --> 00:44:16,893
[SPEAKER_16]: We ask questions.

359
00:44:17,093 --> 00:44:22,640
[SPEAKER_16]: We do our due diligence and review what we need to review.

360
00:44:22,660 --> 00:44:25,964
[SPEAKER_16]: And then once the school budget comes in,

361
00:44:26,520 --> 00:44:27,741
[SPEAKER_16]: we figure out what the gap is.

362
00:44:27,821 --> 00:44:32,563
[SPEAKER_16]: This year, there was only a presented budget, which was a $6 million gap.

363
00:44:32,644 --> 00:44:42,549
[SPEAKER_16]: At that point, we knew that that was because it was based on what the school committee wants to know, what the

364
00:44:44,852 --> 00:44:47,713
[SPEAKER_16]: schools would need if we had all the, you know, all the money in the world.

365
00:44:47,793 --> 00:44:50,194
[SPEAKER_16]: So that was a $6 million gap.

366
00:44:50,214 --> 00:44:55,116
[SPEAKER_16]: But I didn't, we didn't know, myself and, and my chief of staff did not know what the actual gap was.

367
00:44:55,196 --> 00:45:02,379
[SPEAKER_16]: So there was nothing we could do as far as touching budgets to try to reduce city side budgets until we knew what that gap was.

368
00:45:02,479 --> 00:45:06,041
[SPEAKER_16]: And that came probably,

369
00:45:07,544 --> 00:45:11,227
[SPEAKER_16]: It came later than we would like, but obviously everybody's doing hard work behind the scenes.

370
00:45:11,908 --> 00:45:16,111
[SPEAKER_16]: Once we had that, we did not go and review every single budget.

371
00:45:16,131 --> 00:45:17,032
[SPEAKER_16]: We just don't have the time.

372
00:45:17,072 --> 00:45:19,774
[SPEAKER_16]: I'm in four, five, six, seven meetings a day.

373
00:45:20,714 --> 00:45:23,397
[SPEAKER_16]: As Nina and I were able to schedule

374
00:45:24,157 --> 00:45:31,167
[SPEAKER_16]: two to three hours a week in our calendar where we go over early in the week, we would go over the budgets that we were going to be presenting the week after.

375
00:45:31,187 --> 00:45:38,837
[SPEAKER_16]: We would kind of finalize where we were at once we knew what the gap was, the 2.24 million, which was pretty recent.

376
00:45:39,612 --> 00:45:43,915
[SPEAKER_16]: And then we would finalize that on a Wednesday and give it to the department head on a Thursday.

377
00:45:43,935 --> 00:45:54,142
[SPEAKER_16]: And so yes, the department heads had maybe almost a week, a little less than a week to review their budgets, ask questions, push back, see if they could change things.

378
00:45:54,322 --> 00:45:55,603
[SPEAKER_16]: And we were pretty amenable.

379
00:45:57,104 --> 00:46:01,868
[SPEAKER_16]: Knowing we have to tell our department heads that we have almost a $2.5 million gap, this is not like a plentiful year.

380
00:46:05,172 --> 00:46:15,519
[SPEAKER_16]: It's, you know, I feel, we feel terrible for our department heads that, you know, we have to either reduce this line item and tell them they need to, you know, use free cash in the future or.

381
00:46:15,539 --> 00:46:26,307
[SPEAKER_16]: So that's, we just took a few budgets a week as we were presenting, giving them to the council.

382
00:46:26,327 --> 00:46:27,668
[SPEAKER_16]: That's kind of my answer.

383
00:46:27,828 --> 00:46:29,069
[SPEAKER_16]: It's a very tedious process.

384
00:46:43,110 --> 00:46:55,262
[SPEAKER_09]: You mentioned the gap and I'm just curious what, do you guys have an estimate of what the free cash after the budget, after the proposed budget and after the proposed transfers is going to look like?

385
00:46:55,282 --> 00:46:57,965
[SPEAKER_09]: Do you have an estimate of the amount?

386
00:46:59,698 --> 00:47:00,018
[SPEAKER_14]: Thank you.

387
00:47:01,059 --> 00:47:03,502
[SPEAKER_14]: That's such a hard thing to answer at this point in time.

388
00:47:06,885 --> 00:47:17,716
[SPEAKER_14]: I know finance officials across the state try very hard not to commit to those types of questions, and I'm not going to want to put our finance director in the position to

389
00:47:18,777 --> 00:47:28,664
[SPEAKER_14]: I'm not going to commit him to answering those types of questions at this point, but I can tell you we're still looking at transfers that will need to happen and that we'll have that information at the June 23rd meeting.

390
00:47:29,124 --> 00:47:30,365
[SPEAKER_14]: So that will probably be the earliest.

391
00:47:30,425 --> 00:47:34,087
[SPEAKER_14]: We'd probably be able to take a look at that type of thing.

392
00:47:35,749 --> 00:47:44,695
[SPEAKER_14]: In all reality, revenues affect the process just as much as turnbacks do, and there are other major factors as well.

393
00:47:44,795 --> 00:47:46,757
[SPEAKER_14]: So that's a very challenging thing to answer.

394
00:47:47,718 --> 00:47:53,041
[SPEAKER_14]: I don't know as though we've ever tried to answer that in the middle of the fiscal year, never mind even when the fiscal year has been closed.

395
00:47:58,197 --> 00:47:59,659
[SPEAKER_14]: That's my understanding, Councilor Sang.

396
00:47:59,679 --> 00:48:03,362
[SPEAKER_14]: You're asking how much we would close fiscal 26 in terms of cash.

397
00:48:04,423 --> 00:48:05,244
[SPEAKER_09]: Right, right, yeah.

398
00:48:08,072 --> 00:48:27,300
[SPEAKER_09]: Okay, I'm also curious about, well I think this is more of a question of the whole council, but I know councillors have brought up the idea of just the concern that we're spending a lot on legal costs, a lot on litigation, settlements.

399
00:48:27,941 --> 00:48:30,622
[SPEAKER_09]: I think a lot of us personally in

400
00:48:31,202 --> 00:48:39,290
[SPEAKER_09]: Our personal interactions with KP Law have not been the most impressed by the work product, even when it comes to just reviews of ordinances.

401
00:48:41,632 --> 00:48:54,685
[SPEAKER_09]: And I think at the last meeting it was pointed out to us that a lot of the cost for that isn't in the kind of legal department, the law department's budget, but is in kind of professional services for different departments.

402
00:48:55,393 --> 00:48:57,454
[SPEAKER_09]: for fire when they handle their cases.

403
00:48:58,495 --> 00:49:13,643
[SPEAKER_09]: We, I think, we requested from Chief of Staff Nazarian if we could see before the budget what that breakdown looked like for, I think we specified the fire department, but I was wondering if we could get that information from you guys before the budget.

404
00:49:15,150 --> 00:49:17,351
[SPEAKER_16]: Yes, I think we have that request.

405
00:49:19,711 --> 00:49:20,592
[SPEAKER_16]: We do have that request.

406
00:49:20,672 --> 00:49:26,693
[SPEAKER_16]: I know that we have broken it down in the past and just want to reiterate where we're at.

407
00:49:28,154 --> 00:49:31,915
[SPEAKER_16]: We, I think, evaluated in 24 or 25 and it was about $400,000 total that we spent on legal costs.

408
00:49:38,140 --> 00:49:41,422
[SPEAKER_16]: We evaluated about 16 communities at that time.

409
00:49:41,782 --> 00:49:48,907
[SPEAKER_16]: We were either the lowest or the second lowest in legal costs.

410
00:49:48,927 --> 00:49:59,514
[SPEAKER_16]: When we compared specifically to Malden, Malden, which is very similar to the city of Medford, is spending $1.2 million on their legal budget.

411
00:50:00,414 --> 00:50:04,377
[SPEAKER_16]: I did learn today that cities like Lowell have

412
00:50:05,608 --> 00:50:07,809
[SPEAKER_16]: 10 people in their law department.

413
00:50:07,869 --> 00:50:12,011
[SPEAKER_16]: They're spending close to two plus million on legal budgets.

414
00:50:12,551 --> 00:50:22,455
[SPEAKER_16]: We did have a couple of cases that we spent a little bit more money in fiscal year 25, 26, but we had to defend those cases.

415
00:50:23,095 --> 00:50:23,835
[SPEAKER_16]: We had to.

416
00:50:24,155 --> 00:50:31,939
[SPEAKER_16]: I know that KP Law has reviewed, and I apologize if you're not happy with the services, but they've reviewed over 20 ordinances as of recent.

417
00:50:33,305 --> 00:50:43,598
[SPEAKER_16]: for the city council, and I know they helped you with the BJ's litigation and much more, but I feel like we're getting good service.

418
00:50:47,283 --> 00:50:52,509
[SPEAKER_16]: 30 plus municipal attorneys that specialize in every different area.

419
00:50:52,749 --> 00:50:57,695
[SPEAKER_16]: I have department heads that have come to me nervous about their legal budgets getting cut.

420
00:50:58,415 --> 00:51:06,124
[SPEAKER_16]: One came to me just yesterday when I saw him on the stairs saying, I call the legal department, our legal counsel, multiple times a week.

421
00:51:06,244 --> 00:51:06,985
[SPEAKER_16]: What am I going to do?

422
00:51:09,948 --> 00:51:10,728
[SPEAKER_16]: Let us handle it.

423
00:51:10,828 --> 00:51:19,475
[SPEAKER_16]: I really hope that I can explain to the council that those services, we don't overuse, but we use them for zoning.

424
00:51:19,535 --> 00:51:22,998
[SPEAKER_16]: We use KP Law.

425
00:51:23,178 --> 00:51:31,445
[SPEAKER_16]: If we didn't have Chirin from KP Law, we would never have got a signed agreement with Transom to redevelop our underutilized lots.

426
00:51:31,465 --> 00:51:36,389
[SPEAKER_16]: On the personnel level, and I know that's where we get

427
00:51:36,848 --> 00:51:43,753
[SPEAKER_16]: You may get pushback from certain departments because we are in the business of holding people accountable.

428
00:51:44,734 --> 00:51:46,055
[SPEAKER_16]: So I know that's uncomfortable.

429
00:51:46,195 --> 00:51:49,697
[SPEAKER_16]: It's something the city wasn't used to before I came in.

430
00:51:49,737 --> 00:51:51,098
[SPEAKER_16]: There was no human resources.

431
00:51:51,839 --> 00:51:52,680
[SPEAKER_16]: And we do.

432
00:51:53,000 --> 00:51:53,580
[SPEAKER_16]: We need to.

433
00:51:54,021 --> 00:52:00,325
[SPEAKER_16]: In order to keep our residents safe, believe me, I can give you some examples.

434
00:52:00,385 --> 00:52:03,748
[SPEAKER_16]: I can send you some personnel examples tomorrow that will blow your mind.

435
00:52:04,413 --> 00:52:07,536
[SPEAKER_16]: I actually have some pictures of things we have to deal with.

436
00:52:08,877 --> 00:52:14,601
[SPEAKER_16]: Our DEI office is calling the legal department probably every other day.

437
00:52:14,621 --> 00:52:26,971
[SPEAKER_16]: It's every single department that uses, it's probably me the least if I have to be honest, but I don't know what we would do without legal services if those were taken out of the budget.

438
00:52:27,712 --> 00:52:30,073
[SPEAKER_16]: We try to negotiate the rates.

439
00:52:30,133 --> 00:52:31,815
[SPEAKER_16]: We try to negotiate the monthly retain.

440
00:52:32,175 --> 00:52:33,136
[SPEAKER_16]: the monthly retainer.

441
00:52:33,216 --> 00:52:36,639
[SPEAKER_16]: We try to be cognizant of what we're spending on legal.

442
00:52:37,760 --> 00:52:44,926
[SPEAKER_16]: We have the chief of police is in and out of court when he doesn't give a gun license and is getting sued left and right.

443
00:52:45,346 --> 00:52:48,809
[SPEAKER_16]: And Janelle from KP Law is a specialist in that area.

444
00:52:49,190 --> 00:52:51,312
[SPEAKER_16]: But I mean, the list goes on and on and on.

445
00:52:52,138 --> 00:52:55,360
[SPEAKER_09]: It'd be helpful to see what information you have for us.

446
00:52:55,801 --> 00:53:02,585
[SPEAKER_09]: I know we have the FOIA request that we all voted on, and it'd be helpful to get that as soon as possible.

447
00:53:03,886 --> 00:53:08,890
[SPEAKER_09]: I'm also curious about what the plan is to staff the city solicitor position.

448
00:53:08,930 --> 00:53:21,399
[SPEAKER_09]: I noticed that in the budget proposals, the salary's been cut, even though I think one of the kind of main reasons given for why we couldn't hire one was because of our just pay not being competitive.

449
00:53:22,822 --> 00:53:27,145
[SPEAKER_09]: What went wrong with the stability of the department?

450
00:53:28,926 --> 00:53:31,388
[SPEAKER_09]: Because I know we had one for a little bit.

451
00:53:31,588 --> 00:53:34,870
[SPEAKER_09]: And what's the plan to make it stable?

452
00:53:35,330 --> 00:53:42,215
[SPEAKER_16]: Yeah, if the council wants us to repost, I think that probably will be in the email tomorrow.

453
00:53:42,295 --> 00:53:45,878
[SPEAKER_16]: You know, if we can allow our department heads to call

454
00:53:46,645 --> 00:53:53,132
[SPEAKER_16]: an attorney that they're used to calling at Coleman and Page for fiscal year 27, we will commit to posting the job.

455
00:53:53,593 --> 00:54:01,741
[SPEAKER_16]: And if that's what the council wants as far as pushing that up to step five in the budget, I think we're amenable to doing that.

456
00:54:01,821 --> 00:54:03,423
[SPEAKER_16]: That's going to be a discussion for tomorrow.

457
00:54:04,384 --> 00:54:05,545
[SPEAKER_09]: Great.

458
00:54:05,966 --> 00:54:06,807
[SPEAKER_09]: We heard from

459
00:54:09,637 --> 00:54:11,319
[SPEAKER_09]: the library at the last meeting.

460
00:54:12,561 --> 00:54:18,348
[SPEAKER_09]: And their main priority, it seemed, and I think it's a very fair priority.

461
00:54:18,388 --> 00:54:26,698
[SPEAKER_09]: I know people have looked at librarian positions throughout the state and Medford is just, they wanted to work here and it's just not acceptable to them how much.

462
00:54:27,458 --> 00:54:28,579
[SPEAKER_09]: lower our pay was.

463
00:54:28,839 --> 00:54:33,563
[SPEAKER_09]: We heard that we're $11 per hour under regional standards.

464
00:54:33,583 --> 00:54:37,166
[SPEAKER_09]: $8 per hour got us kind of reasonably close enough to be competitive.

465
00:54:38,246 --> 00:54:42,650
[SPEAKER_09]: I believe the board of trustees might have asked for $4 an hour more.

466
00:54:43,570 --> 00:54:46,453
[SPEAKER_09]: And the kind of proposal that we got was $2 per hour more.

467
00:54:46,693 --> 00:54:49,055
[SPEAKER_09]: And the difference between $2 per hour and $4 per hour is $20,000.

468
00:54:54,964 --> 00:55:01,788
[SPEAKER_09]: I'm just curious why we went with $2 and what would get us, what would it take to get us to the $4?

469
00:55:02,849 --> 00:55:04,309
[SPEAKER_16]: That's on our list for tomorrow too.

470
00:55:04,389 --> 00:55:20,999
[SPEAKER_16]: I think going through each budget, what's on my mind, you know, of course the MedFamily Network, but the majority of what's on my mind as I chair the school committee and understand how expensive it is to fund our school department.

471
00:55:22,036 --> 00:55:28,642
[SPEAKER_16]: I think every time I look at a budget, I try to be reasonable and fair on something like increase in salaries.

472
00:55:28,722 --> 00:55:39,452
[SPEAKER_16]: That's a conversation that we also have with our human resource director to make sure we're evaluating it throughout everybody that's non-union, works part-time.

473
00:55:39,933 --> 00:55:42,255
[SPEAKER_16]: We try to make sure we're being fair and equitable.

474
00:55:44,537 --> 00:55:52,623
[SPEAKER_16]: But yes, ultimately, trying to give the schools as much as possible was, is always, is on my mind when you hear of a $2 million gap.

475
00:55:53,164 --> 00:55:55,505
[SPEAKER_16]: But that is something we're going to evaluate tomorrow.

476
00:55:55,786 --> 00:55:57,687
[SPEAKER_16]: Because we know it's a council priority.

477
00:55:57,847 --> 00:56:00,509
[SPEAKER_09]: I'm glad to hear that, that you're reevaluating it.

478
00:56:00,549 --> 00:56:06,914
[SPEAKER_09]: I'm, I guess, I am curious what metrics, like when you're evaluating these pay increases.

479
00:56:06,994 --> 00:56:11,478
[SPEAKER_09]: I think there are just certain groups of workers in the city that have historically been

480
00:56:12,940 --> 00:56:14,182
[SPEAKER_09]: I mean, massively underpaid.

481
00:56:14,202 --> 00:56:22,189
[SPEAKER_09]: I think there's an argument for all workers, of course, but, you know, paraprofessionals, library staff.

482
00:56:23,430 --> 00:56:30,276
[SPEAKER_09]: I'm curious about the metrics that are being used to evaluate what constitutes a fair increase.

483
00:56:30,877 --> 00:56:32,158
[SPEAKER_09]: What questions are you guys asking?

484
00:56:32,705 --> 00:56:43,632
[SPEAKER_16]: Yeah, I mean our HR director leads those discussions, but she will evaluate other people that are working part time for that specific one other people in the city that are working part time.

485
00:56:43,672 --> 00:56:45,793
[SPEAKER_16]: So if you're given some part timers.

486
00:56:47,027 --> 00:56:56,655
[SPEAKER_16]: 12% raise which is what I think close to what the $2 an hour is, what are you giving every other part-time employee in the city and how is that fair?

487
00:56:56,935 --> 00:57:01,839
[SPEAKER_16]: Then we have to evaluate it to our union personnel and what percentage if they're getting the 2.5%, you know,

488
00:57:05,415 --> 00:57:09,296
[SPEAKER_16]: How are they going to respond when they hear somebody else is making 11%?

489
00:57:10,396 --> 00:57:18,618
[SPEAKER_16]: But we also take a look at our comp and class study, when the positions are on our table to be reviewed.

490
00:57:19,438 --> 00:57:34,602
[SPEAKER_16]: We take into account a whole host of things, mostly led by our HR director and trying to just be reasonable, fair, based on our comp and class study and what we currently offer and provide and pay our entire staff, work staff.

491
00:57:35,362 --> 00:57:47,350
[SPEAKER_09]: Yeah, I understand looking at the percentage increases, but of course, many workers in the city are starting at a very low baseline compared to what our neighbors in the region are paying to.

492
00:57:49,760 --> 00:57:56,984
[SPEAKER_09]: I'm just saying that's something I would look at too, and I would recommend looking at when we do make those valuations.

493
00:57:58,125 --> 00:58:16,355
[SPEAKER_16]: Other than Somerville, Cambridge, and Boston, which is really hard to compete with, because Somerville, I think the share probably will be about $170 million with their budget, more than what Medford has, our classic co-op study did not include those three cities and towns, and we were in the middle ground or above for most of our salaries.

494
00:58:17,240 --> 00:58:21,844
[SPEAKER_09]: Were there any that were particularly or were low or very high?

495
00:58:22,024 --> 00:58:28,088
[SPEAKER_16]: We found that the three that we already proposed to you were the most out of whack and that's what we were trying to fix this year.

496
00:58:28,148 --> 00:58:29,930
[SPEAKER_16]: That's why you have the proposal for you.

497
00:58:30,470 --> 00:58:34,693
[SPEAKER_16]: And then over the summer and the fall we're going to be evaluating potentially adopting a new plan.

498
00:58:37,075 --> 00:58:44,179
[SPEAKER_16]: get away from the CAF system and go to a new system and, and potentially, especially if the budget allows, create another step or two for employees.

499
00:58:44,359 --> 00:58:48,381
[SPEAKER_16]: But that's gonna be our fiscal year 27 project.

500
00:58:49,021 --> 00:58:59,626
[SPEAKER_16]: But we did, we did find that those, those three were the most out of whack, which is why we we've had probably eight, eight meetings on them to try to be as fair as possible to all of our staff.

501
00:59:00,146 --> 00:59:00,967
[SPEAKER_09]: Great.

502
00:59:02,551 --> 00:59:09,997
[SPEAKER_09]: Something that I think everyone kind of agrees with in this room is the need to execute the urban forest management plan.

503
00:59:10,897 --> 00:59:19,824
[SPEAKER_09]: I think the memo that we got said that 200 trees per year isn't enough to stop canopy decline in this city.

504
00:59:19,944 --> 00:59:22,686
[SPEAKER_09]: The plan recommends reaching 400 per year by 2030.

505
00:59:27,010 --> 00:59:39,484
[SPEAKER_09]: We have been getting more plantings per year through grant funding, but the plan also recommends adding one urban forester and two laborers, which aren't in this budget.

506
00:59:41,106 --> 00:59:43,048
[SPEAKER_09]: We know the tree warden is retiring.

507
00:59:43,088 --> 00:59:43,588
[SPEAKER_09]: I think that was...

508
00:59:44,229 --> 01:00:03,045
[SPEAKER_16]: I got the tree warden retired, and I believe Tim is presenting tonight, so maybe he would be the best to answer some of these questions, but I believe we have some really good candidates, and I'm very hopeful that the new candidate will also be an arborist, which is a new requirement we added to the job description, and I think it's going to be very beneficial.

509
01:00:03,440 --> 01:00:08,243
[SPEAKER_09]: Yeah, I think that's adding the arborist requirement is a good step forward.

510
01:00:09,063 --> 01:00:19,368
[SPEAKER_09]: I think what a lot of us are kind of curious about is what the plan is to over the next three to five years reach the goals set within the plan.

511
01:00:19,769 --> 01:00:24,771
[SPEAKER_09]: It doesn't seem like there's a lot being done in this budget necessarily towards that.

512
01:00:24,911 --> 01:00:27,813
[SPEAKER_09]: Of course, we can cite tons of financial pressures.

513
01:00:28,973 --> 01:00:31,655
[SPEAKER_09]: But what's the plan for the next few years to get there?

514
01:00:32,148 --> 01:00:45,234
[SPEAKER_16]: Yeah, I mean, this year, I think we need to just right-size the department as it relates to getting a new manager and actually really managing the department we have now and getting on a good track.

515
01:00:45,994 --> 01:00:52,977
[SPEAKER_16]: I think you're going to see, moving forward, a lot of improvements and work productivity enhancements.

516
01:00:54,057 --> 01:00:56,378
[SPEAKER_16]: Start there and then we can evaluate next season.

517
01:00:56,698 --> 01:01:03,801
[SPEAKER_16]: Each year we have a list of anywhere between five and 15 new positions being requested from department heads.

518
01:01:04,041 --> 01:01:05,962
[SPEAKER_16]: So we do our best.

519
01:01:06,082 --> 01:01:09,623
[SPEAKER_16]: Last year was the rec and maybe one other.

520
01:01:09,643 --> 01:01:17,006
[SPEAKER_16]: This year we're adding the three or four salaries that have percentages that were covered by ARPA plus all our contracts.

521
01:01:17,566 --> 01:01:21,668
[SPEAKER_16]: So we're trying to squeeze in a whole lot into one pot of money.

522
01:01:23,846 --> 01:01:31,908
[SPEAKER_09]: I'm also curious, shifting to the inclusion specialists that we've recommended in our budget recommendations.

523
01:01:32,409 --> 01:01:40,951
[SPEAKER_09]: I also noticed that in the, the school's budget for tonight, and we can get to the school's part with the schools.

524
01:01:42,411 --> 01:01:44,972
[SPEAKER_09]: That there was, there's vacancies are just not.

525
01:01:45,540 --> 01:01:52,502
[SPEAKER_09]: positions not funded that we would like to see, that I think the community would like to see with regards to inclusion.

526
01:01:53,762 --> 01:01:58,683
[SPEAKER_09]: Of course, when we talk about inclusion specialists, a lot of that's very different from what DEI does.

527
01:02:00,043 --> 01:02:11,386
[SPEAKER_09]: And I think that's why we want to see investment into that as well to make sure that kids are participating in society and schools, that residents are participating in society and schools.

528
01:02:11,746 --> 01:02:15,127
[SPEAKER_09]: What's the plan to get us to staff those needs?

529
01:02:16,608 --> 01:02:32,739
[SPEAKER_16]: I've been conversating through email with Councilor Lemming a bit over the last few days and there's opportunity, I think, to potentially add a bit to the rec department to take care of one of his concerns.

530
01:02:34,068 --> 01:02:35,589
[SPEAKER_16]: add more inclusive programming.

531
01:02:35,649 --> 01:02:40,331
[SPEAKER_16]: So we're going to take a look at that tomorrow because we know it's a priority of the council.

532
01:02:41,772 --> 01:02:48,515
[SPEAKER_16]: I don't, Kevin has now two additional staff members that he's managing as well.

533
01:02:48,696 --> 01:02:54,218
[SPEAKER_16]: So I think a gradual approach to that is the way we're going to be able to handle it.

534
01:02:54,959 --> 01:03:02,903
[SPEAKER_16]: Adding 100,000 new position, I just, I can't, it's hard when you know that there's a deficit in the school department's budget.

535
01:03:04,296 --> 01:03:05,436
[SPEAKER_09]: I've asked a lot of questions.

536
01:03:05,717 --> 01:03:10,218
[SPEAKER_09]: I guess my last one will hopefully put us on topic for later tonight.

537
01:03:12,859 --> 01:03:15,579
[SPEAKER_09]: We've been talking about the gap for the schools.

538
01:03:15,979 --> 01:03:18,500
[SPEAKER_09]: I think it's all over 2 million.

539
01:03:18,520 --> 01:03:21,181
[SPEAKER_09]: 2.18 is the number I have.

540
01:03:21,321 --> 01:03:24,562
[SPEAKER_09]: But if the city doesn't close that gap,

541
01:03:26,821 --> 01:03:33,946
[SPEAKER_09]: that the public schools has indicated that it's going to need to revisit high school staffing and special education para positions.

542
01:03:36,568 --> 01:03:40,871
[SPEAKER_09]: What is, if we don't fund it, that gap, what's the alternative?

543
01:03:40,951 --> 01:03:46,615
[SPEAKER_09]: How do we prevent these layoffs and how do we stay true to what voters voted for in 2024?

544
01:03:49,447 --> 01:04:01,291
[SPEAKER_16]: Yeah, we don't have $2 million to close the gap, so I'm open to suggestions now that you, after tonight, you would have reviewed all the city budgets, I believe.

545
01:04:02,471 --> 01:04:08,713
[SPEAKER_16]: So I'd look for suggestions from the council on where you might wanna reallocate money.

546
01:04:09,591 --> 01:04:18,399
[SPEAKER_16]: We've done, I mean, I'm getting heat for some of the things that I've cut and I'm trying to be thoughtful and considerate and fair across the board.

547
01:04:20,741 --> 01:04:30,629
[SPEAKER_16]: It's not easy and it's not comfortable, but we're doing the work and we're, you know, doing our best to try to explain it to all of our department heads.

548
01:04:31,894 --> 01:04:45,580
[SPEAKER_16]: explain the rationale, but cities and towns are struggling, and increases in costs and expenses, like I mentioned before, we're doing the absolute best we can.

549
01:04:50,398 --> 01:04:52,820
[SPEAKER_09]: I'll let other counselors speak.

550
01:04:52,880 --> 01:04:54,741
[SPEAKER_09]: I know I've monopolized a lot of time.

551
01:04:55,121 --> 01:04:59,284
[SPEAKER_09]: Of course, the questions are on the list, but we can always chat offline too.

552
01:04:59,504 --> 01:05:00,525
[SPEAKER_16]: Yes, absolutely.

553
01:05:00,825 --> 01:05:02,646
[SPEAKER_16]: I'll email you tomorrow and we can set up a time.

