[SPEAKER_05]: In the budget ordinance, something that we talked about was quarterly financial meetings and seeing the warrants regularly.

563
01:05:48,684 --> 01:05:49,905
[SPEAKER_05]: We haven't been able to keep that up.

564
01:05:50,005 --> 01:05:51,906
[SPEAKER_05]: We only did that I think for Q1 this year.

565
01:05:53,547 --> 01:05:54,728
[SPEAKER_05]: I'd have to go back and look at my email.

566
01:05:54,768 --> 01:05:56,029
[SPEAKER_05]: Maybe we got something for Q2.

567
01:05:56,049 --> 01:05:56,509
[SPEAKER_05]: I'm not 100% sure.

568
01:05:56,529 --> 01:05:56,569
[SPEAKER_05]: So.

569
01:06:03,315 --> 01:06:05,977
[SPEAKER_16]: And we can talk to our CFO about that.

570
01:06:06,177 --> 01:06:11,461
[SPEAKER_05]: Yeah, and I get there's capacity issues across the city and city government, but I think.

571
01:06:12,274 --> 01:06:19,880
[SPEAKER_05]: I think the reason why we are where we are now asking the questions that we were asking about the law department budget is those costs are spread out.

572
01:06:20,260 --> 01:06:22,542
[SPEAKER_05]: It seems those costs are spread out across different departments.

573
01:06:22,562 --> 01:06:28,206
[SPEAKER_05]: When we talked to the chief, he said the actuals in his professional services line reflected some legal costs.

574
01:06:28,266 --> 01:06:32,249
[SPEAKER_05]: When we've heard, you know, from you tonight, other departments are using legal costs.

575
01:06:32,269 --> 01:06:36,373
[SPEAKER_05]: So, you know, the law department budget,

576
01:06:37,191 --> 01:06:44,315
[SPEAKER_05]: when it was, when most of the things were happening in that budget, that budget reflected the cost of our legal services.

577
01:06:46,377 --> 01:06:50,999
[SPEAKER_05]: It seems now that those costs are kind of all over the city budget, across different departments.

578
01:06:51,139 --> 01:06:57,864
[SPEAKER_05]: It's hard to pull that information together to understand it, and that's just before we even get to, you know, potential settlements.

579
01:06:58,984 --> 01:07:04,928
[SPEAKER_05]: We don't have the information you have about, in many cases, about certain decisions, right?

580
01:07:05,048 --> 01:07:06,229
[SPEAKER_05]: But it does seem when we hear

581
01:07:09,149 --> 01:07:19,076
[SPEAKER_05]: hear from folks that arbitrations were lost, settlements were happening, and we don't understand where that's coming from in the budget because we're not seeing the warrants on a quarterly basis.

582
01:07:19,116 --> 01:07:20,757
[SPEAKER_05]: We're not having those update meetings.

583
01:07:21,237 --> 01:07:23,379
[SPEAKER_05]: It's spread across the ledger.

584
01:07:24,860 --> 01:07:28,483
[SPEAKER_05]: I think we end up in the place where we are now where we have kind of a trust deficit.

585
01:07:29,143 --> 01:07:32,246
[SPEAKER_05]: And, you know, I think even when we looked

586
01:07:34,343 --> 01:07:44,688
[SPEAKER_05]: I remember sitting, I think, here in 2024 and saying, well, we're not doing end of year transfers, so the law budget is a law budget.

587
01:07:44,748 --> 01:07:46,408
[SPEAKER_05]: I was saying that to George, right?

588
01:07:47,729 --> 01:07:56,993
[SPEAKER_05]: And since then, it seems that I think I was maybe wrong about that, about exactly what our legal costs are, what the exposure is.

589
01:07:57,033 --> 01:07:59,474
[SPEAKER_05]: And I think a lot of that comes to, you know,

590
01:08:00,652 --> 01:08:23,932
[SPEAKER_05]: a breakdown in the process and the information sharing and in some cases the way that information is compiled, which is I think why we put such an admittedly robust request upon you guys for legal information was to say let's get it all together and then we can have a full understanding of what the picture is there.

591
01:08:25,862 --> 01:08:30,725
[SPEAKER_05]: And I really think it goes back to some process issues around just we don't have the information that we would want to see.

592
01:08:30,785 --> 01:08:34,068
[SPEAKER_05]: So I understand a lot of departments use legal services.

593
01:08:35,529 --> 01:08:47,477
[SPEAKER_05]: There's I think seven different opinions on this council about our different individual interactions with different individuals like KP on different projects and depending on, you know,

594
01:08:48,715 --> 01:08:50,717
[SPEAKER_05]: a lot of different factors on how that's gone.

595
01:08:50,737 --> 01:08:54,140
[SPEAKER_05]: I've certainly had some good work done with some folks at KP.

596
01:08:54,200 --> 01:08:57,583
[SPEAKER_05]: I also have had a bunch of issues with some of the projects that we've worked on, right?

597
01:09:01,346 --> 01:09:04,950
[SPEAKER_05]: I don't want to see us in a situation where we're going a month to month on a law department budget.

598
01:09:05,010 --> 01:09:07,012
[SPEAKER_05]: I don't think that's work that any of us want to be doing.

599
01:09:07,112 --> 01:09:16,060
[SPEAKER_05]: But I think what Councilor Seng was kind of trying to get out there and what I think many of the councilors have said is with the information breakdown, we don't have the information we need.

600
01:09:17,000 --> 01:09:19,344
[SPEAKER_05]: to actually understand really what we're approving, right?

601
01:09:20,105 --> 01:09:23,530
[SPEAKER_05]: So I just wanted to say that was one and a half points.

602
01:09:23,811 --> 01:09:26,755
[SPEAKER_05]: And now I have more of a point and the other two are more questions.

603
01:09:26,775 --> 01:09:30,782
[SPEAKER_05]: But I just wanted to kind of provide some more context on that and maybe we can get somewhere.

604
01:09:30,802 --> 01:09:32,144
[SPEAKER_05]: And I'll pause if you want to.

605
01:09:32,826 --> 01:09:34,988
[SPEAKER_16]: Yeah, no, I appreciate your comments.

606
01:09:35,068 --> 01:09:37,130
[SPEAKER_16]: Thank you, President Behrs.

607
01:09:37,530 --> 01:09:40,792
[SPEAKER_16]: We don't have anything to hide.

608
01:09:42,154 --> 01:09:49,099
[SPEAKER_16]: We do run any settlement by the council that's over $2,500 and we get approval from you.

609
01:09:49,159 --> 01:09:51,181
[SPEAKER_16]: I don't even think it's the law, but we do it.

610
01:09:51,221 --> 01:09:52,982
[SPEAKER_16]: We want to be transparent and open.

611
01:09:54,403 --> 01:09:58,347
[SPEAKER_16]: We've been able to negotiate some large, large claims down to

612
01:09:58,990 --> 01:10:06,556
[SPEAKER_16]: what I consider almost pennies compared to what the claims were demanding initially through good legal representation.

613
01:10:07,276 --> 01:10:10,559
[SPEAKER_16]: We have been asking department heads for many years to

614
01:10:13,168 --> 01:10:22,573
[SPEAKER_16]: pay for what they're using from either KP or Jonathan Silverstein for the zoning or any other attorney a department may use.

615
01:10:23,474 --> 01:10:31,038
[SPEAKER_16]: Other than the retainer and maybe some other funding that we may have in the law department budget, we have been doing that for several years.

616
01:10:31,178 --> 01:10:34,120
[SPEAKER_16]: It's the reason why when we evaluated it in 2023 and 2024, 2023, 2024,

617
01:10:37,549 --> 01:10:38,810
[SPEAKER_16]: We did compile that number.

618
01:10:39,230 --> 01:10:41,392
[SPEAKER_16]: One of those years, it was that 400,000.

619
01:10:41,572 --> 01:10:47,496
[SPEAKER_16]: That was compiled not just from the law budget, but from every department that spent money on legal fees.

620
01:10:48,516 --> 01:10:52,359
[SPEAKER_16]: We're not trying to not be transparent.

621
01:10:52,399 --> 01:10:57,142
[SPEAKER_16]: I think that every city and town is spending money on legal fees.

622
01:10:57,282 --> 01:11:03,206
[SPEAKER_16]: Every city and town is getting sued, and we're left defending these claims.

623
01:11:03,706 --> 01:11:05,868
[SPEAKER_16]: But it would be detrimental to us if we

624
01:11:06,388 --> 01:11:09,950
[SPEAKER_16]: We're not able to continue doing that into the new fiscal year.

625
01:11:10,391 --> 01:11:13,813
[SPEAKER_16]: So we have the public record request, I think.

626
01:11:14,403 --> 01:11:25,130
[SPEAKER_16]: Nina has the amount of documents that it's producing and how long it's going to take some of us to do, mainly our administrative assistant in the law department.

627
01:11:25,850 --> 01:11:32,014
[SPEAKER_16]: We will provide those to you on as much as we can do either each week or biweekly.

628
01:11:32,635 --> 01:11:39,199
[SPEAKER_16]: We just are not going to be able to get that done by, I mean, it's going to take months.

629
01:11:41,270 --> 01:11:44,553
[SPEAKER_16]: If you pull every claim, and yeah, it's going to take months.

630
01:11:45,034 --> 01:11:45,214
[SPEAKER_05]: Right.

631
01:11:45,254 --> 01:11:56,004
[SPEAKER_05]: And I think, you know, it'll take months for you to pull it and then probably weeks and months for us to then take it all and reassess it and put it into the informational format that we want to understand the information.

632
01:11:56,024 --> 01:12:03,290
[SPEAKER_05]: And I think I said this to Chief of Staff Nazarian, like, there's an alternative here based on the original resolution, which is

633
01:12:05,112 --> 01:12:10,093
[SPEAKER_05]: putting together a report so that we can see all the information in the way that we need to see it.

634
01:12:10,854 --> 01:12:33,040
[SPEAKER_05]: And I think, you know, something that has changed for me, I won't speak for anyone else on the council, is just, I think, a number of announcements, certainly by people making claims against the city that, you know, the city has lost a very significant arbitration or claim, right?

635
01:12:36,092 --> 01:12:38,934
[SPEAKER_05]: maybe the city's appealing, you know, what is that gonna cost?

636
01:12:39,075 --> 01:12:54,508
[SPEAKER_05]: And if there's elements of this that need to be discussed in executive session or elements of this that you don't think can be discussed with us, I think we need to find a way that we can be communicated about because we see sticker shock in a lot of the announcements about the cost of legal services to the city.

637
01:12:55,889 --> 01:13:00,653
[SPEAKER_05]: And without, I think coming up with some sort of

638
01:13:01,860 --> 01:13:12,072
[SPEAKER_05]: regular and clear process to kind of create the report that we were asking for back in January or February, we could maybe alleviate some of the questions around the public records.

639
01:13:12,112 --> 01:13:14,134
[SPEAKER_05]: Obviously, the clock is ticking on that, right?

640
01:13:14,214 --> 01:13:14,454
[SPEAKER_05]: So.

641
01:13:14,474 --> 01:13:14,935
[SPEAKER_05]: Yeah.

642
01:13:15,736 --> 01:13:19,420
[SPEAKER_16]: Yeah, we have to focus on that by law so where we just kind of put our energy

643
01:13:20,813 --> 01:13:37,588
[SPEAKER_16]: what we have left of energy after doing the budget and zoning and Memphis Square, all that with the public records request because then we had to ask for an extension and it's been a lot of work trying to figure out how long that's going to take.

644
01:13:38,128 --> 01:13:45,514
[SPEAKER_16]: All I'll add is that when we win a case or I settle a case, we had a case that

645
01:13:46,707 --> 01:13:51,549
[SPEAKER_16]: The demand was about $1.5 million, and then I settled.

646
01:13:51,569 --> 01:13:55,150
[SPEAKER_16]: It took a year, but I settled it for $28,000.

647
01:13:55,550 --> 01:13:57,911
[SPEAKER_16]: I don't go on film and boast about it.

648
01:13:58,271 --> 01:14:02,733
[SPEAKER_16]: We might tell you in executive session, but I'm not going to say, look what we did.

649
01:14:02,773 --> 01:14:05,194
[SPEAKER_16]: Look how much we saved the city in claim money.

650
01:14:05,954 --> 01:14:09,956
[SPEAKER_16]: But yeah, you do have at least one union

651
01:14:14,217 --> 01:14:15,797
[SPEAKER_16]: representation that does.

652
01:14:16,077 --> 01:14:16,738
[SPEAKER_16]: They make videos.

653
01:14:16,818 --> 01:14:26,860
[SPEAKER_16]: So no, we do not win every case, but we are working tirelessly to try to keep costs down and negotiate settlements real hard.

654
01:14:26,880 --> 01:14:41,582
[SPEAKER_16]: I might, you know, I get depoed and instead of settling sometimes, I would rather go through a one, two, or three-day depo of myself because I know that it's going to lead to what is best for the community.

655
01:14:42,403 --> 01:14:43,863
[SPEAKER_16]: So yes, no, I'm not boasting about

656
01:14:44,703 --> 01:14:45,704
[SPEAKER_16]: good negotiations.

657
01:14:45,744 --> 01:14:47,425
[SPEAKER_16]: I'm not boasting about anything we win.

658
01:14:47,785 --> 01:14:52,488
