01:35:49,724 --> 01:35:52,327
[SPEAKER_05]: How did you hear that?

884
01:35:52,367 --> 01:35:53,448
[SPEAKER_05]: Is that the ice cream truck or?

885
01:35:56,531 --> 01:36:00,213
[SPEAKER_05]: Someone projecting calming music into the chambers.

886
01:36:02,015 --> 01:36:03,055
[SPEAKER_05]: We'll start with parking.

887
01:36:03,275 --> 01:36:06,017
[SPEAKER_05]: We have our parking director, Sarah McDermott, with us.

888
01:36:07,618 --> 01:36:10,820
[SPEAKER_05]: Thank you for being here on our last preliminary budget meeting.

889
01:36:14,733 --> 01:36:16,054
[SPEAKER_05]: have kind of a series of questions.

890
01:36:16,094 --> 01:36:17,055
[SPEAKER_05]: I know you've been here before.

891
01:36:17,095 --> 01:36:21,558
[SPEAKER_05]: I think you've probably watched some of the, maybe watched some of our budget hearings that are captivating.

892
01:36:21,818 --> 01:36:23,219
[SPEAKER_18]: I watched a little bit of last week's.

893
01:36:23,439 --> 01:36:24,400
[SPEAKER_05]: Yeah.

894
01:36:24,840 --> 01:36:26,701
[SPEAKER_18]: Get a little prepared, hopefully.

895
01:36:27,022 --> 01:36:27,282
[SPEAKER_05]: Great.

896
01:36:28,162 --> 01:36:30,764
[SPEAKER_05]: Basically, the questions that we'd like to go through are,

897
01:36:32,285 --> 01:36:38,690
[SPEAKER_05]: What are the differences between last year's budget and this year's budget, or fiscal 26 and fiscal 27?

898
01:36:40,111 --> 01:36:42,493
[SPEAKER_05]: What are some of the highlights from this year fiscal 26?

899
01:36:42,994 --> 01:36:45,375
[SPEAKER_05]: What are some of your plans for next year fiscal 27?

900
01:36:46,056 --> 01:36:52,421
[SPEAKER_05]: And what are some items that you believe your department needs that weren't able to be funded in this upcoming proposed budget?

901
01:36:54,142 --> 01:36:55,583
[SPEAKER_19]: Okay, so to begin,

902
01:36:58,212 --> 01:37:14,674
[SPEAKER_19]: we have some we have a net increase to well it's not a net increase to the whole thing um but we have the we have some employees most of my employees have been with the city for several years so we have the their raises their

903
01:37:16,816 --> 01:37:19,598
[SPEAKER_19]: So that's all accounted for.

904
01:37:20,698 --> 01:37:26,582
[SPEAKER_19]: One item that went up is our professional services, which I know seems to be a common theme.

905
01:37:27,102 --> 01:37:33,366
[SPEAKER_19]: So my professional services line item pays for our parking management system, GTECNA.

906
01:37:33,826 --> 01:37:40,110
[SPEAKER_19]: It pays IPS, who manages our meters, our multi-space meters and our single-space meters.

907
01:37:40,650 --> 01:37:45,531
[SPEAKER_19]: and it also pays our merchant processing fees, which are fees associated with credit card transactions.

908
01:37:47,632 --> 01:37:59,916
[SPEAKER_19]: The contracts we have in place with G-TechNet and with IPS, the more productive my staff are with producing citations and selling permits, the higher our costs are.

909
01:38:02,217 --> 01:38:05,559
[SPEAKER_19]: Our contract with GTechna right now, we pay a dollar.

910
01:38:05,579 --> 01:38:12,084
[SPEAKER_19]: Every time one of my staff writes a citation or the police department writes a citation, that costs us a dollar, and that's invoiced monthly.

911
01:38:12,605 --> 01:38:17,729
[SPEAKER_19]: Every time GTechna sends a letter because a citation is late, that gets invoiced monthly.

912
01:38:18,089 --> 01:38:19,010
[SPEAKER_19]: There's a cost to it.

913
01:38:19,911 --> 01:38:22,813
[SPEAKER_19]: Every time we sell a permit online or in the office, it costs us $2.

914
01:38:22,893 --> 01:38:24,034
[SPEAKER_19]: So those items are

915
01:38:25,755 --> 01:38:26,816
[SPEAKER_19]: somewhat unpredictable.

916
01:38:26,997 --> 01:38:29,739
[SPEAKER_19]: The more that we sell, the more tickets we issue.

917
01:38:29,759 --> 01:38:32,342
[SPEAKER_19]: And I'm sorry, let me just backtrack.

918
01:38:32,462 --> 01:38:38,188
[SPEAKER_19]: IPS has a standard rate we pay each month for each of our multispace meter kiosks.

919
01:38:38,549 --> 01:38:42,073
[SPEAKER_19]: And in addition to that, we pay a small fee for every transaction.

920
01:38:42,793 --> 01:38:48,035
[SPEAKER_19]: So all of these costs are based on the activity that we see.

921
01:38:48,255 --> 01:38:56,518
[SPEAKER_19]: So what I usually do, what I did last year and what I also did this year was get the average of the past year and find the average per month and budget for that.

922
01:38:57,518 --> 01:39:04,240
[SPEAKER_19]: But this year we've, my staff has been quite more, quite a bit more productive at least in issuing citations.

923
01:39:06,181 --> 01:39:08,902
[SPEAKER_19]: So the costs have gone up and also there, there are,

924
01:39:09,742 --> 01:39:10,543
[SPEAKER_19]: A couple of costs.

925
01:39:10,563 --> 01:39:13,925
[SPEAKER_19]: The $1 per ticket and the $2 per permit are contracted.

926
01:39:13,965 --> 01:39:16,207
[SPEAKER_19]: Those rates won't go up while we're under contract.

927
01:39:16,747 --> 01:39:23,252
[SPEAKER_19]: But there are other costs for mailing letters and for their online permitting system have gone up slightly so that I

928
01:39:24,624 --> 01:39:34,628
[SPEAKER_19]: looked at the average number of transactions for the last year and budgeted for an increase based on the price, the new prices they gave me, and that amounted to about $4,400, just the price increase.

929
01:39:36,829 --> 01:39:43,131
[SPEAKER_19]: And regretfully, last year I did not account for the merchant processing fees properly.

930
01:39:43,712 --> 01:39:49,674
[SPEAKER_19]: I misjudged what they would cost, and I did not budget for them properly last year, but that I have

931
01:39:52,032 --> 01:39:56,553
[SPEAKER_19]: figured out and accounted for better this year than I did last year.

932
01:39:57,533 --> 01:39:59,334
[SPEAKER_19]: A little bit about those merchant processing fees.

933
01:39:59,374 --> 01:40:06,976
[SPEAKER_19]: We used to use a company called Heartland, and for every transaction they would charge a small fee, every credit card transaction to be specific.

934
01:40:08,136 --> 01:40:15,798
[SPEAKER_19]: And I've subsequently switched our IPS transactions to another company called AMG, and that saved the city

935
01:40:16,638 --> 01:40:31,130
[SPEAKER_19]: literally thousands of dollars since I switched because it was before Heartland would take about 25% of every transaction, every credit card transaction, as a merchant processing fee, which is outrageous.

936
01:40:31,571 --> 01:40:34,433
[SPEAKER_19]: And so I switched to AMG, and currently it's about 10%.

937
01:40:35,634 --> 01:40:39,718
[SPEAKER_19]: So about 10% of the revenue that is credit card-based, not cash.

938
01:40:41,280 --> 01:40:43,203
[SPEAKER_19]: Now goes to merchant processing as opposed to 25%.

939
01:40:44,325 --> 01:40:50,995
[SPEAKER_19]: So these numbers I budgeted for are based on the averages and those averages including the cost of heartland.

940
01:40:51,596 --> 01:40:53,639
[SPEAKER_19]: So they should be lower than what I've.

941
01:40:54,844 --> 01:40:59,388
[SPEAKER_19]: predicted, given that we don't have a huge uptick in people parking at the meters.

942
01:40:59,989 --> 01:41:08,556
[SPEAKER_19]: I'm working with G-Techno to switch them from Heartland to AMG as well for more cost savings there with our credit card processing fees.

943
01:41:08,936 --> 01:41:11,538
[SPEAKER_19]: In addition to that, switching to AMG allowed our

944
01:41:12,600 --> 01:41:17,145
[SPEAKER_19]: the people who use our meters and kiosks to pay with American Express, which they weren't able to do before.

945
01:41:17,726 --> 01:41:24,855
[SPEAKER_19]: So that was substantially, that made a big difference because that was something that the people wanted.

946
01:41:27,338 --> 01:41:43,511
[SPEAKER_19]: So that's probably the biggest increase is the professional services, was at 4,400 from the price increase from GTECNA and then my own budgeting, the merchant processing fees, where I did not do that properly last year.

947
01:41:44,151 --> 01:41:47,614
[SPEAKER_19]: So that accounted for, I believe, 25,740 in the professional services line.

948
01:41:51,877 --> 01:42:09,325
[SPEAKER_19]: I made cuts from some of the other items in our ordinary expenses because this past year I took over cell phone payments for all of our handheld devices and our city issued cell phones that were previously being paid for by the Medford Police Department.

949
01:42:11,026 --> 01:42:14,007
[SPEAKER_19]: We estimated last year that it would be about $5,800 per year.

950
01:42:14,367 --> 01:42:19,610
[SPEAKER_19]: The actual costs were substantially less than that, so now we can go with about $4,000, so that saved about $1,800.

951
01:42:20,850 --> 01:42:24,932
[SPEAKER_19]: Supplies, clothing budget was higher than we've needed the last couple of years.

952
01:42:25,352 --> 01:42:31,114
[SPEAKER_19]: A couple of the other line items were higher than we really used, so we made some small cuts there.

953
01:42:33,355 --> 01:42:35,536
[SPEAKER_19]: I say small, but it was actually pretty substantial.

954
01:42:38,097 --> 01:42:38,557
[SPEAKER_19]: It looks like 12.

955
01:42:42,134 --> 01:42:46,216
[SPEAKER_19]: It looks like around 15 or 16,000 from the other line items.

956
01:42:47,616 --> 01:42:56,620
[SPEAKER_19]: Which doesn't completely offset the cost of professional services, but it will help balance that out a little bit, I think.

957
01:43:00,856 --> 01:43:09,843
[SPEAKER_19]: Another thing I'm looking to do, so I currently am creating an RFP because our contract with GTechNA expires in December of 2026.

958
01:43:11,605 --> 01:43:17,870
[SPEAKER_19]: And overall, I know that from what I've heard from the Memphis Police Department, they're not quite satisfied with that company.

959
01:43:18,691 --> 01:43:24,536
[SPEAKER_19]: And I'm also, I've heard from residents who order their permits online that they do not like GTechNA's system.

960
01:43:25,877 --> 01:43:36,064
[SPEAKER_19]: And I've had a few, I've had a few issues with them myself where they have tried to invoice me for things that specifically they tried to invoice me to switch to AMG.

961
01:43:37,546 --> 01:43:40,828
[SPEAKER_19]: And when I gave them some pushback, they were like, okay, fine, just you won't have to take.

962
01:43:40,888 --> 01:43:42,930
[SPEAKER_19]: So, so I have a feeling that they, they,

963
01:43:44,620 --> 01:43:52,248
[SPEAKER_19]: I just get the impression that they want to charge us for things they shouldn't be charging us for, and it causes me a little bit of distrust with them, so I'm seeking a better company.

964
01:43:52,849 --> 01:44:00,958
[SPEAKER_19]: I know that a neighboring city just switched from a company that was owned by the parent company of GTechNA

965
01:44:01,448 --> 01:44:07,171
[SPEAKER_19]: to a more local company and they're incredibly happy with the price and with the service they've gotten so far.

966
01:44:07,331 --> 01:44:20,977
[SPEAKER_19]: So I know there's, there's opportunities out there for us to improve not only the price of the service, but the service to the residents who do get frustrated every year come renewal time that they can't easily just reorder a permit and call it a day.

967
01:44:21,217 --> 01:44:23,598
[SPEAKER_19]: It turns into a much larger process sometimes.

968
01:44:26,437 --> 01:44:32,922
[SPEAKER_19]: So that's, that's a goal for this year, is to find somebody to take over.

969
01:44:33,362 --> 01:44:42,509
[SPEAKER_19]: And if, if I'm proven wrong and GTechNet is still the best service provider at the best price, then we'll stick with them and re-sign, probably not for five years like we did originally.

970
01:44:42,709 --> 01:44:49,794
[SPEAKER_19]: But it's still, that still remains to be seen, but that's something that's, that's a big thing on the horizon for us.

971
01:44:52,312 --> 01:44:53,718
[SPEAKER_19]: what I would like to see.

972
01:44:53,738 --> 01:44:55,947
[SPEAKER_19]: I mean, what I would have liked to see.

973
01:44:57,177 --> 01:45:04,400
[SPEAKER_19]: What I'd like to see is more people on the streets writing tickets, because I get a lot of complaints from residents that there are not enough people out there.

974
01:45:05,000 --> 01:45:12,023
[SPEAKER_19]: But I also have to admit that I think the staff we have already still has potential for improvement.

975
01:45:12,603 --> 01:45:26,068
[SPEAKER_19]: So I believe that's one reason, and it's just my belief, that's one reason why I've had an open position we have yet to fill, because there's still potential to see what output the current staff can do

976
01:45:27,507 --> 01:45:35,070
[SPEAKER_19]: with a little bit more training, a little bit more encouragement to, and a little, I say a little bit more encouragement, but what I really mean is a little more training.

977
01:45:35,310 --> 01:45:36,931
[SPEAKER_19]: I think that there's room for improvement there.

978
01:45:36,991 --> 01:45:40,952
[SPEAKER_19]: So, but that being said, from between, and,

979
01:45:43,033 --> 01:45:48,755
[SPEAKER_19]: In the 2024 calendar year, the total number of citations issued between my department and the police department was 19,448.

980
01:45:48,795 --> 01:45:52,436
[SPEAKER_19]: And in 2025, the total number of citations issued between our two departments were 27,348.

981
01:45:52,476 --> 01:45:53,997
[SPEAKER_19]: So that's a 40% increase in citations.

982
01:46:04,970 --> 01:46:08,252
[SPEAKER_19]: 40% increase in every time, you know, how much I have to pay a dollar every month.

983
01:46:08,372 --> 01:46:12,195
[SPEAKER_19]: So the costs, as we get more productive under this current contract, do go up.

984
01:46:12,695 --> 01:46:20,820
[SPEAKER_19]: So I've budgeted for averages, but if my staff continues to improve and be more productive, the costs may go up higher.

985
01:46:20,840 --> 01:46:26,323
[SPEAKER_19]: Is that a good place to stop and ask for questions?

986
01:46:27,684 --> 01:46:27,884
[SPEAKER_05]: Yes.

987
01:46:28,285 --> 01:46:28,605
[SPEAKER_19]: Thank you.

988
01:46:29,565 --> 01:46:30,586
[SPEAKER_05]: Thank you for the presentation.

989
01:46:30,606 --> 01:46:33,068
[SPEAKER_05]: My only other question is if you could share,

990
01:46:34,406 --> 01:46:37,668
[SPEAKER_05]: at some point, kind of the revenue for the fiscal year for the department, you know.

991
01:46:37,688 --> 01:46:37,928
[SPEAKER_07]: Sure.

992
01:46:38,929 --> 01:46:40,429
[SPEAKER_05]: And then I'll go to my fellow counselors.

993
01:46:43,951 --> 01:46:44,532
[SPEAKER_18]: I have it.

994
01:46:48,426 --> 01:46:56,431
[SPEAKER_19]: So as of the end of April, because I don't have the deposits for May just yet, but as of the end of April, the total deposits are $1,704,570.07.

995
01:46:56,471 --> 01:46:58,553
[SPEAKER_19]: And that's still with May and June revenue yet to be accounted for.

996
