02:03:00,279 --> 02:03:00,999
[SPEAKER_13]: Thank you very much.

1202
02:03:01,019 --> 02:03:02,180
[SPEAKER_13]: I just had a question.

1203
02:03:03,601 --> 02:03:12,145
[SPEAKER_13]: On the weapons apparatus stipend, it looks like it was budgeted for 58 and it's again for 58 but there's no actuals in there.

1204
02:03:12,886 --> 02:03:13,126
[SPEAKER_13]: Is that?

1205
02:03:14,951 --> 02:03:15,472
[SPEAKER_06]: We'll say that again?

1206
02:03:15,892 --> 02:03:26,677
[SPEAKER_13]: For the weapons apparatus stipend that it looks like it was budgeted for 58 and again for 58, 600, I know it's a slight increase, but there's no actuals.

1207
02:03:26,697 --> 02:03:29,038
[SPEAKER_13]: Does that come in towards the end of the fiscal year?

1208
02:03:30,599 --> 02:03:30,839
[SPEAKER_06]: Yes.

1209
02:03:31,419 --> 02:03:32,400
[SPEAKER_06]: That is in June.

1210
02:03:32,940 --> 02:03:33,420
[SPEAKER_13]: Okay.

1211
02:03:33,540 --> 02:03:39,523
[SPEAKER_06]: And it's a flat stipend depending on whether it's a superior officer or a patrol officer.

1212
02:03:40,184 --> 02:03:41,464
[SPEAKER_06]: The amounts are different.

1213
02:03:42,025 --> 02:03:42,305
[SPEAKER_13]: Okay.

1214
02:03:42,645 --> 02:03:42,845
[SPEAKER_13]: Great.

1215
02:03:43,640 --> 02:03:50,746
[SPEAKER_13]: And then I think the other question I had was around the contracts, but I think you all explained that already, so thank you.

1216
02:03:52,268 --> 02:03:52,588
[SPEAKER_05]: Thank you.

1217
02:03:52,608 --> 02:03:53,529
[SPEAKER_05]: Vice President Lazaro.

1218
02:03:55,551 --> 02:03:55,991
[SPEAKER_17]: Thank you.

1219
02:03:56,011 --> 02:04:03,618
[SPEAKER_17]: I just want to draw attention to the fact that I believe that there was a $2.4 million deficit.

1220
02:04:05,019 --> 02:04:09,023
[SPEAKER_17]: Madam Chief of Staff, would you mind clarifying for me what the deficit is that

1221
02:04:11,629 --> 02:04:14,896
[SPEAKER_17]: We keep talking about how much is the deficit for this budget this year?

1222
02:04:22,074 --> 02:04:22,955
[SPEAKER_14]: That is correct.

1223
02:04:23,135 --> 02:04:25,777
[SPEAKER_17]: That's just like kind of uncanny.

1224
02:04:26,438 --> 02:04:29,460
[SPEAKER_17]: It's the exact amount that is that the police budget has gone up.

1225
02:04:29,520 --> 02:04:35,425
[SPEAKER_17]: So it's interesting that we there was no so like you knew that you guys knew this was coming because the contract was negotiated.

1226
02:04:36,125 --> 02:04:42,830
[SPEAKER_17]: And then there what we have to cut is the schools and the library and the city council budget and every other department.

1227
02:04:43,451 --> 02:04:50,136
[SPEAKER_17]: And to pay for the police budget that was contractually negotiated knowingly.

1228
02:04:51,977 --> 02:04:54,919
[SPEAKER_17]: I mean, can you explain why that happened that way?

1229
02:04:57,581 --> 02:05:04,026
[SPEAKER_14]: The contractual process is such that the city had been in negotiations.

1230
02:05:04,086 --> 02:05:05,688
[SPEAKER_14]: I don't know the timelines, to be honest with you.

1231
02:05:05,728 --> 02:05:08,710
[SPEAKER_14]: These gentlemen would probably know the timelines better than I would.

1232
02:05:09,510 --> 02:05:15,513
[SPEAKER_14]: The city was going through a contractual negotiation with both the patrol union and the superiors union.

1233
02:05:17,674 --> 02:05:24,158
[SPEAKER_14]: As a part of that process, the unions have the option to file with the joint labor management committee.

1234
02:05:24,918 --> 02:05:27,960
[SPEAKER_14]: The joint management labor committee is a mandated

1235
02:05:30,780 --> 02:05:36,582
[SPEAKER_14]: essentially mediation and an arbitration process that is, you know, established and codified in mass general law.

1236
02:05:37,543 --> 02:05:43,265
[SPEAKER_14]: And both police and fire can file with the Joint Labor Management Committee.

1237
02:05:43,945 --> 02:05:45,806
[SPEAKER_14]: And it's a mandated process.

1238
02:05:45,846 --> 02:05:52,548
[SPEAKER_14]: We can't elect to not negotiate or we can't elect to get to an impasse.

1239
02:05:52,628 --> 02:05:54,469
[SPEAKER_14]: We must follow the process.

1240
02:05:55,449 --> 02:06:17,519
[SPEAKER_14]: I can't, I don't recall exactly all the stages, but just before some of the final, we were actually in the final process towards getting a decision awarded by the JLMC before the union was able to settle and the city was able to settle with the union.

1241
02:06:17,539 --> 02:06:18,839
[SPEAKER_17]: So you were like at an impasse?

1242
02:06:19,620 --> 02:06:19,840
[SPEAKER_14]: Sorry?

1243
02:06:19,980 --> 02:06:22,661
[SPEAKER_17]: You were at an impasse and there was somebody was deciding

1244
02:06:23,987 --> 02:06:29,129
[SPEAKER_14]: Well, it's such that cities and towns can't get to an impasse, basically.

1245
02:06:29,149 --> 02:06:36,911
[SPEAKER_14]: The process kind of takes over and it requires cities and towns to... So somebody decided on this contract for you?

1246
02:06:37,111 --> 02:06:38,091
[SPEAKER_14]: No.

1247
02:06:39,092 --> 02:06:45,053
[SPEAKER_14]: So through the process, we were doing extensive amounts of research and work.

1248
02:06:45,494 --> 02:06:52,876
[SPEAKER_14]: I actually have a binder somewhere that we put together for the process, for the negotiations to ensure that

1249
02:06:53,476 --> 02:07:00,158
[SPEAKER_14]: We had gone through our due diligence and looked around the Commonwealth, looked at other cities and towns to understand what numbers they were settling at.

1250
02:07:01,299 --> 02:07:11,042
[SPEAKER_14]: It's important for us to make sure that we tell the city's story in terms of the city's available dollars and budget in that process.

1251
02:07:13,423 --> 02:07:18,904
[SPEAKER_14]: We essentially present at that arbitration hearing and we present information to.

1252
02:07:18,924 --> 02:07:19,564
[SPEAKER_14]: Okay.

1253
02:07:19,584 --> 02:07:19,924
[SPEAKER_14]: We don't have.

1254
02:07:19,944 --> 02:07:20,444
[SPEAKER_17]: That's okay.

1255
02:07:20,504 --> 02:07:20,844
[SPEAKER_17]: That's okay.

1256
02:07:21,144 --> 02:07:21,524
[SPEAKER_17]: I'm sorry.

1257
02:07:21,604 --> 02:07:23,145
[SPEAKER_17]: We can't keep doing this all night.

1258
02:07:23,565 --> 02:07:26,045
[SPEAKER_17]: We, what's your lowest paid police officer paid?

1259
02:07:29,486 --> 02:07:31,746
[SPEAKER_06]: Lowest paid, like entry level.

1260
02:07:31,806 --> 02:07:32,026
[SPEAKER_06]: Yeah.

1261
02:07:32,066 --> 02:07:32,526
[SPEAKER_06]: Entry level.

1262
02:07:32,566 --> 02:07:33,807
[SPEAKER_06]: First step police officer.

1263
02:07:33,907 --> 02:07:34,167
[SPEAKER_06]: Yeah.

1264
02:07:34,187 --> 02:07:34,167
66,000.

1265
02:07:34,207 --> 02:07:35,407
[SPEAKER_06]: A year.

1266
02:07:35,447 --> 02:07:35,727
[SPEAKER_06]: Yeah.

1267
02:07:36,307 --> 02:07:41,768
[SPEAKER_17]: So if we were to divide that up by hour, how many hours do police officers work per week?

1268
02:07:43,822 --> 02:07:44,383
[SPEAKER_17]: 40 hours a week.

1269
02:07:44,863 --> 02:07:48,767
[SPEAKER_17]: So I just want to do a quick math, 66.

1270
02:07:48,867 --> 02:07:49,188
[SPEAKER_17]: Sorry.

1271
02:07:57,788 --> 02:08:03,512
[SPEAKER_17]: 42 divided by 40 is, so that's like $31 an hour.

1272
02:08:03,532 --> 02:08:06,575
[SPEAKER_17]: $31.70 an hour.

1273
02:08:08,676 --> 02:08:10,317
[SPEAKER_17]: And that's like a starting level.

1274
02:08:10,958 --> 02:08:14,160
[SPEAKER_06]: Yeah, because that's a five year step process.

1275
02:08:14,460 --> 02:08:14,660
[SPEAKER_17]: Yeah.

1276
02:08:16,021 --> 02:08:21,165
[SPEAKER_17]: And librarians who work in Medford part time, not in the union.

1277
02:08:22,257 --> 02:08:24,978
[SPEAKER_17]: with a master's degree make $20 an hour.

1278
02:08:25,858 --> 02:08:31,921
[SPEAKER_17]: So the library is asking for $20,000 to pay them slightly more.

1279
02:08:32,761 --> 02:08:39,543
[SPEAKER_17]: They still will not be at market rate, but I just want to compare that.

1280
02:08:40,984 --> 02:08:44,205
[SPEAKER_17]: Were you asked by the chief of staff or the mayor to cut your budget at all?

1281
02:08:46,386 --> 02:08:49,607
[SPEAKER_17]: After this budget was presented to the mayor's office, were you asked to cut it?

1282
02:08:51,294 --> 02:08:52,895
[SPEAKER_06]: There were a few cuts made.

1283
02:08:53,195 --> 02:08:54,155
[SPEAKER_17]: Can you tell me where?

1284
02:08:57,456 --> 02:08:57,977
[SPEAKER_06]: Overtime.

1285
02:09:02,218 --> 02:09:03,158
[SPEAKER_06]: In which?

1286
02:09:03,259 --> 02:09:04,559
[SPEAKER_17]: There are a lot of overtimes.

1287
02:09:04,659 --> 02:09:05,579
[SPEAKER_17]: Do you remember which one?

1288
02:09:08,280 --> 02:09:10,241
[SPEAKER_06]: Overtime for officers, clerical, and training.

1289
02:09:10,701 --> 02:09:11,642
[SPEAKER_17]: All of them?

1290
02:09:12,142 --> 02:09:12,422
[SPEAKER_17]: Okay.

1291
02:09:13,142 --> 02:09:14,923
[SPEAKER_06]: And those increases were more based on

1292
02:09:15,999 --> 02:09:16,399
[SPEAKER_06]: Actuals.

1293
02:09:16,439 --> 02:09:19,360
[SPEAKER_06]: You know, the actuals and salary increases, so.

1294
02:09:19,720 --> 02:09:19,900
[SPEAKER_17]: Yeah.

1295
02:09:20,480 --> 02:09:27,002
[SPEAKER_06]: It's something that also takes part as, you know, how many police officers we're going to have graduating.

1296
02:09:27,402 --> 02:09:28,042
[SPEAKER_06]: Yeah.

1297
02:09:28,082 --> 02:09:32,223
[SPEAKER_06]: How many we hire, and it works hand in hand with the overtime, so.

1298
02:09:32,504 --> 02:09:39,906
[SPEAKER_17]: Another thing I want to ask about is the full-time police officers, the number of positions.

1299
02:09:42,348 --> 02:09:48,091
[SPEAKER_17]: It looks like you will be planning to hire more patrol officers next year?

1300
02:09:48,131 --> 02:09:50,152
[SPEAKER_06]: Yes, we currently have 97 right now.

1301
02:09:50,172 --> 02:09:54,855
[SPEAKER_06]: 105 would give us the opportunity to hire another eight right now immediately.

1302
02:09:55,735 --> 02:09:58,317
[SPEAKER_17]: So eight more patrol officers immediately.

1303
02:09:58,617 --> 02:09:59,057
[SPEAKER_17]: That's great.

1304
02:10:00,298 --> 02:10:01,278
[SPEAKER_17]: The fire department.

1305
02:10:03,400 --> 02:10:07,562
[SPEAKER_17]: Does anybody remember what the fire department was allotted for hiring more firefighters?

1306
02:10:07,622 --> 02:10:08,142
[SPEAKER_17]: I can't remember.

1307
02:10:08,162 --> 02:10:09,203
[SPEAKER_17]: I don't think it was.

1308
02:10:11,447 --> 02:10:12,689
[SPEAKER_05]: It was around 6 or 8.

1309
02:10:12,769 --> 02:10:13,350
[SPEAKER_05]: I'm not 100% sure.

1310
02:10:21,035 --> 02:10:24,017
[SPEAKER_17]: Understand how contractual obligations work.

1311
02:10:24,097 --> 02:10:25,738
[SPEAKER_17]: I know that it took a long time to get there.

1312
02:10:26,278 --> 02:10:36,485
[SPEAKER_17]: An argument was just made by the mayor tonight that if the lowest paid librarians got an increase in their pay, it would be too much of a jump all at once and it wouldn't be fair to other departments.

1313
02:10:37,045 --> 02:10:46,632
[SPEAKER_17]: I think this is a great example of what happens when somebody in one department is being right-sized to a contract that might be something that is

1314
02:10:47,793 --> 02:10:50,656
[SPEAKER_17]: overdue and necessary, perhaps.

1315
02:10:51,998 --> 02:11:04,693
[SPEAKER_17]: But I don't think you can make the argument that one department in the city

1316
02:11:08,147 --> 02:11:18,652
[SPEAKER_17]: should have people that get paid a living wage, and another department in the city should have people that just do it for the love of it when everybody needs to eat and prevent for their families.

1317
02:11:19,212 --> 02:11:20,312
[SPEAKER_17]: And I'm not saying you guys don't.

1318
02:11:20,593 --> 02:11:29,136
[SPEAKER_17]: I'm just saying that this is a great example of disparity within the same employment unit.

1319
02:11:29,296 --> 02:11:35,379
[SPEAKER_17]: So I feel frustrated about, I know it's a very big department.

1320
02:11:35,399 --> 02:11:37,200
[SPEAKER_17]: The police department's very big.

1321
02:11:37,813 --> 02:11:38,975
[SPEAKER_17]: I understand that.

1322
02:11:39,135 --> 02:11:50,135
[SPEAKER_17]: But knowing how many times we've heard about the size of the deficit for this year and seeing that it's exactly this increase and that

1323
02:11:52,475 --> 02:11:59,780
[SPEAKER_17]: All the other departments have just small, small, small asks and that it would make a huge difference for a couple of people.

1324
02:12:01,661 --> 02:12:03,082
[SPEAKER_17]: I feel frustrated again.

1325
02:12:03,262 --> 02:12:06,264
[SPEAKER_17]: I do appreciate your responses to that stuff.

1326
02:12:06,324 --> 02:12:08,845
[SPEAKER_17]: I mean, everything is, it's not unreasonable.

1327
02:12:08,885 --> 02:12:10,747
[SPEAKER_17]: It's just all very stark.

1328
02:12:11,822 --> 02:12:16,083
[SPEAKER_06]: And just to clarify the years of the contract, I mean the 2027 fiscal raise for police is 2.5%.

1329
02:12:16,143 --> 02:12:18,524
[SPEAKER_06]: Yeah, totally.

1330
02:12:19,044 --> 02:12:19,345
[SPEAKER_17]: Of course.

1331
02:12:19,405 --> 02:12:20,625
[SPEAKER_17]: It's just that it's been building.

1332
02:12:20,705 --> 02:12:21,425
[SPEAKER_17]: Yes, of course.

1333
02:12:21,545 --> 02:12:22,065
[SPEAKER_17]: And I understand.

1334
02:12:22,225 --> 02:12:22,726
[SPEAKER_17]: I understand that.

1335
02:12:23,646 --> 02:12:27,847
[SPEAKER_17]: And that is the same thing in the library, too, is that they've been underpaid for so long.

1336
02:12:30,794 --> 02:12:40,477
[SPEAKER_17]: when the ask was small because the hope was to get maybe if we ask for just a little bit we'll get that and then you got half of that, you know, over and over again for years.

1337
02:12:41,278 --> 02:12:54,942
[SPEAKER_17]: And I think we just need to think more along the lines of ask for what we deserve now and maybe get a little bit less than like, you know, ask for nothing and get less than that.

1338
02:12:58,260 --> 02:13:09,027
[SPEAKER_17]: And also that like maybe we have a responsibility as a city to give the people that work here what they deserve all the time, not just every four years and not every 10 years.

1339
02:13:11,229 --> 02:13:11,669
[SPEAKER_17]: But thank you.

1340
02:13:11,869 --> 02:13:12,449
[SPEAKER_17]: And I'm sorry.

1341
02:13:12,469 --> 02:13:12,950
[SPEAKER_17]: Thank you.

1342
02:13:13,670 --> 02:13:13,910
[SPEAKER_17]: Thanks.

1343
02:13:14,030 --> 02:13:14,291
[SPEAKER_03]: Thank you.

1344
02:13:16,452 --> 02:13:16,992
[SPEAKER_05]: Thank you.

1345
02:13:17,012 --> 02:13:19,414
[SPEAKER_05]: Councillor Callahan.

1346
02:13:20,623 --> 02:13:21,203
[SPEAKER_11]: Thanks.

1347
02:13:22,004 --> 02:13:23,885
[SPEAKER_11]: My main questions are just about overtime.

1348
02:13:24,845 --> 02:13:30,368
[SPEAKER_11]: And also overtime, same as the increase to salaries, overtime also comes to about $2 million.

1349
02:13:31,849 --> 02:13:46,257
[SPEAKER_11]: And my question about overtime is really, and we asked the fire department about this, and it was a really interesting answer to sort of understand exactly how fire departments are required to have 24, 23 people per shift by law.

1350
02:13:46,437 --> 02:13:48,398
[SPEAKER_11]: And that means that if they're understaffed,

1351
02:13:49,118 --> 02:13:52,599
[SPEAKER_11]: They literally have to do overtime and people don't want to do it.

1352
02:13:52,779 --> 02:13:54,159
[SPEAKER_11]: So it was a very interesting conversation.

1353
02:13:55,619 --> 02:14:00,780
[SPEAKER_11]: And I would love to understand more about overtime generally in the police department.

1354
02:14:01,500 --> 02:14:14,263
[SPEAKER_11]: And then if you can, also talk about overtime for things like the crossing guards, like when a crossing guard is missing and then a policeman does that.

1355
02:14:15,583 --> 02:14:19,345
[SPEAKER_11]: just to understand how much overtime, what is overtime for?

1356
02:14:19,385 --> 02:14:22,146
[SPEAKER_11]: Why is overtime necessary?

1357
02:14:22,166 --> 02:14:24,187
[SPEAKER_11]: Why does the police force use overtime?

1358
02:14:24,207 --> 02:14:26,928
[SPEAKER_11]: I'd love to have a general understanding.

1359
02:14:28,937 --> 02:14:30,658
[SPEAKER_01]: going to start with the traffic supervisors.

1360
02:14:31,318 --> 02:14:34,880
[SPEAKER_01]: We don't pay police officers to fill their spots on overtime.

1361
02:14:34,980 --> 02:14:36,341
[SPEAKER_01]: It's someone comes off the shift.

1362
02:14:36,621 --> 02:14:39,222
[SPEAKER_01]: It's an hour in the morning, an hour in the afternoon.

1363
02:14:39,682 --> 02:14:43,724
[SPEAKER_01]: So we work with less people at that time is what happens.

1364
02:14:43,744 --> 02:14:44,565
[SPEAKER_11]: So it's not overtime.

1365
02:14:44,645 --> 02:14:45,805
[SPEAKER_01]: So that is not overtime.

1366
02:14:45,845 --> 02:14:46,365
[SPEAKER_01]: Thank you.

1367
02:14:46,386 --> 02:14:47,206
[SPEAKER_01]: That's good to know.

1368
02:14:49,912 --> 02:14:58,918
[SPEAKER_01]: We have a certain amount of people we staff daily, per shift, and we will allow that to go down to a certain number before we have overtime.

1369
02:15:00,980 --> 02:15:03,762
[SPEAKER_01]: We are often forcing people to stay for overtime.

1370
02:15:05,063 --> 02:15:12,348
[SPEAKER_01]: It is a large number because the number we have, 97 people, is very, very low.

1371
02:15:12,368 --> 02:15:16,791
[SPEAKER_01]: I was here, I've been here for 40 years, and I remember when we had 132 offices.

1372
02:15:19,265 --> 02:15:25,306
[SPEAKER_01]: We probably ran an average of 120 to 25 for a very long time.

1373
02:15:25,486 --> 02:15:29,267
[SPEAKER_01]: And in the last 10 years, the numbers just kept going down and down and down.

1374
02:15:29,687 --> 02:15:32,308
[SPEAKER_01]: So the money is one issue.

1375
02:15:32,668 --> 02:15:36,829
[SPEAKER_01]: There's also an issue with hiring people who people just don't want to do this job.

1376
02:15:37,949 --> 02:15:39,709
[SPEAKER_01]: And it's become very difficult.

1377
02:15:39,769 --> 02:15:40,750
[SPEAKER_01]: They're under a lot of stress.

1378
02:15:40,910 --> 02:15:43,750
[SPEAKER_01]: And therefore, the overtime goes up.

1379
02:15:43,970 --> 02:15:46,031
[SPEAKER_01]: So instead of having, we're trying to get to 105.

1380
02:15:47,675 --> 02:15:53,217
[SPEAKER_01]: We're still nowhere near where we should be to service this city, especially a city of this size.

1381
02:15:54,218 --> 02:15:58,539
[SPEAKER_01]: But if we can get to that, it helps reduce the overtime part a little bit.

1382
02:15:58,859 --> 02:16:01,340
[SPEAKER_11]: Do you mind if I just ask a little bit more detail?

1383
02:16:01,360 --> 02:16:01,660
[SPEAKER_11]: Sure.

1384
02:16:02,221 --> 02:16:10,324
[SPEAKER_11]: My understanding from the fire department is that there's a legal requirement per fire truck or per station.

1385
02:16:10,564 --> 02:16:12,885
[SPEAKER_01]: There are standards, industry standards to maintain.

1386
02:16:13,445 --> 02:16:21,947
[SPEAKER_11]: So I would love to, like, how does the police department determine if overtime, if overtime is guesstimated?

1387
02:16:21,967 --> 02:16:22,587
[SPEAKER_11]: We have numbers.

1388
02:16:22,607 --> 02:16:25,148
[SPEAKER_11]: Like, how are those numbers determined?

1389
02:16:25,208 --> 02:16:27,588
[SPEAKER_01]: We have four sectors in the city.

1390
02:16:28,048 --> 02:16:29,889
[SPEAKER_01]: Each sector has two officers.

1391
02:16:30,369 --> 02:16:32,950
[SPEAKER_01]: That's an average of eight officers per sector.

1392
02:16:33,310 --> 02:16:34,910
[SPEAKER_01]: There'll be two sergeants in the street.

1393
02:16:35,150 --> 02:16:36,911
[SPEAKER_01]: One is the east side, one is the west side.

1394
02:16:37,351 --> 02:16:38,531
[SPEAKER_01]: So you're talking 10 there.

1395
02:16:38,951 --> 02:16:40,471
[SPEAKER_01]: Sergeant staffing is a little different.

1396
02:16:40,931 --> 02:16:42,752
[SPEAKER_01]: But we'll go down as low as six.

1397
02:16:43,552 --> 02:16:48,393
[SPEAKER_01]: We won't go lower than six unless we just can't get personnel to fill.

1398
02:16:49,573 --> 02:16:50,813
[SPEAKER_01]: But six is low.

1399
02:16:50,993 --> 02:16:54,534
[SPEAKER_01]: That's a low number to be running around there, whether it's a daytime or evening or midnights.

1400
02:16:54,974 --> 02:16:55,634
[SPEAKER_01]: But we do it.

1401
02:16:55,894 --> 02:16:59,675
[SPEAKER_01]: And one catastrophic event can just put us behind.

1402
02:16:59,715 --> 02:17:03,356
[SPEAKER_01]: We're fortunate that we have several cities and towns that step up and help.

1403
02:17:03,396 --> 02:17:04,316
[SPEAKER_01]: They're all in the same boat.

1404
02:17:04,856 --> 02:17:07,597
[SPEAKER_01]: So mutual aid is a big thing in our business right now.

1405
02:17:09,437 --> 02:17:11,778
[SPEAKER_01]: So that's the number.

1406
02:17:12,379 --> 02:17:26,626
[SPEAKER_01]: A full staff would be the eight sector cars, two to four motorcycles, depending on the shift, a K-9 officer, which we do have another K-9 officer, who's often bumped into the sector cars.

1407
02:17:26,947 --> 02:17:29,848
[SPEAKER_01]: So he's not out doing his regular K-9 routine.

1408
02:17:29,868 --> 02:17:30,729
[SPEAKER_01]: He has to answer calls.

1409
02:17:31,109 --> 02:17:34,991
[SPEAKER_01]: And then when we need a K-9 specifically, we'll take him out of that sector.

1410
02:17:37,532 --> 02:17:43,896
[SPEAKER_01]: We have detectives, we're down to, it's a bare minimum detectives unit following up on cases.

1411
02:17:44,316 --> 02:17:48,818
[SPEAKER_01]: We often get complaints from people that feel we should be following up on their case.

1412
02:17:49,199 --> 02:18:05,407
[SPEAKER_01]: When I was a detective lieutenant, I had explained to them that based on the situation that they're in and the lack of solvability factors, their case got put aside and other cases are assigned to people because we just don't have enough people to take on every case that they want.

1413
02:18:06,528 --> 02:18:08,309
[SPEAKER_01]: our citizens want us to follow up on.

1414
02:18:08,469 --> 02:18:13,292
[SPEAKER_01]: When you become a victim, in some circumstance, you know, we feel for you.

1415
02:18:13,592 --> 02:18:15,313
[SPEAKER_01]: We don't want you to be stuck out there.

1416
02:18:15,333 --> 02:18:23,038
[SPEAKER_01]: But there are some cases that just don't, they don't have the solvability factors and the level of the crime really isn't

1417
02:18:24,360 --> 02:18:26,160
[SPEAKER_01]: I hate to say isn't high, but it isn't.

1418
02:18:26,680 --> 02:18:29,801
[SPEAKER_01]: And so we have to put that on the back burner.

1419
02:18:30,401 --> 02:18:36,323
[SPEAKER_01]: When the detectives are, you know, when things might slow down a little bit, they'll pick at those cases and try to resolve them.

1420
02:18:36,383 --> 02:18:44,464
[SPEAKER_01]: But I've seen our numbers, like I said, go from 132 down to 97 right now.

1421
02:18:44,904 --> 02:18:46,465
[SPEAKER_01]: I've seen them go as low as 90.

1422
02:18:48,185 --> 02:18:50,726
[SPEAKER_01]: And we usually would be bouncing back up within a couple of years.

1423
02:18:50,866 --> 02:18:52,406
[SPEAKER_01]: We're not seeing that bounce back up now.

1424
02:18:53,026 --> 02:18:58,057
[SPEAKER_01]: It's been five years now, so it's at least more than five years that our numbers have been dropping.

1425
02:19:00,528 --> 02:19:02,329
[SPEAKER_01]: It's difficult to get people to do this job now.

1426
02:19:04,291 --> 02:19:07,413
[SPEAKER_01]: Also, it's a six-month training academy.

1427
02:19:08,533 --> 02:19:09,974
[SPEAKER_01]: We talk about a master's degree.

1428
02:19:10,034 --> 02:19:15,098
[SPEAKER_01]: It's certainly not a master's degree, but the amount of credits that would be built into it would give you an associate's degree.

1429
02:19:16,198 --> 02:19:25,744
[SPEAKER_01]: You may be making the same amount of money when you come out as the person who's hired to say work for the DPW that's sweeping the ground, but you are now

1430
02:19:27,625 --> 02:19:45,510
[SPEAKER_01]: You have specialized in mass criminal laws, mass traffic laws, motor vehicle laws, working with people in domestic violence, working with people in mental health issues, as well as all the defensive tactics and firearms things that we go through.

1431
02:19:45,870 --> 02:19:49,611
[SPEAKER_01]: So there's a lot of work that goes to it, and their pay is not good when they're in there.

1432
02:19:49,931 --> 02:19:54,813
[SPEAKER_01]: So some people will leave a career because they want to be a police officer, and they'll sacrifice that.

1433
02:19:55,393 --> 02:19:57,014
[SPEAKER_01]: pay to commit.

1434
02:19:57,074 --> 02:20:02,379
[SPEAKER_01]: And then after they get out of the academy, they'll get up to that step one pay that we just talked about.

1435
02:20:02,799 --> 02:20:08,164
[SPEAKER_01]: So we're all suffering to get somewhere.

1436
02:20:08,364 --> 02:20:14,149
[SPEAKER_01]: And unfortunately, and I understand your comparison, your goal is to get everybody a pay raise.

1437
02:20:15,990 --> 02:20:19,333
[SPEAKER_01]: The unfortunate thing is I know that the

1438
02:20:19,923 --> 02:20:23,485
[SPEAKER_01]: Librarian may have a master's degree, but so do most police officers right now.

1439
02:20:23,965 --> 02:20:24,465
[SPEAKER_01]: I have one.

1440
02:20:25,025 --> 02:20:25,706
[SPEAKER_01]: I know he does.

1441
02:20:26,026 --> 02:20:27,406
[SPEAKER_01]: And those guys over there do.

1442
02:20:27,746 --> 02:20:31,028
[SPEAKER_01]: So many of them officers do have bachelor's degrees, too.

1443
02:20:31,328 --> 02:20:36,630
[SPEAKER_01]: So there might be a couple that don't have a college degree, but most people are working towards it.

1444
02:20:37,771 --> 02:20:43,073
[SPEAKER_01]: So there is that educational aspect that we carry on on our own.

1445
02:20:44,614 --> 02:20:49,436
[SPEAKER_01]: And there's also that you go to work as in the library, odds are you're going home that night.

1446
02:20:49,996 --> 02:20:52,057
[SPEAKER_01]: In this job, you never know how you're going to end up.

1447
02:20:52,277 --> 02:20:54,679
[SPEAKER_01]: We had an event this morning that an officer was almost killed.

1448
02:20:55,339 --> 02:21:03,804
[SPEAKER_01]: And so that risk is also a deciding factor on not just your educational background, but what are the things you're willing to do to help the public.

1449
02:21:04,084 --> 02:21:06,305
[SPEAKER_01]: So thank you.

1450
02:21:06,705 --> 02:21:06,945
[SPEAKER_01]: Thanks.

1451
02:21:07,506 --> 02:21:10,207
[SPEAKER_06]: As far as overtime is concerned, I'd like to elaborate on one more thing.

1452
02:21:10,567 --> 02:21:15,030
[SPEAKER_06]: Back to your question, too, is when I say 97, I should have probably said

1453
02:21:15,810 --> 02:21:20,892
[SPEAKER_06]: We have 91, like, because six, 91 are actually sworn.

1454
02:21:21,372 --> 02:21:23,112
[SPEAKER_06]: We have six in the academy right now.

1455
02:21:23,132 --> 02:21:24,993
[SPEAKER_06]: We have two graduating very soon.

1456
02:21:26,233 --> 02:21:31,635
[SPEAKER_06]: And that's part of that 97 number I probably should have elaborated on earlier.

1457
02:21:31,895 --> 02:21:32,355
[SPEAKER_11]: That's helpful.

1458
02:21:36,056 --> 02:21:36,216
[SPEAKER_01]: Thanks.

1459
02:21:36,296 --> 02:21:38,757
[SPEAKER_01]: Did I answer your question as far as your questions?

1460
02:21:38,777 --> 02:21:38,877
[SPEAKER_01]: Yeah.

1461
02:21:38,897 --> 02:21:39,257
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you.

1462
02:21:40,557 --> 02:21:40,797
[SPEAKER_03]: Great.

1463
02:21:41,137 --> 02:21:42,618
[SPEAKER_03]: Do we have any more questions for?

1464
02:21:44,528 --> 02:21:46,358
[SPEAKER_03]: Technicolino, Lieutenant Gagliardi.

1465
02:21:48,026 --> 02:21:48,609
[SPEAKER_03]: Councillor Cunliffe.

1466
02:21:50,322 --> 02:21:58,147
[SPEAKER_11]: I apologize, just because this writing is so tiny, it's very hard to read it here.

1467
02:21:58,227 --> 02:22:00,228
[SPEAKER_11]: I should have brought them with me from home.

1468
02:22:00,268 --> 02:22:00,988
[SPEAKER_11]: I didn't do that.

1469
02:22:01,369 --> 02:22:02,009
[SPEAKER_11]: So I'm in trouble here.

1470
02:22:02,069 --> 02:22:07,112
[SPEAKER_11]: But I did notice that it is split up into like officers, clerical, and training.

1471
02:22:07,192 --> 02:22:11,194
[SPEAKER_11]: Is there anything that would be interesting for us to know about what is training overtime?

1472
02:22:11,274 --> 02:22:14,416
[SPEAKER_11]: Why is there overtime for training and clerical?

1473
02:22:14,436 --> 02:22:15,517
[SPEAKER_11]: How are those different from each other?

1474
02:22:16,218 --> 02:22:21,561
[SPEAKER_01]: Oftentimes we send people to training on their days off, because our schedule's not a regular Monday through Friday schedule.

1475
02:22:21,981 --> 02:22:24,002
[SPEAKER_01]: So we have to pay them overtime, it's a contractual thing.

1476
02:22:24,503 --> 02:22:29,586
[SPEAKER_01]: Or if we send them in lieu of their shift, we often have to fill that spot with an overtime shift.

1477
02:22:29,626 --> 02:22:30,586
[SPEAKER_01]: So that's what that's for.

1478
02:22:30,606 --> 02:22:30,906
[SPEAKER_01]: Great, thanks.

1479
02:22:35,989 --> 02:22:42,653
[SPEAKER_01]: And to your statement, which is true about building up the money over the years.

1480
02:22:43,815 --> 02:22:46,778
[SPEAKER_01]: I can remember when I came on, the pay was $20,000 a year.

1481
02:22:46,798 --> 02:22:50,242
[SPEAKER_01]: So it's a building process.

1482
02:22:50,262 --> 02:22:54,086
[SPEAKER_01]: And I don't think 66 is probably the equivalent of $20,000 a year.

1483
02:23:00,492 --> 02:23:02,954
[SPEAKER_06]: And police officer training is worth, is more than $150,000.

1484
02:23:03,134 --> 02:23:05,935
[SPEAKER_06]: I mean, we get it from a lot of different funding sources.

1485
02:23:06,796 --> 02:23:10,358
[SPEAKER_06]: So that's, we get it from multiple funding sources.

1486
02:23:10,418 --> 02:23:13,980
[SPEAKER_06]: So that's just from our budget side of it.

1487
02:23:14,120 --> 02:23:14,961
[SPEAKER_06]: There's more training than $150,000.

1488
02:23:18,362 --> 02:23:19,263
[SPEAKER_01]: Just to clarify that.

1489
02:23:19,923 --> 02:23:22,165
[SPEAKER_01]: Over the years, we've established our own training program.

1490
02:23:22,185 --> 02:23:28,208
[SPEAKER_01]: The industry has established training programs whether we participate or not is the department's thing.

1491
02:23:28,228 --> 02:23:32,931
[SPEAKER_01]: But as the state grew, as we grew, the state came up with mandates and laws.

1492
02:23:33,391 --> 02:23:39,815
[SPEAKER_01]: Now, we have the post commission which has increased our normal training by more and they're mandated.

1493
02:23:39,935 --> 02:23:41,276
[SPEAKER_01]: So, that cost is still going.

1494
02:23:41,336 --> 02:23:42,017
[SPEAKER_01]: It goes up even more.

1495
02:23:44,058 --> 02:23:44,418
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you.

1496
02:23:44,658 --> 02:23:47,340
[SPEAKER_04]: Oh, sorry, Vice President Lazaro.

1497
02:23:48,734 --> 02:23:56,600
[SPEAKER_17]: I just wanted to clarify quickly, I didn't intend for my comment to be that it's a comparison of education or that.

1498
02:23:58,916 --> 02:24:02,918
[SPEAKER_17]: having or not having a certain degree means that you deserve more or less money.

1499
02:24:02,958 --> 02:24:23,109
[SPEAKER_17]: I just mean that if you require somebody to have a degree and then offer them $20 an hour to perform a job, it's often having higher degrees means you may have personal debt, you may have

1500
02:24:23,932 --> 02:24:28,436
[SPEAKER_17]: a family to provide for, and that was the reason.

1501
02:24:30,531 --> 02:24:35,054
[SPEAKER_17]: And usually it implies, like, you would have higher pay, hopefully.

1502
02:24:35,435 --> 02:24:37,056
[SPEAKER_17]: But that's all I meant.

1503
02:24:37,076 --> 02:24:46,062
[SPEAKER_17]: It wasn't that, like, I just wanted to compare, like, an entry level position with something that would be maybe a step beyond entry level, because they would have had more training and education.

1504
02:24:47,183 --> 02:24:50,045
[SPEAKER_17]: Not to say it's apples to apples, because it's not.

1505
02:24:50,145 --> 02:24:56,149
[SPEAKER_17]: It's just that when we're looking at different departments' budgets, and we're talking about,

1506
02:24:58,482 --> 02:25:00,743
[SPEAKER_17]: how much money is really at stake.

1507
02:25:02,123 --> 02:25:09,544
[SPEAKER_17]: And it's really hard to compare across departments, because the police department is so big, and then when we're going to talk about the school budget, and it's also huge.

1508
02:25:10,804 --> 02:25:18,446
[SPEAKER_17]: And it's just, it's really hard to do this, and that's why it's useful to have these conversations, but I do appreciate the perspective you share as well.

1509
02:25:19,386 --> 02:25:26,027
[SPEAKER_17]: And I think that everybody should be able to come into a position, in an entry level position, it used to be true in a lot more,

1510
02:25:27,027 --> 02:25:32,974
[SPEAKER_17]: careers that you can come in with a salary that you can live on.

1511
02:25:33,996 --> 02:25:37,420
[SPEAKER_17]: I think that should be kind of baseline for most places, and it's really not.

1512
02:25:38,621 --> 02:25:39,983
[SPEAKER_17]: That's why people live with their parents for longer.

1513
02:25:40,023 --> 02:25:41,805
[SPEAKER_17]: That's why, like, you know, they rely on each other.

1514
02:25:41,865 --> 02:25:42,886
[SPEAKER_17]: They have roommates, that kind of thing.

1515
02:25:43,327 --> 02:25:45,569
[SPEAKER_17]: But anyway, I appreciate this moment.

1516
02:25:45,770 --> 02:25:45,950
[SPEAKER_17]: Thanks.

1517
02:25:48,878 --> 02:25:49,258
[SPEAKER_05]: Thank you.

1518
02:25:50,239 --> 02:25:51,820
[SPEAKER_05]: I just have a couple quick questions.

1519
02:25:51,940 --> 02:25:54,741
[SPEAKER_05]: So, I mean, I brought this up around the fire as well.

1520
02:25:55,301 --> 02:25:59,544
[SPEAKER_05]: And I appreciate that it's kind of more specifically outlined here.

1521
02:26:00,985 --> 02:26:02,445
[SPEAKER_05]: There's six positions funded.

1522
02:26:02,625 --> 02:26:05,687
[SPEAKER_05]: Is it six or seven positions funded at a dollar in this budget?

1523
02:26:06,688 --> 02:26:06,928
[SPEAKER_06]: Seven.

1524
02:26:07,108 --> 02:26:07,428
[SPEAKER_05]: Seven.

1525
02:26:07,508 --> 02:26:07,908
[SPEAKER_05]: So it's this.

1526
02:26:07,928 --> 02:26:10,350
[SPEAKER_06]: One deputy chief and six police officers, yes.

1527
02:26:10,690 --> 02:26:10,910
[SPEAKER_05]: Great.

1528
02:26:11,070 --> 02:26:11,370
[SPEAKER_05]: Okay.

1529
02:26:11,650 --> 02:26:12,971
[SPEAKER_05]: Six patrol deputy chief.

1530
02:26:13,391 --> 02:26:13,571
[SPEAKER_06]: Yes.

1531
02:26:13,691 --> 02:26:14,492
[SPEAKER_05]: Funded at a dollar.

1532
02:26:16,579 --> 02:26:17,499
[SPEAKER_05]: effective staffing is 105.

1533
02:26:17,539 --> 02:26:19,360
[SPEAKER_05]: What's that?

1534
02:26:19,600 --> 02:26:22,281
[SPEAKER_05]: The effective staffing is 105 uniformed officers.

1535
02:26:22,962 --> 02:26:24,703
[SPEAKER_01]: We're funded, yeah.

1536
02:26:24,843 --> 02:26:25,143
[SPEAKER_05]: Okay.

1537
02:26:25,383 --> 02:26:25,663
[SPEAKER_01]: All right.

1538
02:26:25,703 --> 02:26:28,544
[SPEAKER_01]: That's the whole department, 105, not just uniformed officers.

1539
02:26:28,985 --> 02:26:30,705
[SPEAKER_05]: Okay.

1540
02:26:30,725 --> 02:26:32,126
[SPEAKER_05]: It says in this sheet.

1541
02:26:32,506 --> 02:26:33,327
[SPEAKER_01]: That's from the chief down 105.

1542
02:26:34,459 --> 02:26:34,639
[SPEAKER_05]: Right.

1543
02:26:34,699 --> 02:26:35,580
[SPEAKER_05]: I didn't mean just patrol.

1544
02:26:35,600 --> 02:26:40,803
[SPEAKER_05]: So it says in here 105 uniformed officers, so just FYI.

1545
02:26:41,043 --> 02:26:44,605
[SPEAKER_05]: But yeah, understanding that's chief, captain, lieutenant, sergeants, and patrol, right.

1546
02:26:47,267 --> 02:26:48,787
[SPEAKER_05]: You know, this isn't really on you guys.

1547
02:26:50,729 --> 02:27:03,296
[SPEAKER_05]: If you have any kind of context or explanation for including the 112 number with the $1 items, is that, you know, something that the department wanted to maintain in here to show that,

1548
02:27:04,613 --> 02:27:05,974
[SPEAKER_05]: In the future, we want that?

1549
02:27:05,994 --> 02:27:07,355
[SPEAKER_01]: We want to get our numbers back up.

1550
02:27:07,375 --> 02:27:09,356
[SPEAKER_01]: We want to be able to do more for the public.

1551
02:27:09,436 --> 02:27:12,938
[SPEAKER_01]: There is a lot more that we can do out there.

1552
02:27:13,018 --> 02:27:15,079
[SPEAKER_01]: Traffic is one of our biggest problems in this city.

1553
02:27:15,840 --> 02:27:18,281
[SPEAKER_01]: Our traffic division opens and closes every job.

1554
02:27:18,381 --> 02:27:19,122
[SPEAKER_01]: It's closed right now.

1555
02:27:19,202 --> 02:27:20,022
[SPEAKER_01]: We have no one in it.

1556
02:27:20,363 --> 02:27:21,703
[SPEAKER_01]: We don't have enough people to staff it.

1557
02:27:22,584 --> 02:27:27,647
[SPEAKER_01]: That's a division that should have at least six patrol officers and two sergeants in it, and it could work.

1558
02:27:28,241 --> 02:27:31,765
[SPEAKER_01]: day and evening, and there's so much more we could do with that.

1559
02:27:32,486 --> 02:27:38,193
[SPEAKER_01]: We bring back motorcycles within that, and we should have a lot of departments.

1560
02:27:38,233 --> 02:27:40,175
[SPEAKER_01]: They used to have what's called CAT teams.

1561
02:27:40,195 --> 02:27:42,358
[SPEAKER_01]: They're called community action teams.

1562
02:27:42,418 --> 02:27:44,821
[SPEAKER_01]: Years ago, we had community police officers in different areas.

1563
02:27:45,842 --> 02:27:50,386
[SPEAKER_01]: because our numbers over the years were dropping, this was a good way to make a team of community officers.

1564
02:27:50,846 --> 02:28:05,237
[SPEAKER_01]: So a CAT team is a community action team where you have officers who will work in various areas of the city where needed, get out there, get them to know the public, and also get them to act on specific problems that arise in those areas.

1565
02:28:05,917 --> 02:28:08,239
[SPEAKER_01]: But those are all goals right now.

1566
02:28:08,860 --> 02:28:09,280
[SPEAKER_05]: For sure.

1567
02:28:09,400 --> 02:28:11,782
[SPEAKER_05]: And the reason I ask is, you know, I personally,

1568
02:28:13,388 --> 02:28:20,291
[SPEAKER_05]: I personally don't think we should have books that say there's 112 people when we know seven of them are funded for a dollar and it's really 105.

1569
02:28:20,791 --> 02:28:26,113
[SPEAKER_05]: Because I think, to your point, right, and we hear it from every department, heard it from FIRE, heard it from you tonight.

1570
02:28:27,254 --> 02:28:30,275
[SPEAKER_05]: Certainly we hear it from some of the smaller departments in the city.

1571
02:28:32,496 --> 02:28:38,738
[SPEAKER_05]: The austerity and the budget cuts that have come to municipal government impact all of our departments.

1572
02:28:41,508 --> 02:28:52,737
[SPEAKER_05]: really the main issue that we're facing right now, whether it's our operating needs and our personnel or our capital needs, is that there is a huge gap between the money we need to spend and the money that we bring in.

1573
02:28:53,177 --> 02:28:59,382
[SPEAKER_05]: We need to have significantly higher expenditures if we want the things that you just said, right?

1574
02:28:59,562 --> 02:29:06,188
[SPEAKER_05]: And to me, and it's a difference of opinion that I've raised earlier in our conversation with the mayor and

1575
02:29:07,310 --> 02:29:14,573
[SPEAKER_05]: and in previous budget meetings, I don't think that we are effectively communicating to the public when we say, oh, no, no, it's 112.

1576
02:29:15,974 --> 02:29:21,056
[SPEAKER_05]: But then you read the asterisk and it's 105 because it's a real issue.

1577
02:29:22,476 --> 02:29:29,919
[SPEAKER_05]: We're facing really significant, you know, we have, you know, we can talk about the budget deficit, the funds deficit.

1578
02:29:29,939 --> 02:29:30,920
[SPEAKER_05]: We have a needs deficit.

1579
02:29:30,980 --> 02:29:36,022
[SPEAKER_05]: There are a bunch of things that we need that are in deficit and we do not have the money to pay for them because,

1580
02:29:36,855 --> 02:29:41,138
[SPEAKER_05]: The cost of providing those services is going up faster than the revenue that the city brings in.

1581
02:29:41,978 --> 02:29:45,100
[SPEAKER_05]: That's basically the whole budget problem in four sentences.

1582
02:29:45,840 --> 02:29:47,301
[SPEAKER_05]: And there's two ways to bring money in.

1583
02:29:47,641 --> 02:29:49,842
[SPEAKER_05]: You can ask the residents if they want to pay more.

1584
02:29:49,862 --> 02:29:59,928
[SPEAKER_05]: And if we say, let's say we put something forward that said we think we need six patrol officers and two sergeants to fully staff a traffic division so we can address the dangerous drivers on our streets.

1585
02:29:59,948 --> 02:30:03,230
[SPEAKER_05]: Because we know the dangerous drivers on our streets are an incredibly big problem.

1586
02:30:03,650 --> 02:30:05,331
[SPEAKER_05]: We get tons of communications about it.

1587
02:30:07,572 --> 02:30:09,292
[SPEAKER_05]: That's having the honest conversation.

1588
02:30:09,312 --> 02:30:09,892
[SPEAKER_05]: We have a need.

1589
02:30:10,133 --> 02:30:12,173
[SPEAKER_05]: This is how much it costs the voters.

1590
02:30:12,253 --> 02:30:12,833
[SPEAKER_05]: Can you do that?

1591
02:30:13,193 --> 02:30:16,234
[SPEAKER_05]: And they can say no, and then we can say that's where we're at.

1592
02:30:17,494 --> 02:30:27,516
[SPEAKER_05]: The other side of it is trying to bring in more of the new growth because the only way that we can raise revenue without increasing the tax burden on the existing taxpayer is to bring in new development.

1593
02:30:28,436 --> 02:30:29,897
[SPEAKER_05]: So those are our options.

1594
02:30:30,957 --> 02:30:36,878
[SPEAKER_05]: You don't make that decision, but I think you illustrated the point well, and I personally

1595
02:30:37,655 --> 02:30:41,698
[SPEAKER_05]: I understand the intent behind saying we'd like to, that's where we want to be.

1596
02:30:41,959 --> 02:30:44,841
[SPEAKER_05]: That's where we think we can do more with 112 than with 105.

1597
02:30:45,341 --> 02:30:49,064
[SPEAKER_05]: But I just have some issues on my own of putting that in a dollar.

1598
02:30:49,425 --> 02:30:50,586
[SPEAKER_05]: It's aspirational for sure.

1599
02:30:50,606 --> 02:30:53,008
[SPEAKER_05]: I just think there's maybe a different way to show that aspiration.

1600
02:30:53,568 --> 02:30:55,490
[SPEAKER_05]: So, thank you.

1601
02:30:55,950 --> 02:30:56,230
[SPEAKER_05]: That's it.

1602
02:30:57,111 --> 02:30:57,732
[SPEAKER_01]: Thank you very much.

1603
02:30:58,212 --> 02:30:58,792
[SPEAKER_05]: Thank you very much.

1604
02:30:59,013 --> 02:30:59,973
[SPEAKER_05]: We do have very quickly.

1605
02:31:02,158 --> 02:31:07,720
[SPEAKER_06]: Traffic supervisors and- One more thing I'd like to add, the training was 400, I misspoke, I said 150.

1606
02:31:08,361 --> 02:31:09,541
[SPEAKER_06]: This is very small.

1607
02:31:12,482 --> 02:31:13,623
[SPEAKER_06]: I was looking going 150.

1608
02:31:14,063 --> 02:31:18,645
[SPEAKER_06]: I'm sitting here going.

1609
02:31:21,306 --> 02:31:26,088
[SPEAKER_05]: Just very quickly, traffic supervisors and traffic commission, if we could go through that.

1610
02:31:26,828 --> 02:31:28,609
[SPEAKER_05]: I'm noticing a relatively small

1611
02:31:29,985 --> 02:31:35,049
[SPEAKER_05]: increase for traffic supervisors, is that a step increase or a contract negotiation?

1612
02:31:35,469 --> 02:31:36,130
[SPEAKER_06]: Two percent raise.

1613
02:31:36,350 --> 02:31:36,950
[SPEAKER_05]: Two percent raise.

1614
02:31:36,990 --> 02:31:37,951
[SPEAKER_06]: They got a two percent raise.

1615
02:31:37,991 --> 02:31:40,993
[SPEAKER_06]: Right now we have 23 permanent, six reservists.

1616
02:31:41,033 --> 02:31:49,480
[SPEAKER_06]: Some of those will be permanent in the off season and we usually fund 25 and then we have extra monies for reservists.

1617
02:31:50,260 --> 02:31:50,721
[SPEAKER_06]: Okay.

1618
02:31:50,801 --> 02:31:57,826
[SPEAKER_06]: To fill in and this year there's a little extra money left in that but there were a lot of police officers covering

1619
02:31:58,767 --> 02:32:01,448
[SPEAKER_06]: traffic supervisor shifts out there.

1620
02:32:02,128 --> 02:32:08,289
[SPEAKER_06]: So that's why it was a little, the spending wasn't as high as it probably could have been.

1621
02:32:08,309 --> 02:32:11,270
[SPEAKER_06]: It probably, we were short.

1622
02:32:11,290 --> 02:32:12,810
[SPEAKER_05]: Was that a lot of people out sick or?

1623
02:32:12,830 --> 02:32:14,431
[SPEAKER_06]: We had a bunch of reservists recently.

1624
02:32:14,771 --> 02:32:15,111
[SPEAKER_06]: Okay.

1625
02:32:15,211 --> 02:32:21,932
[SPEAKER_06]: So we were short and out of those 23 permanent that we have, one is out on an injury unrelated to this job.

1626
02:32:21,952 --> 02:32:22,613
[SPEAKER_06]: Yeah.

1627
02:32:22,853 --> 02:32:24,393
[SPEAKER_06]: So there were a lot of police officer coverage.

1628
02:32:25,193 --> 02:32:29,476
[SPEAKER_05]: And just so folks know, this is the morning and afternoon supervisors at our schools.

1629
02:32:29,736 --> 02:32:29,916
[SPEAKER_06]: Yes.

1630
02:32:29,996 --> 02:32:30,237
[SPEAKER_06]: Yes.

1631
02:32:30,317 --> 02:32:30,657
[SPEAKER_05]: Great.

1632
02:32:31,678 --> 02:32:33,979
[SPEAKER_05]: Traffic commission, no change.

1633
02:32:37,281 --> 02:32:39,003
[SPEAKER_06]: Yeah, we usually level fund.

1634
02:32:39,063 --> 02:32:39,303
[SPEAKER_05]: Great.

1635
02:32:39,803 --> 02:32:39,943
[SPEAKER_06]: Yep.

1636
02:32:40,764 --> 02:32:41,044
[SPEAKER_05]: All right.

1637
02:32:41,845 --> 02:32:43,366
[SPEAKER_05]: Do we have any more questions?

1638
02:32:44,687 --> 02:32:48,009
[SPEAKER_05]: Seeing none, I do see Mr. Gilbrey here.

1639
02:32:48,029 --> 02:32:49,230
[SPEAKER_05]: I recognize you.

1640
02:32:50,708 --> 02:32:52,309
[SPEAKER_01]: Can Lieutenant McGilvery say something?

1641
02:32:52,429 --> 02:32:53,590
[SPEAKER_05]: Yeah, I'm recognizing him, yes.

1642
02:32:53,630 --> 02:32:58,454
[SPEAKER_15]: I'm not here as Lieutenant McGilvery, I'm here as the representative for the Supervisors Union.

1643
02:32:58,495 --> 02:32:59,616
[SPEAKER_15]: I was on the bargaining team.

1644
02:33:00,516 --> 02:33:08,103
[SPEAKER_15]: So I understand the sticker shock that you may have when you see the wages increase 17.5%, but for the last three years,

1645
02:33:10,661 --> 02:33:14,063
[SPEAKER_15]: Our salary line item was based on 2022 wages.

1646
02:33:14,703 --> 02:33:21,006
[SPEAKER_15]: That 17.5% represents a three-year pay increase, which was exactly the same as everyone else in the city got.

1647
02:33:21,627 --> 02:33:26,109
[SPEAKER_15]: We went right down the line with the same raise on percentages as everybody else.

1648
02:33:26,629 --> 02:33:34,633
[SPEAKER_15]: There was a little something extra for post and getting the chief's job out of civil service and creating a deputy chief's job.

1649
02:33:35,494 --> 02:33:37,995
[SPEAKER_15]: But our wages are right in line with everyone else in the city.

1650
02:33:38,415 --> 02:33:40,056
[SPEAKER_15]: We didn't get any more than anyone else.

1651
02:33:41,320 --> 02:33:42,001
[SPEAKER_15]: It's that simple.

1652
02:33:44,002 --> 02:33:44,362
[SPEAKER_05]: Thank you.

1653
02:33:47,044 --> 02:33:56,832
[SPEAKER_05]: And, you know, I think one other thing I was going to say back to Vice President Lazaro's point, the part-time union, part-time librarians,

1654
02:33:57,770 --> 02:34:00,711
[SPEAKER_05]: They make about $31 an hour, so similar to.

1655
02:34:02,071 --> 02:34:06,192
[SPEAKER_01]: So it's really an issue with the- Are they actually required to have a master's degree?

1656
02:34:06,412 --> 02:34:06,652
[SPEAKER_05]: Yes.

1657
02:34:06,892 --> 02:34:07,152
[SPEAKER_01]: Really?

1658
02:34:07,472 --> 02:34:07,912
[SPEAKER_01]: Yeah.

1659
02:34:08,012 --> 02:34:09,273
[SPEAKER_05]: And that's the pay?

1660
02:34:09,553 --> 02:34:12,353
[SPEAKER_05]: That's state certification requirements for a librarian.

1661
02:34:14,134 --> 02:34:20,255
[SPEAKER_05]: And it's not easy to get a library sciences master's.

1662
02:34:22,376 --> 02:34:22,976
[SPEAKER_05]: Counselor Malone.

1663
02:34:23,641 --> 02:34:35,469
[SPEAKER_13]: This might be just a question to the chair but when did we, and again apologies if this came up earlier, when did we know that the contracted services like this were going to hit the budget at this level?

1664
02:34:36,089 --> 02:34:42,233
[SPEAKER_13]: Did we know this like last fiscal year or like, I'm just curious about the timeline of that.

1665
02:34:42,273 --> 02:34:46,676
[SPEAKER_15]: We came before the council last November with a negotiated settlement.

1666
02:34:46,696 --> 02:34:47,237
[SPEAKER_15]: She wasn't here.

1667
02:34:47,297 --> 02:34:47,817
[SPEAKER_13]: I wasn't here.

1668
02:34:51,318 --> 02:34:55,160
[SPEAKER_13]: We came in front of the council last November with a negotiated settlement.

1669
02:34:55,180 --> 02:34:56,661
[SPEAKER_13]: We went to the JLMC and

1670
02:35:13,755 --> 02:35:14,976
[SPEAKER_15]: because we reached an impasse.

1671
02:35:14,996 --> 02:35:18,438
[SPEAKER_15]: The JLMC is there because police and firefighters cannot go on strike.

1672
02:35:18,859 --> 02:35:22,161
[SPEAKER_15]: So we need an outside entity to settle our contract disputes.

1673
02:35:22,181 --> 02:35:23,061
[SPEAKER_15]: We reached an impasse.

1674
02:35:23,081 --> 02:35:24,102
[SPEAKER_15]: We went to mediation.

1675
02:35:24,462 --> 02:35:25,843
[SPEAKER_15]: We were heading to arbitration.

1676
02:35:26,344 --> 02:35:27,905
[SPEAKER_15]: We never stopped negotiating.

1677
02:35:28,585 --> 02:35:33,929
[SPEAKER_15]: We were able to sit down with the mayor and we were able to negotiate a settlement.

1678
02:35:34,549 --> 02:35:35,710
[SPEAKER_15]: It came before this council.

1679
02:35:35,750 --> 02:35:37,852
[SPEAKER_15]: This council voted unanimously to fund it.

1680
02:35:39,172 --> 02:35:47,781
[SPEAKER_15]: So I get the fact that when you see that line item, 17.5%, that it looks like, whoa, and we're in a budget, deficit and all that good stuff.

1681
02:35:48,241 --> 02:35:55,408
[SPEAKER_15]: But I also want to remind everybody that we did a $7.5 million override to fund salaries on the school side, so.

1682
02:35:55,808 --> 02:35:58,011
[SPEAKER_13]: And all I just wanted to say, nothing against that.

1683
02:35:58,051 --> 02:36:03,116
[SPEAKER_13]: It was more to the point of, I think, at the beginning when we were having the conversation with the mayor about

1684
02:36:03,907 --> 02:36:13,034
[SPEAKER_13]: planning and how we're looking at revenue and expenses and looking at it more like a one, three, five year type of time span.

1685
02:36:13,494 --> 02:36:16,657
[SPEAKER_13]: That's where I was just curious about when we may have had that.

1686
02:36:16,757 --> 02:36:20,800
[SPEAKER_13]: So as it's obviously, we knew it was coming.

1687
02:36:21,361 --> 02:36:23,662
[SPEAKER_15]: And it should have been in a negotiated salaries account.

1688
02:36:23,822 --> 02:36:29,787
[SPEAKER_05]: Well, so this I want to, I just want to, if we could just keep it, I'd like to keep it from the back and forth.

1689
02:36:29,847 --> 02:36:32,169
[SPEAKER_05]: And I'd ask everyone to let me recognize them before they speak.

1690
02:36:34,052 --> 02:36:45,098
[SPEAKER_05]: Yes, and I think that's part of the issue where we talk about the budgets before we have the budget book in some cases or, you know, I think there are some schedules and charts that would be incredibly useful to provide additional information to us, right?

1691
02:36:45,358 --> 02:36:52,261
[SPEAKER_05]: I, right at the beginning, I think you might have been here, but I asked Chief of Staff Nazarian about that, right?

1692
02:36:52,361 --> 02:36:56,063
[SPEAKER_05]: What was in the negotiated salaries line last year?

1693
02:36:58,690 --> 02:37:09,036
[SPEAKER_05]: And is that mostly shifting here now into the police salaries line because we have this negotiation that's, I think it was four fiscal years if I'm right.

1694
02:37:09,356 --> 02:37:11,577
[SPEAKER_15]: It was three and a half, we were out three and a half years when we started.

1695
02:37:11,597 --> 02:37:12,838
[SPEAKER_05]: Three and a half, yeah.

1696
02:37:13,038 --> 02:37:13,158
[SPEAKER_15]: So.

1697
02:37:13,178 --> 02:37:13,979
[SPEAKER_15]: Just one other point.

1698
02:37:14,519 --> 02:37:14,679
[SPEAKER_05]: Yeah.

1699
02:37:14,919 --> 02:37:16,100
[SPEAKER_15]: 2002, we had 106 patrol offices.

1700
02:37:18,711 --> 02:37:19,992
[SPEAKER_15]: We're down to 78 now.

1701
02:37:20,472 --> 02:37:23,054
[SPEAKER_15]: When Stephanie Burke was mayor, she came up with the number 85.

1702
02:37:23,294 --> 02:37:26,215
[SPEAKER_15]: That was going to be the lowest we were going to go.

1703
02:37:26,736 --> 02:37:30,938
[SPEAKER_15]: We haven't hit that number 85 in probably 15 years.

1704
02:37:31,939 --> 02:37:37,442
[SPEAKER_15]: So our overtime is there because we don't have people to staff shifts.

1705
02:37:37,922 --> 02:37:40,143
[SPEAKER_15]: You need us out there staffing shifts.

1706
02:37:41,424 --> 02:37:41,724
[SPEAKER_15]: Sorry.

1707
02:37:42,024 --> 02:37:42,385
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you.

1708
02:37:42,445 --> 02:37:43,145
[SPEAKER_15]: It's unnecessary.

1709
02:37:43,245 --> 02:37:46,027
[SPEAKER_15]: If you hire more officers, your overtime is going to get cut.

1710
02:37:46,347 --> 02:37:48,008
[SPEAKER_15]: But then you've got to pay the benefits package.

1711
02:37:48,799 --> 02:37:55,643
[SPEAKER_15]: And we've been playing that game for a long time where the city would pay overtime instead of paying benefits.

1712
02:37:56,264 --> 02:38:02,948
[SPEAKER_15]: So, but right now it's just a struggle to get to, you know, a decent staffing level.

1713
02:38:03,989 --> 02:38:04,409
[SPEAKER_03]: Thank you.

1714
02:38:06,150 --> 02:38:06,430
[SPEAKER_03]: You good?

1715
02:38:06,811 --> 02:38:06,951
[SPEAKER_17]: Yeah.

1716
02:38:07,451 --> 02:38:07,751
[SPEAKER_03]: Great.

1717
02:38:08,792 --> 02:38:09,692
[SPEAKER_05]: Vice President Lazaro.

1718
02:38:10,113 --> 02:38:11,093
[SPEAKER_17]: I'm sorry to keep doing this.

1719
02:38:11,534 --> 02:38:13,335
[SPEAKER_17]: I do just want to clarify that.

1720
02:38:15,639 --> 02:38:35,735
[SPEAKER_17]: My main point in referencing this is that the increase here was a known amount and it is the number that keeps being referenced as the reason why we can't do anything else in the whole rest of the city.

1721
02:38:37,016 --> 02:38:42,301
[SPEAKER_17]: We can't have anything else in the whole rest of the city because of this known contractual increase.

1722
02:38:43,832 --> 02:38:47,611
[SPEAKER_17]: that happens to be the exact dollar amount of the deficit.

1723
02:38:49,637 --> 02:38:50,537
[SPEAKER_17]: We could have done an override.

1724
02:38:50,918 --> 02:38:53,859
[SPEAKER_17]: I mean, we could have done an override, maybe, if we had talked about it.

1725
02:38:54,920 --> 02:38:59,442
[SPEAKER_17]: There could have been any number of opportunities for us to raise revenue.

1726
02:38:59,922 --> 02:39:01,203
[SPEAKER_17]: Is there a plan to raise revenue?

1727
02:39:02,063 --> 02:39:08,226
[SPEAKER_17]: I mean, we don't make the budgets on city council, but we have been working very hard to figure out ways to raise revenue.

1728
02:39:09,467 --> 02:39:10,588
[SPEAKER_17]: We've been working on zoning.

1729
02:39:10,628 --> 02:39:16,210
[SPEAKER_17]: We've been talking about opportunities to bring in business to the city.

1730
02:39:18,300 --> 02:39:25,243
[SPEAKER_17]: I personally, like I'm thinking of lots of ways to try to raise revenue for the city and new growth is a way to bring in more money to the city.

1731
02:39:27,824 --> 02:39:28,384
[SPEAKER_17]: That's all.

1732
02:39:29,204 --> 02:39:30,024
[SPEAKER_17]: That's the reason.

1733
02:39:31,165 --> 02:39:33,106
[SPEAKER_17]: And I do appreciate the perspective.

1734
02:39:35,186 --> 02:39:40,788
[SPEAKER_17]: I just want, I want, I'm just repeating myself now, so I'm going to stop.

1735
02:39:42,249 --> 02:39:47,511
[SPEAKER_17]: But I appreciate Mr. Gilbrey's comments.

1736
02:39:48,895 --> 02:39:49,215
[SPEAKER_03]: Thank you.

1737
02:39:49,235 --> 02:39:53,036
[SPEAKER_03]: Do you have any further questions for, yes, Chief of Staff Nazari.

1738
02:39:53,916 --> 02:39:54,817
[SPEAKER_14]: Thank you, President Behrs.

1739
02:39:55,137 --> 02:40:06,580
[SPEAKER_14]: Through you to Councilor Lazaro, just for clarification, the personnel, the permanent employees line for fiscal 20, I feel like this point wasn't, I wasn't able to make this point earlier.

1740
02:40:06,640 --> 02:40:16,183
[SPEAKER_14]: So I want to, for informational purposes, share that pointing out the permanent employees line, which is going up by 1.616 million for the police department,

1741
02:40:16,803 --> 02:40:26,690
[SPEAKER_14]: If we look at the fiscal 26 budget, the city had allocated 1.575 million in contractual agreements.

1742
02:40:27,110 --> 02:40:31,453
[SPEAKER_14]: So this was anticipated, the city was forecasting it, the city was budgeting for it.

1743
02:40:31,674 --> 02:40:31,974
[SPEAKER_14]: Thank you.

1744
02:40:38,398 --> 02:40:38,618
[SPEAKER_05]: All right.

1745
02:40:38,999 --> 02:40:39,859
[SPEAKER_05]: Any further questions?

