2083
03:22:41,817 --> 03:22:56,408
[SPEAKER_00]: And we would not just have to go to free cash, but also just put it in our operating budget so that we can consistently invest in our buildings and grounds, consistently invest in our building repairs for the HVAC systems, for our elevators.

2084
03:22:56,428 --> 03:22:58,870
[SPEAKER_00]: So those are areas that sadly we would have to look at and see.

2085
03:23:00,071 --> 03:23:05,996
[SPEAKER_00]: If you think of it as like a code, you've got your code red, which is our most important things, and you've got your code orange,

2086
03:23:06,430 --> 03:23:08,130
[SPEAKER_00]: your code yellow, and then your code green.

2087
03:23:08,710 --> 03:23:20,832
[SPEAKER_00]: And we would, for facilities purposes, without speaking for our COO, we would look at our code reds and our code oranges, and then have to look at our code yellows and say, hey, I know some of those code yellows you really wanted to get done.

2088
03:23:21,573 --> 03:23:30,334
[SPEAKER_00]: We might have to either come back to the city council later in the next fiscal year for some free cash, or we might look to postpone that to fiscal year 28.

2089
03:23:30,934 --> 03:23:33,275
[SPEAKER_00]: Similar with some of the curriculum, I know that,

2090
03:23:35,875 --> 03:23:44,542
[SPEAKER_00]: Dr. Talbot is doing a fantastic job in reviewing how we are running the district as a whole and reviewing our curriculum.

2091
03:23:44,582 --> 03:23:52,349
[SPEAKER_00]: So I know she's identifying some areas she would love to see more instructional, more hands-on instructional supplies.

2092
03:23:53,089 --> 03:23:54,290
[SPEAKER_00]: to go with the curriculum.

2093
03:23:54,810 --> 03:24:01,735
[SPEAKER_00]: Again, not that we want to postpone that, but that might be something where we wanted to say we wanted to invest $75,000 in our science department.

2094
03:24:02,295 --> 03:24:06,197
[SPEAKER_00]: We might be only able to invest $50,000 where every department may have to take a small hit.

2095
03:24:06,237 --> 03:24:10,480
[SPEAKER_00]: Again, I'm just throwing up numbers based on preliminary conversations we have.

2096
03:24:11,040 --> 03:24:13,022
[SPEAKER_00]: These are never easy conversations to have.

2097
03:24:13,462 --> 03:24:14,382
[SPEAKER_00]: These are conversations

2098
03:24:15,403 --> 03:24:23,908
[SPEAKER_00]: we as a district don't want to have, but we are well aware, you know, we're also not going to disrespect any number.

2099
03:24:24,828 --> 03:24:31,832
[SPEAKER_00]: As we told the mayor beforehand, whatever number we are given, we're going to fit into that number, because at the end of the day, we understand we're a city.

2100
03:24:33,613 --> 03:24:36,756
[SPEAKER_00]: It's not just the school department, there's the police department, there's DPW department.

2101
03:24:36,776 --> 03:24:39,839
[SPEAKER_00]: So we don't want to take resources away from every department.

2102
03:24:39,859 --> 03:24:43,142
[SPEAKER_00]: We also want to make sure that we're doing the best with the funding we have.

2103
03:24:43,462 --> 03:24:50,208
[SPEAKER_00]: And again, any decisions in which we have to back off of, I don't want to say it's on the chopping block, it might just be

2104
03:24:50,628 --> 03:24:53,089
[SPEAKER_00]: hey, maybe not now, we might have to look at fiscal year 28.

2105
03:24:53,629 --> 03:25:01,352
[SPEAKER_00]: But again, every decision we make will always, I can assure you, will always be the furthest from impacting our students in the classroom.

2106
03:25:01,472 --> 03:25:07,635
[SPEAKER_00]: And as the superintendent alluded to, sometimes that means affecting other staff in other areas that are not in the classroom.

2107
03:25:08,816 --> 03:25:16,663
[SPEAKER_00]: You know, and so it's a tough, it's still a tough conversation to have, but we do have, we always have a plan B and a plan C ready.

2108
03:25:16,983 --> 03:25:24,910
[SPEAKER_00]: So those are some of the areas I hope that answered you, your question of like, you know, where we're looking to trim back on and maybe come back in fiscal year 2018.

2109
03:25:25,210 --> 03:25:26,591
[SPEAKER_00]: You might see that again on the same doc.

2110
03:25:26,631 --> 03:25:29,033
[SPEAKER_00]: I'll be honest with you, you're gonna see it again on next year's presentation.

2111
03:25:29,654 --> 03:25:32,176
[SPEAKER_00]: Certain things we didn't get, you're gonna see it right back on there because

2112
03:25:32,676 --> 03:25:42,442
[SPEAKER_00]: We're gonna continue to advocate for it, and we're gonna continue to fight for it, to continue to provide the best public school, I believe, in the state of Massachusetts when it's all said and done.

2113
03:25:42,962 --> 03:25:43,842
[SPEAKER_09]: Yeah, no, thank you.

2114
03:25:43,922 --> 03:25:45,883
[SPEAKER_09]: That very much answers my question.

2115
03:25:45,983 --> 03:25:59,231
[SPEAKER_09]: I think it's helpful for us to get, I think, a really tangible view of what's at stake and how that impacts our kids, our parents, our teachers.

2116
03:25:59,958 --> 03:26:02,180
[SPEAKER_09]: their work experience in the schools as well.

2117
03:26:03,561 --> 03:26:07,163
[SPEAKER_09]: And I think, you know, I think we all have the same goal here, right?

2118
03:26:07,583 --> 03:26:10,285
[SPEAKER_09]: Of making Medford Public Schools the best school in the state.

2119
03:26:10,325 --> 03:26:11,246
[SPEAKER_09]: And to

2120
03:26:13,415 --> 03:26:16,658
[SPEAKER_09]: minimize the effect of any of this on the kids.

2121
03:26:16,698 --> 03:26:19,400
[SPEAKER_09]: And I think it's really apparent that that's the goal here.

2122
03:26:20,581 --> 03:26:24,484
[SPEAKER_09]: I think it's also apparent that no matter what we do, it's gonna have an impact.

2123
03:26:25,785 --> 03:26:33,771
[SPEAKER_09]: And I think that's why our council has, I think, always found it really important to push for the full ask.

2124
03:26:34,872 --> 03:26:37,194
[SPEAKER_09]: And hopefully this year we can push for that again.

2125
03:26:39,514 --> 03:26:59,891
[SPEAKER_12]: I'd also like to take a moment to thank our legislative delegation who was able to secure funding in the state budget supplemental for van for the vocational program and for robotics curriculum at the middle school along with,

2126
03:27:02,513 --> 03:27:04,535
[SPEAKER_12]: equipment to go along with that curriculum.

2127
03:27:04,615 --> 03:27:10,000
[SPEAKER_12]: So that was a little piece in helping us to close our budget gap.

2128
03:27:13,263 --> 03:27:13,483
[SPEAKER_05]: Great.

2129
03:27:13,523 --> 03:27:13,803
[SPEAKER_05]: Thank you.

2130
03:27:13,823 --> 03:27:16,445
[SPEAKER_05]: Do we have any more questions for our team from Memphis Public Schools?

2131
03:27:20,229 --> 03:27:22,711
[SPEAKER_03]: Chief of Staff seems to want to speak.

2132
03:27:27,662 --> 03:27:29,664
[SPEAKER_14]: I get the unpopular job most of the time.

2133
03:27:29,684 --> 03:27:44,118
[SPEAKER_14]: I want to start off by saying that I have a lot of respect for my peers here today and I know that my peers are doing everything that they can for the schools and the children and it's incredibly hard to come up here and

2134
03:27:45,359 --> 03:27:49,462
[SPEAKER_14]: present a different perspective with regard to the base budget.

2135
03:27:51,144 --> 03:27:57,609
[SPEAKER_14]: My peers know the position of the school, of the city on this matter, and so none of this is gonna come to them as a surprise.

2136
03:28:02,092 --> 03:28:12,320
[SPEAKER_14]: The higher figure that's being, I think it's important to start off on, before I dive deep into base budget details, to say that this is fairly complicated.

2137
03:28:16,122 --> 03:28:17,863
[SPEAKER_14]: not something I would expect.

2138
03:28:17,883 --> 03:28:26,027
[SPEAKER_14]: I personally, if I was seated in your positions, to be candid with you, my learning system would not allow me to digest this this evening.

2139
03:28:27,208 --> 03:28:31,150
[SPEAKER_14]: But I'm going to go through this and I'm going to state what I feel needs to be stated.

2140
03:28:33,312 --> 03:28:34,773
[SPEAKER_14]: And I'm happy to answer any questions.

2141
03:28:34,793 --> 03:28:39,697
[SPEAKER_14]: I'm also happy to provide this written down if that's helpful.

2142
03:28:40,338 --> 03:28:46,723
[SPEAKER_14]: I hope, I hope maybe part of it doesn't even matter because I think we're all just headed towards the same direction.

2143
03:28:46,763 --> 03:28:52,689
[SPEAKER_14]: But I, it's important to outline the differences in perspective in terms of the base budget here because

2144
03:28:54,240 --> 03:29:10,573
[SPEAKER_14]: These types of things are going to then, if, if unaddressed by myself, for instance, they are gonna go down the road and be assumed that, for instance, the, the city's finance team on, on the municipal side and the city administration agree that this is a part of the base budget when we don't believe that that's accurate.

2145
03:29:14,417 --> 03:29:21,462
[SPEAKER_14]: The, the higher figure that's being discussed is effectively incorporating the FY 26 general fund appropriation of $85,400,000.

2146
03:29:23,845 --> 03:29:34,743
[SPEAKER_14]: $90,000 and then adding funds that were carried into Fiscal 26 from 25 through the Stabilization Fund, effectively treating those funds as part of the ongoing base.

2147
03:29:36,603 --> 03:29:41,704
[SPEAKER_14]: From our perspective, that approach doesn't align with the original intent or budgeting logic, in my opinion.

2148
03:29:42,985 --> 03:29:45,065
[SPEAKER_14]: As we understand it, the progression is as follows.

2149
03:29:45,125 --> 03:29:47,266
[SPEAKER_14]: The fiscal 25 budget was $76 million.

2150
03:29:48,726 --> 03:29:52,267
[SPEAKER_14]: Question seven was $3 million approved by the voters, this council, of course.

2151
03:29:52,967 --> 03:29:55,708
[SPEAKER_14]: Question eight, $4 million approved by this council and the voters.

2152
03:29:56,428 --> 03:29:58,569
[SPEAKER_14]: The total fiscal 25 appropriation was $83 million.

2153
03:30:00,617 --> 03:30:10,263
[SPEAKER_14]: For fiscal 26, the $83 million total was increased by 3%, inclusive of the $7 million override, resulting in a general fund appropriation of $85,490,000.

2154
03:30:12,964 --> 03:30:22,350
[SPEAKER_14]: Separately, as has been discussed tonight, the $2.185 million from question eight was placed into a stabilization fund with the following planned use schedule.

2155
03:30:23,732 --> 03:30:24,353
[SPEAKER_14]: Fiscal 26, $1.85 million.

2156
03:30:24,393 --> 03:30:24,613
[SPEAKER_14]: Fiscal 27, $750,000.

2157
03:30:24,713 --> 03:30:24,894
[SPEAKER_14]: Fiscal 28, $350,000.

2158
03:30:34,434 --> 03:30:38,977
[SPEAKER_14]: For fiscal 27, applying a 2.76 increase to the fiscal 26 base of $85,490,000 yields $87,850, 887 million, I don't know what I've been saying to be honest with you, I think I'm losing it here.

2159
03:30:38,997 --> 03:30:42,979
[SPEAKER_14]: $87,850,000 consistent with the city's finance director's communication back in February of 2026 to the school department.

2160
03:31:06,472 --> 03:31:08,253
[SPEAKER_14]: Again, we're referring now to Fiscal 27.

2161
03:31:08,694 --> 03:31:13,477
[SPEAKER_14]: The agreed upon use of the Stabilization Fund in Fiscal 27 was $750,000.

2162
03:31:14,457 --> 03:31:20,281
[SPEAKER_14]: Reframing these amounts, and this is probably the key to focus on because that was just a lot of numbers.

2163
03:31:21,082 --> 03:31:32,830
[SPEAKER_14]: Reframing these amounts in a way that incorporates Stabilization Fund into the base effectively suggests that the school would receive not only the $7 million in the override, but also another $2.185 million.

2164
03:31:36,938 --> 03:31:39,181
[SPEAKER_14]: added permanently to the base by Fiscal 28.

2165
03:31:40,202 --> 03:31:44,547
[SPEAKER_14]: That $2.185 million was already part of the original Question No.

2166
03:31:44,807 --> 03:31:55,579
[SPEAKER_14]: 8 funding in Fiscal 25 and was intended to only be phased forward to avoid absorption into free cash, not to permanently increase the baseline budget.

2167
03:31:57,682 --> 03:32:07,048
[SPEAKER_14]: Treating those same dollars as both a temporary bridge across fiscal years and a permanent addition to the base budget results in counting the same funds twice in different ways.

2168
03:32:08,089 --> 03:32:16,275
[SPEAKER_14]: The outcome materially changes the agreed upon financial framework and produces a higher ongoing obligation than was originally contemplated.

2169
03:32:17,295 --> 03:32:22,299
[SPEAKER_14]: Another way to frame the concern is to say that the voters did not approve a $9.185 million override.

2170
03:32:25,798 --> 03:32:35,602
[SPEAKER_14]: Another, yet another way to say it is by looking at the overall trajectory, the FY24 school general fund budget was $71 million roughly.

2171
03:32:35,622 --> 03:32:37,003
[SPEAKER_14]: It was just over $71 million.

2172
03:32:37,823 --> 03:32:43,926
[SPEAKER_14]: And the current interpretation points towards a FY27 requirement on the order of $90 million.

2173
03:32:45,467 --> 03:32:52,470
[SPEAKER_14]: That scale increase over a short period further underscores the extent to which this approach departs from the original financial plan.

2174
03:32:54,891 --> 03:33:03,117
[SPEAKER_14]: Again, I understand that we're all vying for the same dollars and the schools is just doing that for the best interest of the community and I support that.

2175
03:33:03,398 --> 03:33:04,558
[SPEAKER_14]: I think the mayor supports that.

2176
03:33:04,579 --> 03:33:05,419
[SPEAKER_14]: Everyone supports that.

2177
03:33:05,459 --> 03:33:06,520
[SPEAKER_14]: I know you all support that.

2178
03:33:07,721 --> 03:33:21,071
[SPEAKER_14]: But I just can't not indicate that there is a very real and concerning point with regard to treating the $2.185 million as part of the base budget because it's not.

2179
03:33:21,872 --> 03:33:22,092
[SPEAKER_14]: Thank you.

2180
03:33:27,062 --> 03:33:28,062
[SPEAKER_03]: Thank you.

2181
03:33:30,823 --> 03:33:33,263
[SPEAKER_03]: Is there anything you guys wanna say about that?

2182
03:33:33,363 --> 03:33:37,924
[SPEAKER_12]: Yeah, I think on this point we agree to disagree.

2183
03:33:39,164 --> 03:33:51,266
[SPEAKER_12]: You know, our position is that initially we did receive a 4 million dollars from question 8 in our FY25 budget and we reduced that amount by 2.1.

2184
03:33:52,646 --> 03:33:55,407
[SPEAKER_12]: So we technically we did not get

2185
03:33:56,993 --> 03:34:02,274
[SPEAKER_12]: $4 million added to our budget at the end of the day.

2186
03:34:02,314 --> 03:34:23,320
[SPEAKER_12]: And we did indicate in the FY 26 budget if we go back to those slides and we were having a very similar discussion about a budget gap, we indicated that we would use a million eighty-five to close the gap.

2187
03:34:26,950 --> 03:34:31,891
[SPEAKER_12]: adding that money to our budget in order to help close the gap.

2188
03:34:33,112 --> 03:34:55,238
[SPEAKER_12]: The other thing was if you remember the $3 million in question 7, a large amount of that was given to us in our appropriation kind of pre-funded, you know, without knowing how that,

2189
03:34:57,025 --> 03:35:05,529
[SPEAKER_12]: override would pass, so the city did have a plan to fund that, you know, in the event the override didn't pass.

2190
03:35:05,629 --> 03:35:16,615
[SPEAKER_12]: But when the override did pass, the city was retained, I want to say it was about $1.7 million.

2191
03:35:17,095 --> 03:35:16,615
1.75.

2192
03:35:17,115 --> 03:35:25,880
[SPEAKER_12]: 1.75 to kind of make them whole for the money they had already given us.

2193
03:35:27,467 --> 03:35:34,132
[SPEAKER_12]: The additional 1.2 or so was added to our budget in the supplemental.

2194
03:35:34,732 --> 03:35:47,821
[SPEAKER_12]: So, you know, I think at the end of the day, we, it's still a $2 million budget gap no matter how you slice or dice it.

2195
03:35:49,562 --> 03:35:52,905
[SPEAKER_12]: We do not believe we're spending

2196
03:35:56,173 --> 03:36:05,019
[SPEAKER_12]: 9.8, 9 million, 9.1 million dollars from override amount of 7 million.

2197
03:36:06,459 --> 03:36:15,164
[SPEAKER_12]: That's not something we can agree to but we are using

2198
03:36:16,949 --> 03:36:37,386
[SPEAKER_12]: $2.1 million that we turned back in FY25 in order to spend it over the next three years and that part of the reason of doing that was to manage the impact of kind of unwinding from that stabilization fund.

2199
03:36:37,885 --> 03:36:51,415
[SPEAKER_12]: But the other aspect of it was it follows the three-year contract that we have with the teacher's union and that's, you know, what the money was voted on in order to

2200
03:36:52,885 --> 03:37:00,090
[SPEAKER_12]: meet the requirements of the schedule and improve the salaries of teachers and paraprofessionals, so.

2201
03:37:00,790 --> 03:37:06,594
[SPEAKER_20]: And just if we want the numbers, it did bring back, we cut 14 full-time positions at that time.

2202
03:37:07,134 --> 03:37:12,218
[SPEAKER_20]: And when the override was successful, we were able to reinstate those 14 positions.

2203
03:37:12,238 --> 03:37:15,480
[SPEAKER_05]: All right.

2204
03:37:17,081 --> 03:37:21,544
[SPEAKER_05]: Yeah, I mean, I kind of, not to add a third perspective to the whole situation,

2205
03:37:22,269 --> 03:37:41,553
[SPEAKER_05]: But, you know, my understanding was that these funds were essentially serving as a ramp for the city to have general fund increases greater than 2.75% per year.

2206
03:37:42,074 --> 03:37:48,035
[SPEAKER_05]: Understanding that the schools would need that and these funds were a ramp so that the city budget could sustain that.

2207
03:37:49,083 --> 03:38:00,809
[SPEAKER_05]: And that's why I was considering a part of the base and just reading from the letter where we established the, I mean, I could see it being interpreted differently than I'm interpreting it, but this is June 18th, 2025 from the mayor.

2208
03:38:01,590 --> 03:38:05,652
[SPEAKER_05]: Establish and transfer funds to Medford Public Schools special purpose override stabilization funds.

2209
03:38:05,712 --> 03:38:14,056
[SPEAKER_05]: It concludes, by taking this action, we will have a source of funding available to supplement the Medford Public Schools annual operating budget in the upcoming fiscal year or future fiscal year.

2210
03:38:15,350 --> 03:38:25,561
[SPEAKER_05]: It specifically says annual operating budget which means recurring expenditures not one time expenses and therefore needs to be planned for to be maintained going forward.

2211
03:38:26,382 --> 03:38:31,828
[SPEAKER_05]: So that's like what we voted on the letter to establish the stabilization fund from the mayor.

2212
03:38:34,798 --> 03:38:47,665
[SPEAKER_05]: So I agree with the chief of staff it's not that the overrides 9.1 million but I also agree with you guys that it's to supplement the annual operating budget in the upcoming fiscal year and in future fiscal years which is what the mayor wrote to us when we approved the fund.

2213
03:38:48,165 --> 03:38:49,906
[SPEAKER_05]: So thank you.

2214
03:38:50,006 --> 03:38:50,767
[SPEAKER_05]: Councillor Callahan.

2215
03:38:52,852 --> 03:39:05,480
[SPEAKER_11]: I was just going to say that this is one reason why it's not advised for cities and towns to use free cash or stabilization funds for operating expenses because here we are and nobody knows, right?

2216
03:39:06,040 --> 03:39:14,105
[SPEAKER_11]: Wow, gosh, we used millions of dollars of essentially savings for operating expenses and now we don't know.

2217
03:39:14,385 --> 03:39:15,726
[SPEAKER_11]: We don't know what the voters wanted.

2218
03:39:16,867 --> 03:39:18,308
[SPEAKER_11]: So hopefully we will not be doing that again.

2219
03:39:19,955 --> 03:39:31,277
[SPEAKER_12]: Well, as Chief of Staff said, it was designed to prevent that money from going to free cash and preserve it for what the voters intended with that money.

2220
03:39:34,338 --> 03:39:34,478
[SPEAKER_05]: Right.

2221
03:39:34,558 --> 03:39:45,380
[SPEAKER_05]: And I think if it seemed to me from the letter from the mayor from last year that we were all in agreement that we know that the schools need more than 2.75 percent per year above the

2222
03:39:46,187 --> 03:39:52,172
[SPEAKER_05]: even with the override figure included, and that this was a way to mitigate that ramp up.

2223
03:39:52,632 --> 03:40:00,859
[SPEAKER_05]: You know, the city would have to do a little bit less in fiscal 26, you know, than they otherwise would have a little bit more in 27, a little bit more in 28.

2224
03:40:01,739 --> 03:40:04,201
[SPEAKER_05]: And then in 29, it would be addressed.

2225
03:40:04,301 --> 03:40:11,467
[SPEAKER_05]: But it seems like where we were in agreement in the letter being submitted to us last year, we're not in agreement anymore.

2226
03:40:14,077 --> 03:40:19,340
[SPEAKER_05]: Do we have any further questions for the school leadership team?

2227
03:40:24,442 --> 03:40:25,383
[SPEAKER_03]: All right, thank you.

2228
03:40:25,403 --> 03:40:26,003
[SPEAKER_13]: Thank you.

2229
03:40:26,023 --> 03:40:26,203
[SPEAKER_13]: All right.

2230
03:40:27,904 --> 03:40:28,785
[SPEAKER_05]: Thank you all very much.

2231
03:40:28,965 --> 03:40:30,866
[SPEAKER_05]: DPW, we have Tim McGivern.

2232
03:40:30,906 --> 03:40:33,187
[SPEAKER_05]: We'll do general fund, then we'll do enterprise fund.

2233
03:40:33,587 --> 03:40:39,430
[SPEAKER_05]: And I'll take it in, I think the order that it's in the packet, Tim.

2234
03:40:40,551 --> 03:40:42,112
[SPEAKER_05]: So we can start with highway.

2235
03:40:43,324 --> 03:40:46,548
[SPEAKER_10]: Sure, good evening President Behrs and council members.

2236
03:40:50,934 --> 03:40:53,258
[SPEAKER_10]: I had a late cup of coffee, so I'm good.

2237
03:40:55,788 --> 03:41:01,713
[SPEAKER_10]: But I have just a small presentation to make, just reading off some of the facts from last year.

2238
03:41:02,473 --> 03:41:04,635
[SPEAKER_10]: And then we can dive into questions.

2239
03:41:05,015 --> 03:41:05,296
[SPEAKER_03]: Great.

2240
03:41:05,816 --> 03:41:10,039
[SPEAKER_10]: So as many of you know, DPW is comprised of seven divisions.

2241
03:41:11,260 --> 03:41:17,425
[SPEAKER_10]: And those are engineering, fleet, water and sewer, highway, forestry, parks, and cemetery.

2242
03:41:18,526 --> 03:41:23,090
[SPEAKER_10]: We operate with general fund money as well as water and sewer enterprise and perpetual care funds.

2243
03:41:24,088 --> 03:41:25,869
[SPEAKER_10]: Our budget this year is about $48 million.

2244
03:41:26,109 --> 03:41:29,911
[SPEAKER_10]: A lot of that is water, buying water for the city.

2245
03:41:31,852 --> 03:41:36,494
[SPEAKER_10]: So lots of great stuff happened over the past year or so.

2246
03:41:36,514 --> 03:41:46,278
[SPEAKER_10]: As a lot of you know, and we talked a little bit about earlier, we have an urban forest management plan now that was paid for by the state through an MVP grant.

2247
03:41:47,066 --> 03:41:50,952
[SPEAKER_10]: That included a tree inventory, which is really exciting because we didn't have that before.

2248
03:41:51,012 --> 03:41:54,016
[SPEAKER_10]: So now we have a GIS-based tree inventory, which is wonderful.

2249
03:41:57,016 --> 03:42:06,159
[SPEAKER_10]: And another big thing that we've been working on, that I think most of you know about as well, is transitioning our waste contracts into a more modern waste system.

2250
03:42:07,600 --> 03:42:11,741
[SPEAKER_10]: So that's just some big sort of administrative accomplishments.

2251
03:42:12,181 --> 03:42:14,302
[SPEAKER_10]: The engineering division has been up to a lot.

2252
03:42:14,342 --> 03:42:16,383
[SPEAKER_10]: There's five new staff members in engineering.

2253
03:42:17,883 --> 03:42:20,024
[SPEAKER_10]: Hopefully, you've seen lots of improvements going on.

2254
03:42:20,064 --> 03:42:24,066
[SPEAKER_10]: A big one was the traffic signal improvements at Spring Street and Central, for example.

2255
03:42:25,671 --> 03:42:32,485
[SPEAKER_10]: We basically completed resurfacing of six streets, about 5,650 feet, about 11,000 feet of sidewalk reconstruction.

2256
03:42:38,229 --> 03:42:52,760
[SPEAKER_10]: We did 7,700 feet of water main, 4,600 feet of sewer main, and we are rapidly removing the lead from the service lines, feeding the homes and businesses here in Medford.

2257
03:42:53,280 --> 03:42:54,781
[SPEAKER_10]: We resolved 857 of those, which is a large amount.

2258
03:43:04,848 --> 03:43:13,034
[SPEAKER_10]: Fleet maintenance, we take care of 240 city vehicles, including 27 fire apparatus, 51 police vehicles, and 20 pieces of heavy equipment.

2259
03:43:15,035 --> 03:43:25,802
[SPEAKER_10]: In the water and sewer division, we take care of 15,083 water services, and those come off of 144 miles of distribution pipe.

2260
03:43:26,703 --> 03:43:31,366
[SPEAKER_10]: And one of the big things that we accomplished in water this year is finished a citywide meter swap.

2261
03:43:31,426 --> 03:43:34,068
[SPEAKER_10]: We only have a few left, so that was a very large accomplishment.

2262
03:43:35,205 --> 03:43:41,247
[SPEAKER_10]: And we fixed 66 water service leaks and 67 water main breaks.

2263
03:43:41,968 --> 03:43:44,028
[SPEAKER_10]: I'll talk a little bit more about that in a minute.

2264
03:43:45,509 --> 03:43:52,151
[SPEAKER_10]: Highway, so we maintain 95 miles of public roads and about 29 miles of private roadways.

2265
03:43:52,531 --> 03:43:53,892
[SPEAKER_10]: Private roadways have limited service.

2266
03:43:55,578 --> 03:44:01,603
[SPEAKER_10]: We placed about 780 tons of asphalt this past year, repaired 110 structures.

2267
03:44:02,323 --> 03:44:05,186
[SPEAKER_10]: We painted 375,000 feet of traffic lines.

2268
03:44:06,207 --> 03:44:10,650
[SPEAKER_10]: And we have, it's not new anymore, but we've had paving equipment for the last couple of years.

2269
03:44:10,910 --> 03:44:16,815
[SPEAKER_10]: And last season, we did 11 paving spots, which is much larger than a patch.

2270
03:44:16,875 --> 03:44:18,677
[SPEAKER_10]: We paved a stretch of road, basically.

2271
03:44:18,697 --> 03:44:20,298
[SPEAKER_10]: And that was about 590 tons of asphalt.

2272
03:44:23,159 --> 03:44:33,209
[SPEAKER_10]: The forestry division is something that I looked at over the course of the last year with the urban forest management plan.

2273
03:44:33,229 --> 03:44:40,235
[SPEAKER_10]: It helps me as the manager of the DPW to know what we're up against and what we need to do to service those assets.

2274
03:44:40,696 --> 03:44:42,758
[SPEAKER_10]: So that was really important for the DPW.

2275
03:44:44,078 --> 03:44:46,619
[SPEAKER_10]: The parks division, we have a lot of parks in Medford.

2276
03:44:47,220 --> 03:44:58,946
[SPEAKER_10]: We have 16 major parks, 7 passive parks, and 14 playgrounds, 9 baseball fields, 7 softball fields, 4 soccer fields, 13 basketball courts, 9 tennis courts, and a pickleball court.

2277
03:45:00,026 --> 03:45:08,591
[SPEAKER_10]: And this year we are refinishing or refurbishing, however you'd like to call it, Playstead Park tennis courts, which is a very, very popular set of tennis courts here in the city.

2278
03:45:12,758 --> 03:45:17,020
[SPEAKER_10]: Goals for next year, they kind of build off of goals from last year.

2279
03:45:17,040 --> 03:45:19,782
[SPEAKER_10]: We want to improve our asphalt operations.

2280
03:45:21,143 --> 03:45:25,125
[SPEAKER_10]: We want to have two to three highway division trainings for asphalt knowledge and skills.

2281
03:45:25,825 --> 03:45:27,987
[SPEAKER_10]: We plan on upgrading our milling equipment.

2282
03:45:29,788 --> 03:45:39,554
[SPEAKER_10]: And we are shooting for weekly deployment of our paving equipment this season, which goes through November.

2283
03:45:40,996 --> 03:45:51,162
[SPEAKER_10]: Another goal is to improve our concrete operations, have two to three highway division trainings for concrete knowledge and skills, and weekly deployment of concrete spot repair crew.

2284
03:45:53,263 --> 03:45:57,706
[SPEAKER_10]: Another goal is to establish protocols for tree inventory updates.

2285
03:45:57,846 --> 03:45:58,907
[SPEAKER_10]: We're already working on that.

2286
03:45:58,987 --> 03:46:03,910
[SPEAKER_10]: It's a collaboration between the GIS and engineering division and the forestry division.

2287
03:46:05,209 --> 03:46:11,356
[SPEAKER_10]: The goal is to have an effective GIS-based tree database that can be used effectively for asset management.

2288
03:46:12,357 --> 03:46:17,623
[SPEAKER_10]: Another goal is to have 100% of the lead services removed out of the ground by 2032.

2289
03:46:17,944 --> 03:46:22,669
[SPEAKER_10]: That goal is going to remain until then.

2290
03:46:24,272 --> 03:46:31,194
[SPEAKER_10]: Then we have a lot of capital projects going on at the cemetery, so we have a goal to make some progress on those projects.

2291
03:46:31,594 --> 03:46:34,555
[SPEAKER_10]: We have an expansion design going on.

2292
03:46:35,095 --> 03:46:38,416
[SPEAKER_10]: We have a soil removal project that is almost done.

2293
03:46:38,436 --> 03:46:45,258
[SPEAKER_10]: I'm hoping this is the last year of doing that, and then we'll have just regular operational removals after that.

2294
03:46:45,478 --> 03:46:46,638
[SPEAKER_05]: Piles looking good, Tim.

2295
03:46:47,158 --> 03:46:47,859
[SPEAKER_10]: The piles looking good?

2296
03:46:47,879 --> 03:46:48,039
[SPEAKER_05]: Yeah.

2297
03:46:48,159 --> 03:46:48,940
[SPEAKER_10]: Yeah, it's getting down there.

2298
03:46:49,060 --> 03:46:49,260
[SPEAKER_05]: Yeah.

2299
03:46:49,420 --> 03:46:52,082
[SPEAKER_10]: Yeah, the weeds growing on top, though, look kind of big.

2300
03:46:52,122 --> 03:46:53,163
[SPEAKER_10]: They almost look like trees, so.

2301
03:46:55,204 --> 03:47:03,211
[SPEAKER_10]: Anyway, you know, and the roads up there are horrible, so we have a project there that we're trying to make some progress on, and buildings as well.

2302
03:47:03,251 --> 03:47:05,332
[SPEAKER_10]: We have two buildings that are in rough shape.

2303
03:47:05,713 --> 03:47:14,740
[SPEAKER_10]: We have estimates for preserving those buildings that are quite high, and then I'm actually working on doing a comparison of what a new building might look like in cost.

2304
03:47:16,002 --> 03:47:19,025
[SPEAKER_10]: to compare, so I'd like to make some progress on those.

2305
03:47:20,005 --> 03:47:34,519
[SPEAKER_10]: And then we are continuing to work on asset management transition to field devices, so the goals right now, we have water set up, but really to move on to highway engineering and forestry, especially for the trees as we talked about.

2306
03:47:36,755 --> 03:47:42,918
[SPEAKER_10]: Just to get ahead a couple of questions, you know, some of the concerns that I have with this particular budget is material costs.

2307
03:47:43,018 --> 03:47:43,898
[SPEAKER_10]: Those go up every year.

2308
03:47:44,759 --> 03:47:48,600
[SPEAKER_10]: So, you know, really our DPW budget, even if we do a level budget, it is cut.

2309
03:47:49,341 --> 03:47:53,963
[SPEAKER_10]: Even if it's level across the boards because material costs go up, contract costs go up as well.

2310
03:47:54,543 --> 03:47:58,225
[SPEAKER_10]: Fuel costs is a concern I have this year in particular because it's so variable.

2311
03:47:58,245 --> 03:47:59,886
[SPEAKER_10]: We don't know what's going to happen with fuel right now.

2312
03:47:59,946 --> 03:48:04,928
[SPEAKER_10]: So we kind of did our best and did some shock analysis to see what our budget could handle.

2313
03:48:05,368 --> 03:48:09,910
[SPEAKER_10]: And it should be able to handle reasonable increases in fuel.

2314
03:48:11,211 --> 03:48:20,895
[SPEAKER_10]: And then things that are challenging and are coming is more regulation and more enforcement of those regulations.

2315
03:48:21,135 --> 03:48:22,896
[SPEAKER_10]: We're seeing more ADA activity.

2316
03:48:25,337 --> 03:48:39,447
[SPEAKER_10]: more requests for GIS services, you know, we're seeing a lot of activity from the state and local, the state and federal level for water regulations, keeping our water clean, things like that.

2317
03:48:40,408 --> 03:48:44,331
[SPEAKER_10]: And then also deteriorating assets, which I talk about a lot with this group.

2318
03:48:45,052 --> 03:48:49,855
[SPEAKER_10]: You know, we have an old water system, we have old roads, and they all happen to be failing now.

2319
03:48:50,355 --> 03:48:52,297
[SPEAKER_10]: They're long failures, so, you know,

2320
03:48:52,840 --> 03:49:00,203
[SPEAKER_10]: over the next, for water, probably over the next 20 years, 15 to 20 years, we really should have everything replaced by then.

2321
03:49:00,443 --> 03:49:15,389
[SPEAKER_10]: And then roads as well, we're maintaining a steady condition index, but we're talking with the mayor on what the capital plan should look like to start to tick up on our index, which is great.

2322
03:49:16,669 --> 03:49:20,171
[SPEAKER_10]: And then I'm always trying to right size the department and

2323
03:49:21,973 --> 03:49:29,198
[SPEAKER_10]: I've worked on kind of each division, one division per year, and we just got finished looking at forestry.

2324
03:49:29,838 --> 03:49:39,824
[SPEAKER_10]: You talked a little bit about what a right size of forestry might look like, so we know that information, so we have something to work towards over time, and then I see

2325
03:49:41,345 --> 03:49:46,288
[SPEAKER_10]: Retaining and hiring mechanics is a significant issue coming, too.

2326
03:49:46,828 --> 03:49:51,930
[SPEAKER_10]: The private industry pays mechanics a lot better than here on the public side.

2327
03:49:52,591 --> 03:49:56,353
[SPEAKER_10]: So we've been trying to hire mechanics for going on a year.

2328
03:49:56,713 --> 03:50:04,077
[SPEAKER_10]: And unfortunately, it's not one of those jobs where if we increase the salary, we're going to attract more people, because we just won't be able to compete with $50, $60 an hour out there.

2329
03:50:07,354 --> 03:50:10,445
[SPEAKER_10]: you know, private fleets are giving out.

2330
03:50:17,385 --> 03:50:21,108
[SPEAKER_10]: And then just a little bit about the override and what we're doing there.

2331
03:50:21,409 --> 03:50:28,535
[SPEAKER_10]: So we have three new employees, and I would say now we're at a normal sort of opening level.

2332
03:50:29,135 --> 03:50:34,260
[SPEAKER_10]: We do have a handful of openings, but we've filled the highway rolls.

2333
03:50:34,941 --> 03:50:38,183
[SPEAKER_10]: We bought a new hotbox, so we have two pothole crews now.

2334
03:50:38,824 --> 03:50:41,787
[SPEAKER_10]: Actually, that second hotbox is going to be deployed next week.

2335
03:50:44,226 --> 03:50:47,148
[SPEAKER_10]: And then we're planning on upgrading our milling machine.

2336
03:50:47,548 --> 03:50:51,591
[SPEAKER_10]: And as I talked about, we're deploying our paver more and more.

2337
03:50:51,611 --> 03:50:56,914
[SPEAKER_10]: So we're going to continue to do that to keep our condition index high, or as high as we can.

2338
03:50:58,275 --> 03:51:03,398
[SPEAKER_10]: And then you notice some adds in the budget, some decreases, too, to right-size things.

2339
03:51:03,418 --> 03:51:09,242
[SPEAKER_10]: But we need more software, CitizenServe, other things.

2340
03:51:11,601 --> 03:51:14,382
[SPEAKER_10]: Our fleet, the fleet is getting older.

2341
03:51:14,603 --> 03:51:21,286
[SPEAKER_10]: We're replacing vehicles, but we seem to have a little bit more in fleet costs each year.

2342
03:51:21,446 --> 03:51:22,446
[SPEAKER_10]: So you'll see some of that.

2343
03:51:24,087 --> 03:51:26,628
[SPEAKER_10]: Tree warden is another tick up.

2344
03:51:26,868 --> 03:51:28,869
[SPEAKER_10]: We're paying that position more now.

2345
03:51:29,430 --> 03:51:30,990
[SPEAKER_10]: So I think you saw that the other night.

2346
03:51:33,772 --> 03:51:36,613
[SPEAKER_10]: And solid waste has an uptick as well.

2347
03:51:38,264 --> 03:51:42,487
[SPEAKER_10]: And then water main breaks as well as wholesale water increases.

2348
03:51:42,807 --> 03:51:45,009
[SPEAKER_10]: So those are kind of the big increases that we saw this year.

2349
03:51:46,050 --> 03:51:46,570
[SPEAKER_10]: Thank you very much.

2350
03:51:47,631 --> 03:51:48,091
[SPEAKER_05]: Thank you.

2351
03:51:48,111 --> 03:51:49,012
[SPEAKER_05]: Vice President Lazaro.

2352
03:51:51,374 --> 03:51:52,655
[SPEAKER_17]: Thank you for the presentation.

2353
03:51:53,956 --> 03:52:02,142
[SPEAKER_17]: Could you just help me understand in the parks budget it says food for the inmates and I don't see who pays.

2354
03:52:03,143 --> 03:52:03,704
[SPEAKER_17]: So who.

2355
03:52:04,244 --> 03:52:04,864
[SPEAKER_17]: Can you explain.

2356
03:52:06,146 --> 03:52:06,306
[SPEAKER_10]: Yes.

2357
03:52:07,856 --> 03:52:18,420
[SPEAKER_10]: So we have a partnership with the state correctional facility, and we basically have inmates that will do work on our islands.

2358
03:52:19,421 --> 03:52:21,261
[SPEAKER_10]: Governor's Avenue is a good example.

2359
03:52:21,301 --> 03:52:24,663
[SPEAKER_10]: They trim all the weeds up against the wall a couple times a year.

2360
03:52:25,203 --> 03:52:27,844
[SPEAKER_10]: So the deal is that we provide them lunch.

2361
03:52:28,424 --> 03:52:28,884
[SPEAKER_10]: We feed them.

2362
03:52:29,125 --> 03:52:29,645
[SPEAKER_10]: That's the deal.

2363
03:52:30,845 --> 03:52:31,806
[SPEAKER_10]: And they come in and do some work.

2364
03:52:31,826 --> 03:52:32,806
[SPEAKER_17]: Do you know how much they get paid?

2365
03:52:34,467 --> 03:52:34,907
[SPEAKER_10]: They don't get paid.

2366
03:52:35,898 --> 03:52:36,438
[SPEAKER_10]: that we feed them.

2367
03:52:36,658 --> 03:52:37,159
[SPEAKER_17]: I hate that.

2368
03:52:38,379 --> 03:52:39,880
[SPEAKER_17]: I know it's not anything I can do.

2369
03:52:41,361 --> 03:52:42,442
[SPEAKER_17]: I hate that so much.

2370
03:52:43,202 --> 03:52:47,544
[SPEAKER_10]: It is part of their rehabilitation and their community service.

2371
03:52:48,265 --> 03:52:49,045
[SPEAKER_10]: OK.

2372
03:52:49,345 --> 03:52:50,166
[SPEAKER_17]: It's community service?

2373
03:52:50,546 --> 03:52:52,467
[SPEAKER_10]: I think it counts as community service for them, I believe.

2374
03:52:54,428 --> 03:52:55,949
[SPEAKER_10]: They want to be good standing as prisoners.

2375
03:52:57,170 --> 03:52:59,771
[SPEAKER_10]: We have great success with them.

2376
03:52:59,811 --> 03:53:00,712
[SPEAKER_10]: No, I'm sure they're wonderful.

2377
03:53:00,932 --> 03:53:02,933
[SPEAKER_17]: The thing that I hate is that they're not

2378
03:53:04,198 --> 03:53:12,914
[SPEAKER_17]: being paid money, but if it's for community service, but it says inmates, so I'm confused.

2379
03:53:17,647 --> 03:53:18,147
[SPEAKER_17]: I'm confused.

2380
03:53:18,607 --> 03:53:25,171
[SPEAKER_17]: Also the actuals in the parks budget in general seem really low in a few places.

2381
03:53:25,311 --> 03:53:27,292
[SPEAKER_17]: Is it where they just know it's 527.

2382
03:53:28,232 --> 03:53:28,852
[SPEAKER_17]: It doesn't really matter.

2383
03:53:28,872 --> 03:53:31,734
[SPEAKER_17]: It seems like the actuals are all over the place in a lot of these budgets.

2384
03:53:33,755 --> 03:53:42,119
[SPEAKER_17]: And I did notice that in the highway budget the I think that was just because this year we had an insane amount of snow but it was private contractors was really high.

2385
03:53:42,619 --> 03:53:42,919
[SPEAKER_17]: Is that why.

2386
03:53:44,906 --> 03:53:47,447
[SPEAKER_10]: If it was the snow and ice contract line, then yeah.

2387
03:53:47,607 --> 03:53:48,968
[SPEAKER_17]: It just said private contractors.

2388
03:53:49,028 --> 03:53:49,348
[SPEAKER_17]: Hold on.

2389
03:53:51,168 --> 03:53:53,369
[SPEAKER_17]: There's a lot of papers for your department.

2390
03:53:55,269 --> 03:53:55,489
[SPEAKER_10]: Yes.

2391
03:53:56,910 --> 03:54:06,213
[SPEAKER_17]: Yeah, it was in highway, and it's highlighted, and it says private contractors.

2392
03:54:06,233 --> 03:54:08,233
[SPEAKER_17]: 46,000 is budgeted, $238,212 is in actuals.

2393
03:54:14,320 --> 03:54:17,361
[SPEAKER_17]: And then $46,000 is proposed budget for next year.

2394
03:54:18,701 --> 03:54:20,862
[SPEAKER_17]: Any idea why it would be like that?

2395
03:54:25,143 --> 03:54:26,644
[SPEAKER_09]: There are two lines.

2396
03:54:26,744 --> 03:54:31,645
[SPEAKER_17]: One says private contractors, the other says snow and ice materials, which is also astronomically high.

2397
03:54:32,685 --> 03:54:37,427
[SPEAKER_17]: That whole highlighted section on highway is kind of all over the place.

2398
03:54:38,982 --> 03:54:40,523
[SPEAKER_17]: Does it even out if you add it all up?

2399
03:54:40,603 --> 03:54:42,744
[SPEAKER_10]: It might be snow and ice.

2400
03:54:43,244 --> 03:54:44,705
[SPEAKER_17]: Well, they're probably both snow and ice.

2401
03:54:44,785 --> 03:54:47,167
[SPEAKER_05]: It's line items 423-5241 to 423-5530.

2402
03:54:47,567 --> 03:54:49,588
[SPEAKER_05]: Oh, I see it.

2403
03:54:49,768 --> 03:54:50,368
[SPEAKER_05]: Yeah.

2404
03:54:50,508 --> 03:54:51,089
[SPEAKER_10]: Yeah.

2405
03:54:51,329 --> 03:54:52,990
[SPEAKER_10]: That's snow and ice contractors.

2406
03:54:53,070 --> 03:54:55,471
[SPEAKER_10]: So we have actuals from those two large storms.

2407
03:54:55,671 --> 03:54:55,971
[SPEAKER_17]: Yeah.

2408
03:54:56,192 --> 03:54:59,774
[SPEAKER_17]: And then... It's materials and it's contractors.

2409
03:55:00,234 --> 03:55:04,776
[SPEAKER_10]: Sometimes, last year I think we had, we zeroed out all the snow and ice lines.

2410
03:55:05,277 --> 03:55:06,557
[SPEAKER_10]: This year it doesn't look like we are.

2411
03:55:06,577 --> 03:55:07,698
[SPEAKER_10]: There's some, you know,

2412
03:55:08,185 --> 03:55:09,205
[SPEAKER_10]: nominal amount in there.

2413
03:55:11,986 --> 03:55:12,587
[SPEAKER_17]: Sorry, wait.

2414
03:55:14,067 --> 03:55:15,427
[SPEAKER_17]: How do you mean you zeroed it all out?

2415
03:55:16,268 --> 03:55:19,509
[SPEAKER_10]: So last year when we did the budget, it's been different each year.

2416
03:55:19,549 --> 03:55:24,811
[SPEAKER_10]: The last few years, our proposed budget just would have zero in those lines.

2417
03:55:26,031 --> 03:55:26,271
[SPEAKER_10]: Why?

2418
03:55:26,771 --> 03:55:33,114
[SPEAKER_10]: Because snow and ice can go into deficit, and it's an unforecasted or non-forecasted expense.

2419
03:55:33,594 --> 03:55:34,374
[SPEAKER_17]: That's why it's highlighted.

2420
03:55:35,739 --> 03:55:38,741
[SPEAKER_10]: It's highlighted because I think it was changed, I think.

2421
03:55:38,761 --> 03:55:40,742
[SPEAKER_17]: So now it's not going to be zeroed out?

2422
03:55:40,762 --> 03:55:45,305
[SPEAKER_10]: It's highlighted because it's snow and ice, I think.

2423
03:55:45,685 --> 03:55:47,386
[SPEAKER_10]: The whole section is highlighted as snow and ice.

2424
03:55:47,406 --> 03:55:49,948
[SPEAKER_05]: All of those highlighted items are the snow and ice line items.

2425
03:55:50,148 --> 03:55:50,568
[SPEAKER_17]: OK.

2426
03:55:51,369 --> 03:56:01,335
[SPEAKER_17]: I guess my question here is those actuals don't seem to match the budget for either year.

2427
03:56:04,004 --> 03:56:04,804
[SPEAKER_10]: No, and they won't.

2428
03:56:05,145 --> 03:56:05,825
[SPEAKER_10]: We would expect them not to.

2429
03:56:05,845 --> 03:56:06,245
[SPEAKER_17]: And they won't ever?

2430
03:56:06,785 --> 03:56:09,366
