2432
03:56:19,431 --> 03:56:21,312
[SPEAKER_17]: Yeah, so those are the lines we use.

2433
03:56:21,412 --> 03:56:22,672
[SPEAKER_17]: Just silly little games, OK.

2434
03:56:22,772 --> 03:56:25,994
[SPEAKER_10]: Yeah, and there's no money in those lines until we spend the money.

2435
03:56:26,154 --> 03:56:28,495
[SPEAKER_10]: And I don't know the mechanics behind how that happens.

2436
03:56:29,535 --> 03:56:31,356
[SPEAKER_17]: OK, there's no money in the lines until you spend it.

2437
03:56:31,476 --> 03:56:33,177
[SPEAKER_17]: So it gets put in as needed.

2438
03:56:34,497 --> 03:56:36,619
[SPEAKER_10]: Well, it's an emergency response.

2439
03:56:36,879 --> 03:56:37,159
[SPEAKER_10]: Got it.

2440
03:56:37,720 --> 03:56:40,242
[SPEAKER_10]: So, um, and you know, it looks like maybe she has more to say.

2441
03:56:43,886 --> 03:56:57,555
[SPEAKER_14]: Just to say, thank you for the opportunity, just to say that it's common with cities and towns to kind of keep a level budget with snow and ice because of the unprecedented changes that happen year after year.

2442
03:56:58,096 --> 03:57:04,020
[SPEAKER_14]: It is one of the only budgets that we can spend into deficit under state statutes with the understanding that

2443
03:57:04,720 --> 03:57:08,441
[SPEAKER_14]: You know, we can't predict snow and ice each year.

2444
03:57:08,561 --> 03:57:11,022
[SPEAKER_14]: We can't possibly anticipate that amount.

2445
03:57:11,642 --> 03:57:18,524
[SPEAKER_14]: Also, and I need to check my facts on this, but my recollection is that if we do increase it, we can't decrease it in subsequent years.

2446
03:57:18,604 --> 03:57:24,586
[SPEAKER_14]: So it's a tricky one that cities and towns manage very similar to how we're managing.

2447
03:57:24,706 --> 03:57:29,567
