2621
04:10:07,440 --> 04:10:08,601
[SPEAKER_10]: So anyway, good news.

2622
04:10:08,621 --> 04:10:09,161
[SPEAKER_10]: That's great news.

2623
04:10:09,581 --> 04:10:09,761
[SPEAKER_10]: Mm-hm.

2624
04:10:10,501 --> 04:10:12,821
[SPEAKER_10]: Including the traffic safety things as well.

2625
04:10:12,841 --> 04:10:13,081
[SPEAKER_10]: Awesome.

2626
04:10:13,281 --> 04:10:13,581
[SPEAKER_05]: Thank you.

2627
04:10:13,781 --> 04:10:13,882
[SPEAKER_10]: Mm-hm.

2628
04:10:15,682 --> 04:10:16,522
[SPEAKER_05]: Counselor Callahan.

2629
04:10:18,157 --> 04:10:18,397
[SPEAKER_11]: Thanks.

2630
04:10:18,717 --> 04:10:26,583
[SPEAKER_11]: I just want to say, of all of the budgets that I've seen this year, I feel the most optimistic and hopeful seeing this budget.

2631
04:10:28,064 --> 04:10:44,657
[SPEAKER_11]: You know, I honestly, when I first started running two years ago, two plus, almost three years ago now, I made lead lines one of my top topics, and then people weren't that interested, so I stopped talking about it, but like I never thought I would see the day.

2632
04:10:45,257 --> 04:10:46,778
[SPEAKER_11]: when we would get rid of all the lead lines.

2633
04:10:46,798 --> 04:10:48,279
[SPEAKER_11]: So that's incredibly exciting work.

2634
04:10:49,640 --> 04:11:01,586
[SPEAKER_11]: The fact that we have an urban tree management plan, that we're, we've got a tree inventory and we are really looking to properly fund the forestry department is like incredibly exciting to me.

2635
04:11:03,127 --> 04:11:10,051
[SPEAKER_11]: Even our, I know this is not, did not happen in the last two years, but the fact that we have a composting, you know, citywide is amazing that facilities do that.

2636
04:11:11,152 --> 04:11:12,453
[SPEAKER_11]: I love the fact that,

2637
04:11:13,134 --> 04:11:18,871
[SPEAKER_11]: And I know the in-house repaving crew was partly funded by the override but.

2638
04:11:19,577 --> 04:11:34,326
[SPEAKER_11]: The idea, like having more engineers on board and the idea that we also have this in-house repaving crew, when you mentioned like even maintaining our condition index is great because that's not the trajectory we were on before.

2639
04:11:34,406 --> 04:11:39,609
[SPEAKER_11]: And so if we can get that condition index up, I'm always in favor of a little bit more funding.

2640
04:11:40,169 --> 04:11:44,332
[SPEAKER_11]: And my only question, and I apologize if you mentioned this in your opening statement is,

2641
04:11:45,112 --> 04:11:50,216
[SPEAKER_11]: You know, there's one line item here that is, like, wildly larger than everything else.

2642
04:11:51,517 --> 04:11:57,742
[SPEAKER_11]: The, you know, $9 million budgeted, $7.5 million spent, $10.5 million for next year.

2643
04:11:57,762 --> 04:12:03,646
[SPEAKER_11]: And I just want to double check that that is what I think it is.

2644
04:12:03,966 --> 04:12:10,311
[SPEAKER_11]: This is, like, the contractors we pay to repave our roads and to improve our roads and sidewalks.

2645
04:12:10,371 --> 04:12:11,132
[SPEAKER_11]: Is that accurate?

2646
04:12:11,650 --> 04:12:12,190
[SPEAKER_10]: Not that one.

2647
04:12:12,731 --> 04:12:14,592
[SPEAKER_10]: That's the trash contract.

2648
04:12:14,732 --> 04:12:21,475
[SPEAKER_10]: Yeah, our biggest line and highway is the trash contracts, solid waste contracts.

2649
04:12:22,796 --> 04:12:27,799
[SPEAKER_11]: I'm a little sadder that that's the line item that's going on, but I know we can't do anything about it.

2650
04:12:28,339 --> 04:12:34,745
[SPEAKER_10]: Any line that says materials, so there's materials lines in the highway budget that include asphalt and concrete.

2651
04:12:35,366 --> 04:12:37,247
[SPEAKER_10]: Those went up last year, they didn't go up this year.

2652
04:12:37,848 --> 04:12:44,774
[SPEAKER_10]: They went up last year because of the override and the expectation that we'll have 20% more asphalt being placed.

2653
04:12:45,374 --> 04:12:52,121
[SPEAKER_10]: Which, as the numbers I stated, they're getting up there and we're trying to shoot for more, so.

2654
04:12:53,764 --> 04:12:53,944
[SPEAKER_11]: Great.

2655
04:12:54,024 --> 04:12:55,425
[SPEAKER_11]: Well, I'm still excited.

2656
04:12:55,445 --> 04:13:00,448
[SPEAKER_11]: I'm glad that we are going to be able to keep that road condition index where it is and maybe bump it up.

2657
04:13:00,728 --> 04:13:01,148
[SPEAKER_10]: I hope so.

2658
04:13:01,468 --> 04:13:02,088
[SPEAKER_10]: Fingers crossed.

2659
04:13:02,449 --> 04:13:02,689
[SPEAKER_03]: Thank you.

2660
04:13:03,029 --> 04:13:05,310
[SPEAKER_03]: Yep.

2661
04:13:05,670 --> 04:13:07,411
[SPEAKER_05]: Tim, just a couple quick questions.

2662
04:13:09,853 --> 04:13:14,455
[SPEAKER_05]: Is that line item, the 433-5293, is that just the waste contract?

2663
04:13:15,916 --> 04:13:16,956
[SPEAKER_10]: Let me just double check.

2664
04:13:16,976 --> 04:13:17,537
[SPEAKER_10]: I believe it is.

2665
04:13:23,648 --> 04:13:26,989
[SPEAKER_10]: It's the waste contracts plus waste expenses.

2666
04:13:27,269 --> 04:13:35,890
[SPEAKER_10]: So we pay housing, we pay schools, sorry, not schools, we pay municipal buildings and housing authority.

2667
04:13:37,331 --> 04:13:38,791
[SPEAKER_05]: We pay the housing authority's trash bill?

2668
04:13:39,071 --> 04:13:39,471
[SPEAKER_10]: Yeah.

2669
04:13:39,511 --> 04:13:43,612
[SPEAKER_10]: Previously, they were just included in the general services pickup.

2670
04:13:49,036 --> 04:13:58,368
[SPEAKER_10]: But we changed that because we want to be able to quantify just Medford Housing Authority and see if we can make their collection system more efficient.

2671
04:13:58,428 --> 04:14:01,472
[SPEAKER_10]: If you were to go to one of their properties today,

2672
04:14:02,707 --> 04:14:05,149
[SPEAKER_10]: during a trash pickup day, it's just bins everywhere.

2673
04:14:06,069 --> 04:14:14,915
[SPEAKER_10]: And we're trying to have, well, we haven't started the conversations yet, but we will have conversations with them to see if we can have a more efficient pickup, dumpsters, for example.

2674
04:14:15,436 --> 04:14:16,176
[SPEAKER_10]: So that's what that is.

2675
04:14:16,496 --> 04:14:21,860
[SPEAKER_10]: So we changed it to be a separate bill so we can analyze it separately.

2676
04:14:22,340 --> 04:14:26,863
[SPEAKER_10]: So it's the contracts plus the housing, and same with municipal buildings.

2677
04:14:27,664 --> 04:14:30,166
[SPEAKER_10]: This building, for example, has 12 bins out there.

2678
04:14:30,486 --> 04:14:31,466
[SPEAKER_10]: Is there a better way to do it?

2679
04:14:31,747 --> 04:14:32,147
[SPEAKER_10]: Probably.

2680
04:14:32,958 --> 04:14:34,440
[SPEAKER_05]: Yeah.

2681
04:14:34,981 --> 04:14:49,298
[SPEAKER_05]: Have you guys considered I probably ask you this every year taking the trash contracts and the administration that are in the highway department and just making a separate sub budget in DPW for that.

2682
04:14:53,847 --> 04:14:54,988
[SPEAKER_10]: I don't think you've asked that before.

2683
04:14:55,669 --> 04:14:59,872
[SPEAKER_10]: But I know you do bring up the fact that it kind of muddles the rest of the- It's opaque.

2684
04:14:59,892 --> 04:15:00,873
[SPEAKER_05]: It's very opaque, yeah.

2685
04:15:01,053 --> 04:15:03,115
[SPEAKER_10]: Yeah, it kind of muddles all the rest of the budget.

2686
04:15:03,815 --> 04:15:04,176
[SPEAKER_10]: I agree.

2687
04:15:04,396 --> 04:15:09,560
[SPEAKER_10]: It's something we can think about, I mean, for next year if I remember, and maybe we'll talk about it again and I'll be reminded.

2688
04:15:10,060 --> 04:15:20,349
[SPEAKER_10]: I didn't do it this year, but previous years I had broken it out and almost given a separate highway budget just to see what the number is really for highway, you know, because-

2689
04:15:21,731 --> 04:15:27,781
[SPEAKER_10]: Just for example the highways line is just over 15 million dollars, but ten and a half of that is is waste

2690
04:15:28,787 --> 04:15:28,927
[SPEAKER_10]: Yeah.

2691
04:15:28,987 --> 04:15:29,507
[SPEAKER_10]: For example.

2692
04:15:29,987 --> 04:15:31,488
[SPEAKER_10]: So it does model it.

2693
04:15:31,728 --> 04:15:32,328
[SPEAKER_10]: Same with water.

2694
04:15:32,348 --> 04:15:40,391
[SPEAKER_10]: You know, water is almost a $30 million budget, but $23 million of that is buying water from the MWRA.

2695
04:15:40,651 --> 04:15:40,951
[SPEAKER_10]: Right.

2696
04:15:41,031 --> 04:15:41,311
[SPEAKER_10]: Yeah.

2697
04:15:41,331 --> 04:15:43,171
[SPEAKER_10]: So similar kind of situation.

2698
04:15:43,632 --> 04:15:43,772
[SPEAKER_05]: Yeah.

2699
04:15:44,212 --> 04:15:52,914
[SPEAKER_05]: My only other question in all of the budgets is the, there's also a reduction of one MEO3 in the water and sewer enterprise budget.

2700
04:15:53,335 --> 04:15:54,575
[SPEAKER_05]: Is that also inaccurate?

2701
04:15:58,984 --> 04:16:01,946
[SPEAKER_10]: That may have been a correction that we made.

2702
04:16:02,006 --> 04:16:09,612
[SPEAKER_10]: I think there, if I remember, I'm gonna have to double check this, but if I recall, there was an extra position in water from last year, and that's a correction.

2703
04:16:10,273 --> 04:16:10,673
[SPEAKER_10]: Okay.

2704
04:16:10,773 --> 04:16:10,953
[SPEAKER_10]: Yeah.

2705
04:16:12,214 --> 04:16:16,818
[SPEAKER_05]: It is, okay, that might make sense, actually, given the figures here.

2706
04:16:25,965 --> 04:16:26,145
[SPEAKER_04]: Yeah.

2707
04:16:26,566 --> 04:16:26,746
[SPEAKER_04]: Okay.

2708
04:16:32,308 --> 04:16:35,269
[SPEAKER_05]: appreciate the update on the waste contract.

2709
04:16:35,329 --> 04:16:39,111
[SPEAKER_05]: I think that that's something a lot of residents are reaching out about and wanting to understand.

2710
04:16:39,131 --> 04:16:42,932
[SPEAKER_05]: I think I haven't heard much since the forums in the winter.

2711
04:16:43,853 --> 04:16:47,894
[SPEAKER_05]: So I think people will be, who knows how people will feel.

2712
04:16:48,575 --> 04:16:49,475
[SPEAKER_05]: I won't assume their feelings.

2713
04:16:49,615 --> 04:16:54,277
[SPEAKER_05]: I'm sure people will be interested to know that there is a consideration of changes given the feedback.

2714
04:16:54,675 --> 04:17:01,920
[SPEAKER_10]: Yeah, well, that was one of the points of receiving all that feedback, was to really understand it and digest it.

2715
04:17:01,980 --> 04:17:03,160
[SPEAKER_10]: And that's what we're doing, so.

2716
04:17:03,941 --> 04:17:04,141
[SPEAKER_10]: Great.

2717
04:17:04,501 --> 04:17:05,041
[SPEAKER_10]: Yep, thank you.

2718
04:17:06,122 --> 04:17:08,163
[SPEAKER_05]: I have no further questions from members of the council.

2719
04:17:08,564 --> 04:17:12,146
[SPEAKER_05]: If you want to add anything, Madam Chief of Staff?

2720
04:17:15,336 --> 04:17:19,239
[SPEAKER_14]: I know that this was more of a question by Councilor Lozaro, but I just wanted to tie this back.

2721
04:17:19,359 --> 04:17:33,848
[SPEAKER_14]: I can appreciate the complexity of municipal finance law and municipal budgets and trying to follow it, so I share this in hopes to provide that backdrop.

2722
04:17:35,589 --> 04:17:37,010
[SPEAKER_14]: I found the statute I was looking for.

2723
04:17:37,070 --> 04:17:39,932
[SPEAKER_14]: It's Mass General Law Chapter 44, Section 31D.

2724
04:17:39,972 --> 04:17:45,675
[SPEAKER_14]: It talks about snow and ice removal and emergency expenditures and the reporting requirements under that statute.

2725
04:17:45,735 --> 04:17:56,701
[SPEAKER_14]: It specifically says that the appropriation for such purposes in any said fiscal year must effectively equal or exceed the appropriation for said purposes in the prior fiscal year.

2726
04:17:57,262 --> 04:18:00,764
[SPEAKER_14]: So cities and towns intentionally do not increase this line.

2727
04:18:02,044 --> 04:18:05,886
[SPEAKER_14]: for the purpose of not finding themselves in a situation where they have a surplus.

2728
04:18:06,326 --> 04:18:06,966
[SPEAKER_14]: Thank you very much.

2729
04:18:07,266 --> 04:18:07,627
[SPEAKER_05]: Got it.

2730
04:18:08,107 --> 04:18:10,568
[SPEAKER_05]: Tim, I might have one more question for you, sorry.

2731
04:18:10,588 --> 04:18:16,570
[SPEAKER_05]: No, I guess I don't.

2732
04:18:17,951 --> 04:18:22,052
[SPEAKER_05]: Well, sorry, I'm just looking at an old budget here.

2733
04:18:37,278 --> 04:18:43,819
[SPEAKER_05]: I guess it looks like sometimes we're coming in over budget on the actuals for the waste removal contract.

2734
04:18:43,880 --> 04:18:47,780
[SPEAKER_05]: Is that mostly the expensive side of things ending up being higher than we thought it would be?

2735
04:18:49,521 --> 04:18:52,942
[SPEAKER_10]: There's variables in our waste management contract.

2736
04:18:53,862 --> 04:18:55,602
[SPEAKER_10]: So disposal costs aren't known.

2737
04:18:55,742 --> 04:18:57,803
[SPEAKER_10]: We can just project those.

2738
04:18:57,823 --> 04:18:58,663
[SPEAKER_10]: We forecast those.

2739
04:18:59,703 --> 04:19:00,983
[SPEAKER_10]: Fuel is another one.

2740
04:19:01,584 --> 04:19:03,484
[SPEAKER_10]: And then the recycling market is another one.

2741
04:19:03,991 --> 04:19:12,259
[SPEAKER_10]: So we add a 2% factor of safety onto the waste management contract number because of those things?

2742
04:19:12,900 --> 04:19:13,080
[SPEAKER_05]: Yeah.

2743
04:19:14,922 --> 04:19:15,202
[SPEAKER_05]: Okay.

2744
04:19:16,403 --> 04:19:18,345
[SPEAKER_05]: I have my own spreadsheet running and I just want to make sure.

2745
04:19:19,246 --> 04:19:19,626
[SPEAKER_05]: get it right.

2746
04:19:19,686 --> 04:19:25,148
[SPEAKER_05]: One of the things that I'm breaking out trash just to have a better understanding of that cost driver.

2747
04:19:25,528 --> 04:19:25,768
[SPEAKER_10]: Sure.

2748
04:19:25,808 --> 04:19:25,948
[SPEAKER_10]: Yeah.

2749
04:19:26,008 --> 04:19:35,511
[SPEAKER_10]: And if you want to follow up we have a whole spreadsheet just for that line and just for the waste management contract on how we basically forecast the budget costs.

2750
04:19:36,231 --> 04:19:36,531
[SPEAKER_10]: Great.

2751
04:19:36,971 --> 04:19:37,471
[SPEAKER_05]: That would be great.

2752
04:19:37,712 --> 04:19:37,852
[SPEAKER_05]: Yeah.

2753
04:19:37,872 --> 04:19:38,352
[SPEAKER_05]: We have that.

2754
04:19:38,472 --> 04:19:40,652
[SPEAKER_05]: So if you could share that with the council we'd love to see that.

2755
04:19:40,892 --> 04:19:41,093
[SPEAKER_10]: Sure.

2756
04:19:41,113 --> 04:19:41,353
[SPEAKER_10]: Yeah.

2757
04:19:43,253 --> 04:19:43,593
[SPEAKER_05]: Thank you.

2758
04:19:45,255 --> 04:19:46,996
[SPEAKER_05]: Some of us would love to see it.

2759
04:19:49,499 --> 04:19:49,939
[SPEAKER_10]: I'm joking.

2760
04:19:49,959 --> 04:19:50,259
[SPEAKER_10]: I'm joking.

2761
04:19:50,279 --> 04:19:51,540
[SPEAKER_10]: Yeah, absolutely.

2762
04:19:52,982 --> 04:19:53,722
[SPEAKER_10]: It does break down.

2763
04:19:53,762 --> 04:19:55,744
[SPEAKER_10]: That's a big number, so it does break down that number a little bit.

2764
04:19:55,764 --> 04:19:57,305
[SPEAKER_10]: It's a huge expense.

2765
04:19:58,006 --> 04:19:59,147
[SPEAKER_10]: All right.

2766
04:19:59,447 --> 04:20:00,408
[SPEAKER_05]: Do we have any more questions?

2767
04:20:02,814 --> 04:20:04,214
[SPEAKER_05]: Public works.

2768
04:20:05,295 --> 04:20:06,955
[SPEAKER_05]: Oh one last thing Tim just want to confirm.

2769
04:20:06,975 --> 04:20:12,597
[SPEAKER_05]: Yeah the crew from the sidewalk the crew from the override the paving pothole patching sidewalk crew.

2770
04:20:12,737 --> 04:20:13,998
[SPEAKER_05]: Yeah that exists.

2771
04:20:14,138 --> 04:20:15,658
[SPEAKER_05]: It is hired and it is on the street.

2772
04:20:15,978 --> 04:20:16,278
[SPEAKER_10]: That's right.

2773
04:20:16,458 --> 04:20:20,840
[SPEAKER_05]: And it is allowing you to have people out on doing that work five days a week when the weather allows.

2774
04:20:21,322 --> 04:20:22,203
[SPEAKER_10]: That's yeah that's right.

2775
04:20:22,243 --> 04:20:26,289
[SPEAKER_10]: Whether it's pothole work concrete work or roadway asphalt work.

2776
04:20:26,309 --> 04:20:26,549
[SPEAKER_10]: Yeah.

2777
04:20:27,050 --> 04:20:29,734
[SPEAKER_10]: Not all at the same time and they all don't get out five days a week.

2778
04:20:29,854 --> 04:20:31,056
[SPEAKER_10]: But yes.

2779
04:20:31,456 --> 04:20:34,020
[SPEAKER_05]: And that's up from three days a week before the over.

2780
04:20:35,503 --> 04:20:38,745
[SPEAKER_10]: It's less days a week and more number of crews.

2781
04:20:40,066 --> 04:20:47,651
[SPEAKER_10]: For example, next week when we do potholes, we'll probably do potholes for three or four days next week, depending on the weather.

2782
04:20:48,352 --> 04:20:53,635
[SPEAKER_10]: And instead of sending out one hotbox and one crew, we'll send out two hotboxes and two crews.

2783
04:20:54,696 --> 04:20:55,497
[SPEAKER_05]: For the whole four days.

2784
04:20:56,577 --> 04:20:57,158
[SPEAKER_10]: Right, exactly.

2785
04:20:57,178 --> 04:20:57,678
[SPEAKER_05]: So it's doubling.

2786
04:20:57,758 --> 04:20:59,199
[SPEAKER_10]: I can't commit, I can't say it.

2787
04:20:59,219 --> 04:20:59,500
[SPEAKER_05]: Sure, sure, sure.

2788
04:20:59,520 --> 04:21:00,721
[SPEAKER_10]: I'm not saying, yeah.

2789
04:21:00,741 --> 04:21:16,854
[SPEAKER_10]: But maybe we'll do, depending on availability of staff and what priorities exist, maybe we'll do a day where we have two pothole crews out there, and then another day, one pothole crew and a sidewalk repair crew, which we didn't do that before.

2790
04:21:17,454 --> 04:21:18,395
[SPEAKER_10]: So now we're doing that.

2791
04:21:18,415 --> 04:21:18,655
[SPEAKER_10]: Yeah.

2792
04:21:18,815 --> 04:21:24,000
[SPEAKER_05]: So basically, it's, in theory, if capacity is there, doubled your capacity every day.

2793
04:21:24,661 --> 04:21:26,182
[SPEAKER_10]: Yeah, yeah.

2794
04:21:26,262 --> 04:21:32,626
[SPEAKER_10]: At the end, you know, we're really looking at somewhere in the range of 20 to 25% increase in production, really.

2795
04:21:32,787 --> 04:21:32,987
[SPEAKER_10]: Sure.

2796
04:21:33,167 --> 04:21:33,327
[SPEAKER_10]: Yeah.

2797
04:21:34,067 --> 04:21:34,288
[SPEAKER_04]: Okay.

2798
04:21:35,128 --> 04:21:35,328
[SPEAKER_05]: Great.

2799
04:21:36,549 --> 04:21:36,889
[SPEAKER_05]: Thank you.

2800
04:21:37,850 --> 04:21:39,811
[SPEAKER_05]: You're welcome.

2801
04:21:39,911 --> 04:21:41,112
[SPEAKER_05]: I think that's it for the night.

2802
04:21:41,252 --> 04:21:42,153
[SPEAKER_05]: Do we have a motion?

2803
04:21:43,434 --> 04:21:46,516
[SPEAKER_05]: Keep the paper in committee and adjourn.

2804
04:21:47,591 --> 04:21:49,071
[SPEAKER_05]: Motion to keep the paper in committee and adjourn.

2805
04:21:49,111 --> 04:21:51,172
[SPEAKER_05]: And, Tim, we're just going to trust you to send us that spreadsheet.

2806
04:21:51,212 --> 04:21:52,312
[SPEAKER_05]: So we won't make a motion.

2807
04:21:52,933 --> 04:21:53,213
[SPEAKER_04]: Okay.

2808
04:21:53,273 --> 04:21:53,453
[SPEAKER_04]: Yeah.

2809
04:21:53,553 --> 04:21:53,833
[SPEAKER_04]: Thanks.

2810
04:21:55,433 --> 04:21:55,914
[SPEAKER_05]: Thank you.

2811
04:21:56,694 --> 04:21:56,974
[SPEAKER_05]: All right.

2812
04:21:59,515 --> 04:22:02,776
[SPEAKER_05]: Mr. Clerk, when you're ready, please call the roll on the motion and keep the paper in committee and adjourn.

2813
